text: I have been to this place a couple of times and they have never disappoint me with one of the best zhi char dishes. <br><br>Their specialty is the Mongolian pork rib which is heavenly. The ribs are not cut into small cubes and there are still huge chunks of meat stuck to it. Perhaps it&#39;s not favourable for dainty ladies that will be paiseh to hold up the bones and rip the meat off; I have no qualms for that =D  The ribs has a very unique taste; creamy, peppery and there&#39;s a hint of mint. The sauce is very appetising and I can finish my whole of rice just with the sauce alone. The rib if always cooked till tender but not too soft till it just falls off the bone. <br><br>Another house special will be the signature tofu. If I guess it correctly, it&#39;s normal tofu smashed with other condiments like onions+ carrot + minced meat, then being re-shaped into a cube and deep fried. Sounds like a perfectly simple dish yet tastes awesome. They are served with some fresh cabbage and mayo on the side. <br><br>The rib and tofu is my &#34;must-order&#34; dishes. Other common zhi char dishes are very good too; sambal kangkong, fu rong egg, pai gu wang. <br><br>The next time you are around Bugis but looking for a non-shopping-mall-food-chain-place, you should definitely try 3838. Highly recommended!

text: Decent place if you want an inexpensive cup of coffee with some quick (albeit oily) food to go. The food variety isn&#39;t that different from the myriad Yakun Kaya/ Toastbox establishments that are littered around the island so don&#39;t get your hopes up if you&#39;re really into quality food. <br><br>Situated right at the main entrance of Bukit Panjang Plaza, so it&#39;s pretty impossible to miss.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/IHjfGhAsEdVKnL89FZrNqQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/starbucks-pacific-plaza-singapore?reviewid=c38YyF7pQxUY6UQvonYwZQ&select=IHjfGhAsEdVKnL89FZrNqQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Starbucks Pacific Plaza - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: 1 star solely for the dining in experience, unless you like to share your food with the birds. <br><br>Location wise, the Starbucks outside Pacific Plaza is pretty good for a grab and go. It used (or maybe still is) to be a nice place to chill with friends or a book. But recently the presence of birds (mynahs, pigeons and crows) have really marred the experience. <br><br>When the place is not crowded, you would notice several tables being taken over by the birds. They are there waiting....for the food scraps left by diners. This is a very good reason for Singapore to instill a culture of clearing your own plates. There are dried droppings on the tables and chairs. I&#39;m sure the Starbucks staff do go around cleaning the place, but when you have at least 5 birds fluttering around, you are no match for them. <br><br>To combat the birds problem, Starbucks has installed a sound system and played sounds of birds (probably their predators) every other minute, but the birds seemed immune to the sounds now. Shoo-ing them does not work either. I saw a guy waved something at the bird walking on his table and it took a long while before it flew to the next table. <br><br>The staff also tried to shoo the birds away but they would just hopped or flew over a couple of feet away. All the while, just waiting. <br><br>My experience? There I was, minding my own business, when suddenly a pigeon landed on my table (it was shooed from another table). Sad to say I froze...then hopped up and grabbed my bag. The pigeon calmly settled down on the table and started pecking at my sandwich. The shoo-ing motion of the staff did not perturb the pigeon at all. In the end, the staff actually carried the bird off the table to outside the premise, and there it sat on the sidewalk. Still waiting. I thought it was injured, but it was not as it flew off to yet another table after a while. <br><br>To the Starbucks&#39; staff&#39;s credit, they replaced my sandwich and coffee (which I requested for to go) of their own accord. I think it must have been quite a common occurrence by now. I am not sure if the situation would be better when the place is packed. <br><br>NOTE:<br>So I would really recommend to just do a &#34;grab and go&#34; for your caffeine fix. <br>Food and drinks wise, it is of Starbucks&#39; standards. No complaints. Likewise for the service.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/g1BN7UL2JNbuwzDgHLo8mg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/hattendo-cafe-singapore?reviewid=d2xS4Dcc5NWvDrZQU5s_zQ&select=g1BN7UL2JNbuwzDgHLo8mg', 'altText': 'Photo of Hattendo Cafe - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Surprisely for a Sunday afternoon, the place was pretty crowded. The female manning the cashier was working half heartedly. One could see that she had already to leave as her friends were waiting for her to knock off from work. She kept interrupting the staff in the kitchen, whom one could see having problems keeping an eye on the stove through the open kitchen. One could not help but notice that he had thrown what was on the pan to the bin. For an order of french toast, I had waited almost 30 minutes for it.<br><br>French Toast($9.00)<br>Selected custard bun for the dish, which was pan fried with slightly top and bottom. It was served with pieces of fruit such as lemon, kiwi, blue berries, orange and strawberries, and a scoop of vanilla ice cream by the side. The caramelised crust of the bun gave a different feel to the bun.<br><br>Topup $2.50 for a cup of hot tea to go with it.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/0R3bCc6fkbeOYO_3qukM1Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/gloria-jeans-coffees-singapore-5?reviewid=6TJ9fmWg5Z6x-K7daGrLtw&select=0R3bCc6fkbeOYO_3qukM1Q', 'altText': "Photo of Gloria Jean's Coffees - Singapore, Singapore", 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Being a freelancer, I often head to cafes to get work done over a quiet tea or coffee. I avoid noisy, crowded places at all costs, and Gloria Jean&#39;s at PS is a great place for me to work on weekdays. <br><br>Suspended on between the levels on the 5th floor, you&#39;re in an open space with natural light from the skylight above. I really like the openness, and I find it very conducive for productive work.<br><br>It&#39;s not very quiet as PS always seems to have a hustle and bustle about it at all times, but it&#39;s a cosy spot with lots of comfy chairs and cushions for or to lounge in. <br><br>They play soothing instrumental jazz music, and there are also many power points available for me to plug my laptop into for charging. Service here is fast and efficient, but the coffee from this chain is fairly mediocre.

text: Went with Some colleagues to this place. Inside was no room left, so we sat outside which is nice and hot. <br>We ordered the dish of the day and some other things. After already a few minutes the first dish came. But than it took at least 10minutes for the next few dishes. But still after a long waiting time, 2 of our dishes were not there yet. After having asked for, they told us the dish was not available anymore, so we choose something else and again needed to wait. So very bad service. <br>The food was good, not great and my dish was a bit lacking variety. <br>Not to be repeated for me, but if you want a large size dish which is cheap, than this is the place for the local cuisine.

text: Need a detox from all that hawker center food?<br><br>Little Farms has got you covered. Ingredients are wholesome, nutritious and as much as possible, organic. Brunch is served until 3pm, but lunch goes on until 5pm. I love the colorful salads (from S$18 and up) here on display right in front of you, just pick and choose. <br><br>You&#39;d have to pick a seat, grab the number at your table and then place your order at the counter. I got the vegetable stack (S$24) which had beautifully roasted squash, tomatoes, eggplant, cauliflower, zucchini, olives and topped with a simple EVOO and balsamic glaze plus sprinkling of sea salt. You can really taste the freshness and high quality ingredients they use here. Cookies are not their strong point as the sea salt chocolate cookie I had was dry and hard :( <br><br>I&#39;m not sure if there&#39;s a scarcity of brunch places in the River Valley area, but Little Farms was PACKED even on an off hour of 2pm on a weekday. Also seems to be a favorite among expats and their kids. All I gotta say is, I&#39;m going to be back since HOM Yoga is right next door.

text: Great quality (organic) food, clean interior decor, LOTS of tables, and busy at all times - what&#39;s not to like?<br><br>The prices. C&#39;mon. Charging S$9 for a tiny glass of milk shake or S$25 for a small breakfast plate is outright ridiculous and robbery.<br><br>Apparently I&#39;m the only one thinking so as this place is, as I mentioned, packed at all times.<br><br>Great food, don&#39;t get me wrong, but ridic prices.

text: This is my 4th stop of the day on 17th Jan 2015.<br><br>Was introduced to this place by Melissa Y. It is not too far from the Kembangan MRT and you could probably see the signboard from afar.<br><br>Came here as Mel had purchased 2 Sugar coupons for the waffles and we decided to try the waffles with Hokkaido Milk &amp; Honey and Figs . We also ordered the B.F.F. 4 types of fries and four types of sauces. <br><br>The waffle was over-crispy but the ice creams were delicious. It was melting on the tongue after putting it in your mouth. Didn&#39;t really like the waffle that much as this time round it was over-cooked.<br><br>The B.F.F. was interesting mix of fries. I like the truffle fries as it was crunchy but it doesn&#39;t have much truffle flavor on it. The wedges and the criss-cut fries were al-right (probably cause I&#39;ve been eating too much other stuffs before coming here). I didn&#39;t try the shoestring fries (Curly fries?). The dips I have no clue what they are besides the tartar sauce.<br><br>This place is rather cosy and inviting. On the walls it has writings and interesting quotes. Was not as crowded as I thought it maybe especially on a Saturday evening. Definitely a good place to hang out or even board game sessions :)

text: Located along Changi road is Rice &amp; Fries. From what I understand it has opened for over a year now and I have just learnt about this place via the SUGAR app. It is within walking distance of Kembangan MRT. We managed to easily find a parallel parking street parking spot along Changi Road.<br><br>1. Rack o&#39; Ribs ($22.80)<br>The great BBQ aroma from this dish would make anyone hungry! It was slighly charred to perfection and the meat fell off the bone. For Singapore standards it&#39;s pretty good, still nowhere near what I used to eat daily in the States. For $22.80 it&#39;s not too pricey, although that&#39;s as much as I would ever pay for ribs in Singapore.<br>The meat was juicy and tender. The ribs were well executed with the barbecue sauce over nicely done meat.<br><br>2. Waffles with Ice Cream ($5.80 each)<br>With the SUGAR app, we managed to buy each waffle with ice cream for about $2 each! But nonetheless even at $5.80 It&#39;s still quite reasonable, compared to some cafes that charge like $9 for a whole waffle and ice cream. This is indeed only half a waffle but there&#39;s so much to love about this waffle.<br>The waffle is delightfully crispy! It is not the fluffy kind, some online reviewers have mentioned that it tastes like over-cooked waffles or even &#34;burnt&#34;. But to me, it was nice and crispy and I like it this way. <br><br>The chocolate ice cream was a bit bitter, the green tea ice cream was nice and had the legit green tea taste in there. The salted caramel was the sweet ice cream amongst the 3 flavours. The waffle was slightly salty, some of my friends didn&#39;t like it so salty, but I felt that it was a good compliment for the salted caramel ice cream, since the ice cream was so sweet. <br><br>Waffles and ice cream! Who can resist such a great combination of colours and flavours.<br><br>The food at Rice &amp; Fries may not be super awesome , it&#39;s nevertheless tasty and the ambience is very enjoyable. We were the only customers there on a saturday afternoon at 3pm.

text: Hungry after an errand at Orbea, the bike shop, I decided to give Rice and Fries a try. I wanted something light but couldn&#39;t resist the spicy prawn aglio olio. I enjoyed the huge prawns, the pasta slightly above mediocre. Not overly impressed but would give it another shot if I needed food and AC at 4pm again.
Must try their lamb shank. Very delicious and roasted with long hours. A good place to chill out with friends as well.

text: The wanton noodle is fantastic. It tasted like an authentic HongKong&#39;s style of wanton noodle less the spicy. The noodle texture was chewy and tasted a lot better than others. Best of all, you can have this as little as 3 dollars.

Why I&#39;m only the 2nd reviewer I have no idea. Perhaps everyone already knows about TDC judging by the massive line ups every single bloody day. We come here almost religiously whenever we want a quick healthy warm bite to cover off our protein/veggie/ grain needs. Excellent value especially the ribeye add-on.

text: Good fresh food - among the better salad joints in SG. Friendly staff. They change the menu from time to time, which is a plus. Generally quite healthy options.<br><br>So what could be better?<br>- Staff needs to clean up better, stay on top of things<br>- Prices honestly on the high side - especially for things like drinks<br>- Super unfriendly customer service - if you think they&#39;re interested in your opinion, you&#39;re in for a big surprise. No support at all.

I&#39;ve been hearing about the Daily Cut for a while, but I&#39;m too lazy to run over to the Raffles location for lunch, so when they opened one at the Tanjong Pagar MRT,which is close to my house, I decided to check it out.  You basically pick your protien, sides (veggies) and carb along with a dressing.  There are a lot of these places around Sing, but DC uses really solid quality ingredients.  I liked they ask if you want breast meat for the chicken or thigh.  I GATE dark meat, so this was a bit sell for me.  $12.50 gave me a full chicken breast with broccoli, edamame, brown rice, and mushrooms with a sesame peanut dressing. You can also get a topping (almonds, chia, ect, but I oped for none.  It was exactly what I needed after a killer spin class.  Good price, quality food.

text: A great find in the Joo Chiat area. You&#39;ll note there is a roti prata stall sharing this address with some amazing reviews, and yes, that it correct- this is a Vietnamese restaurant that shares space with Mr and Mrs Moghans Super Crispy Roti Prata. <br><br>So I went after reading some really good reviews on the roti prata. When I arrived I had to order at the stall then told to take a seat in the restaurant. Once seated then someone from the restaurant came to take our drink order. Once the roti prata was ready it was brought out by the stall owners. <br><br>This appeared to be local hangout for many coming for their morning coffee and a chat. I ordered a coffee for myself which was black and served with condensed milk, it was delicious. <br><br>Service is pretty laid back and the roti was quite good (see my other review for that!)<br><br>So really, I&#39;m only rating the coffee, service and ambiance. I&#39;m sure they have their own menu though I didn&#39;t try it, but this place seems worth checking out. It&#39;s always a good sign to me of its busy with locals.

I like this place. The fact that it&#39;s a bit hard to get to means that it&#39;s also a quiet, cosy place that fits in with the ambience of the surrounding neighbourhood. <br><br>They don&#39;t charge for GST and service, which is a plus point.<br><br>My favourite items on the menu are the salmon cream pasta, the all day big breakfast and the sharing platter (their sides are really awesome). The salmon cakes are also worth a shot.<br><br>Service staff are really friendly and as the management is social-media savvy, checking in on Foursquare can unlock you discounts and special offers!

Terribly bad place to visit in East Coast. Ordered a 6pc chicken wings and I got 3 only. They included the mid and joint wings as separate. I find that a tad dishonest but it&#39;s okay. Ordered a half platter &#34;I see seafood&#34; platter and it came with 3 measly pathetic small prawns, insufficient fries, 4 exact calamarai rings and charged $36 for it. <br><br>This place is seriously in bad decor, overpriced and mediocre service. I don&#39;t see any reason to visit here at all. East coast is littered with places with better food and better ambience than this place. Don&#39;t bother coming here.

text: Cosy area in East Coast with carpark around the corner. Dogs can sit at the tables by the road. They do have a dog menu too. Do be careful to leash your pet if they love to run around. Food can be a little pricey ($120 for 2 mains, 3 sides, 1 pitcher of lemongrass drink and 1 dessert). Food is acceptable.

text: The ambience and decor of the place isn&#39;t great, doesn&#39;t have a very welcoming feel nor is it stylish - the concrete walls are painted in terracotta and left plain with wooden tables and chairs being the main decorative item - resulting in the noise bouncing off the walls and echo-ing around the cafe.  <br><br>The food however is pretty decent - the burger and wedges were good, moist and tasty although the burger could have been a slightly bigger portion for its price especially when you compare it to the big breakfast your neighbour is having next to you :P  <br><br>I had the ugly salmon cakes which were pretty good - the mash they used in the cakes were very buttery and tasty, but it could have done with some batter and extra time in the pan - and also some cheese I think.  Although simplicity in cooking is the key, these salmon cakes lacked a little depth in its flavour.  Otherwise no complaints, great portion size, and the salad that came with it was fresh.<br><br>What I found slightly strange was the iced mocha that I ordered - it really wasn&#39;t milky enough, as you could tell instantly from the colour. It didn&#39;t taste bad, just not what an iced mocha is really! There was an overpowering taste of chocolate / cocoa powder - bit too much for my liking.

text: The setting is very casual and relaxing. It was almost like eating at a coffee shop at the old housing estates. The good weather calls for some alfresco dining, Also, i noticed that the seats inside do kinda smell of food but the diners don&#39;t seem to mind. <br><br>The first thing that caught my eye was obviously &#34;All Day Breakfasts&#34;. Breakfast is one of my favorite foods. <br><br>Runny Salmon Scramble-Up ($12.50)- Creamy scrambled eggs topped with lots of smoked salmon, warm toast by side. This was heavenly. The eggs were runny as promised and had a rich creamy texture to it. The salmon provided the slight saltiness that the dish required. Only downside is that the salmon didn&#39;t seem very fresh? Didn&#39;t have a very nice bite to it? Not chewy enough i guess.<br><br>My Juicy Shrimp &amp; Roast Pumpkin ($14.90)- A rich pink sauce of tender baked pumpkin, shrimp and whole oven-roasted garlic cloves. The linguine was more on the cooked side but the plus point is that it makes it really easy to swallow (trust me that&#39;s a good thing). I was basically gobbling mouth after mouth of pasta. The sauce was light and not too sour, perfect base for a pasta marathon. I could go on eating this forever.<br><br>Knickerbooker Glory Sunday ($12.50)- Vanilla gelato with Peach Melba, almond stracciatella, sea-salt dulce de leche &amp; jaffa truffle bar. Was a crazy ass dessert. Every mouthful is a burst of flavors and the mixture was absolutely exhilarating and surprising. Some orange, then chocolate then REAL vanilla ice cream (with vanilla beans!) followed by the taste of sea salt caramel and then hitting the sweet notes with the Peach Melba again. This is a must try.

text: I&#39;ve been to Garden Slug once and would love to go back again, but because of it&#39;s location, its pretty hard to travel there.<br><br>The staffs at Garden Slug are friendly and cheerful, the food there are really not bad and the ambiance of the place gives a casual dining experience. It&#39;s also a pretty good place for gatherings as they do cater to large group settings too. I think it&#39;s best if you called to reserve instead.<br><br>I would recommend their soups and desserts. It not only tastes good, it looks good too! I love how they will spend time and effort in plating their food before serving it to you. <br><br>A good place to try out if you haven&#39;t.

text: The Garden Slug is the sort of place you hear about from friends or people who&#39;ve been there. Reason being its quiet location in the middle of Telok Kurau. <br><br>But once you discover it, you can be sure you&#39;ll keep going back for more. Wait staff and friendly and very efficient, always popping to check if you need something and even when they&#39;re at they&#39;re busiest, your orders come decently quickly. Being a pet friendly joint, you can expect many of our furry friends lazing around while they&#39;re owners enjoy their meal. <br><br>The biggest draw, for me, has to be their decently prized all-day breakfast sets that are huge on portions and good on your belly. The perfect place to nurse your hangover in fact.

It&#39;s not an easy place to get to (especially if you live in the West like me) but I do love going to The Garden Slug. <br><br>It&#39;s a home-y fun place where I can meet up with friends and just chill out (while stuffing our faces, of course). One of my favourites is the Bangers and Mash -there is also the Ultimate Bangers and Mash but I have never had the guts to try it! <br><br>The last time I was there I also had the high tea set of four slices of cake + tea/coffee. It was dessert overload, but I regret nothing.<br><br>They&#39;re also active on Twitter, which means that if you follow @thegardenslug you can be constantly tempted with photos of food and updates on their specials. We once even made reservations for a table via Twitter!

Love this place. Only problem is the food is inconsistent. Once my scrambled eggs looked like mash omelette and the next time it was so runny almost like half boiled eggs. Service is a tad bit slow and the chairs aren&#39;t comfortable. Affordable prices but it seems recently the portions are getting smaller.

text: Located at telok kurau road , this stall is one of the hidden place perhaps only the people staying in the east will know. The shop has an interesting name and logo, and it would be hard to miss the shop.<br><br>This bistro restaurant menu is pretty simple to understand and the deco and interior design are cosy and warm. They provide free wifi and some reading materials for people who wish to laze their afternoon away. <br><br>Food to try is their fish and chip, the fish is tender and juicy, very well prepared, the crust is crunchy giving the extra texture. And do try their signature chocolate popsicle ! It looks just like a popsicle but it is in chocolate flavor. It is even served with an ice cream stick.<br><br>The owner is friendly and the price range is affordable, definitely a great place to chill out with friends  or date with you loved one.

text: After my doctor&#39;s appointment, texted my friend who works at Millenia Tower and asked if she wanted to lunch together. Told her I did not mind to have a light lunch. In the end, I told her to decide whatever she wanted to go. She decided we should lunch at Hoshino Coffee at Suntec. I specifically told her to wait somewhere for me at Millenia Walk which I am familiar, if not I would get lost again. Yep, I was lost again earlier while trying to take the subway (MRT) from Orchard Road to Millenia Walk. However, I was rather pleased with myself for taking a bus from Gleneagles Hospital to Orchard Road area. I don&#39;t even remember when was the last time I took a bus. It was quite fun. <br><br>SERVICE 3/5<br><br>Upon arriving at Hoshino Coffee, we stood at the sign that said &#34;please wait to be seated&#34; at the entrance for a while. Then a staff finally showed up and asked us to place our order first on the notepad. I thought it must be really crowded inside. We waited even longer and finally another staff showed up and led us in. Only then I realized the place has plenty of empty seats :(  Why??<br><br>AMBIENCE 4/5<br><br>I like those little booths, cozy and lots of privacy. Not like we were gossiping like we both girls were during our last high tea session. Oh yeah, we were talking about this odd ball in our class during our high school years. No, we did not bully her, she just wanted to be a loner and we basically left her alone after my effort to rope her into our clique failed. <br><br>FOOD 5/5<br><br>I ordered the lobster bisque spaghetti. I had lobster bisque rather often but not with spaghetti. The combination is new to me. Surprisingly, it turned out to be amazing. I was even thinking of making the same at home. <br><br>Overall, it was a great lunch!! Thank you to CK for buying me lunch today. Next week lunch at Conrad Centennial on me :D

text: Smelly sofa seats!!! Super stinky and wet sofa. Really terrible stench! <br><br>Not my first time at Hoshino Coffee, but this is probably going to be my last. At least for this branch. <br><br>They are known for their drip coffee, matcha and soufflé. They have pretty good pasta too. This is based on past knowledge and past visits.<br><br>Today, we just popped in for a cup of matcha green tea. ($7!) For a Japanese chain, ordering matcha green tea should be a very safe choice. Unfortunately, it was extremely terrible! It tasted like instant green tea, it looks green but taste plain and bitter. It super disappointing. <br><br>The thing that annoyed me most was the horrible smell. It smelled like stinky sweat all over the fabric of the sofa. It was so bad that I had to ask my friends to move to another seat. It stink too but was just so slightly better. I highly suspect it&#39;s the dirty, moist and stinky cloth that they use to wipe across all the surfaces that is causing the stench. <br><br>The only redeeming factor is that the service is good. Good but not enough to redeem itself from the horrible smell and drink.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/t3Rc0W2MQtcOuTpgkYMAzA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/sprout-singapore-2?reviewid=pvlehc1ThXkHiz4fjrRsCg&select=t3Rc0W2MQtcOuTpgkYMAzA', 'altText': 'Photo of Sprout - Singapore, Singapore. Portobello breakfast bagel sandwich :)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Portobello breakfast bagel sandwich :)'}]
text: Come here just for the bathroom, seriously.  This bathroom belongs on the Nicest Bathrooms in Singapore List.  I am not joking, I could have just taken my yummy bagel in the bathroom, and sat there all day.  <br><br>I had seen this place starting to open a few months ago, and noticed that it did about a month ago.  Saturday, on my way home from Cru, I stopped in around noon trying to feed myself after a killer spin class.  The place itself is CUTTTEEE, love the decor, it&#39;s modern without being too trendy, and just a nice little place to grab a coffee or juice and chill.  It&#39;s also bright and warm, and not too squeezed together like some coffee shops in Singapore.  Just a really good zen feel of the place.  I was immediately greeted, and decided to order the one of the bagels.  They serve bagels on the weekend I believe all day. You can make your own including a base, protein (salmon, tuna, chicken breast, sirloin) and toppings galore. I believe they also have salads, and perhaps other things for dinner, not sure.  I had the salmon and avadado bagel, with is served with a side salad.  I also got a iced latte, and a juice.  Both were excellent.  Water is already served on each table, which I appreciated not having to ask for it, and service was both quick and with a smile.   Prices are on point with the area, not cheap, but worth it.  All in all, I will definately be adding it to my rotation of grabbing a quick lunch on the weekends or perhaps breakfast on the weekends.

text: The environment and food is not bad. But the place is so small, there are only 16 seats total. Avoid to be there at lunch time, we waited 40 minutes for the burgers to be served. And when we feedback the slow service, we got the response, I quote &#34;that&#39;s how the food is done here, you&#39;re welcome not to come back again&#34;. Okay, I sure will not visit again.
excellent banana prata. crisp outside. generous portions of sliced sweet banana inside.<br><br>friendly chatty proprietor.

Say the word Ya Kun and Singaporeans will know it rhymes with Kaya toast, Kopi and soft boiled eggs which is our typical Singaporean breakfast set. <br><br>Ya Kun branches are pretty much in every accessible part of Singapore. Though nothing fantastic to rave about, I like the fact that they are everywhere. Kaya toast is fine, kopi is normal but take note that standards for toast can vary at different outlets. So<br><br>My humble opinion is that the best kaya toast or Kopi is still from the traditional or old-school &#34;Kopitiams&#34; that are not franchised but can be inconvenient to go to. <br><br>Oh, I tried the steam bread version here at Funan IT Mall and found it more enjoyable than the toasted version. But it can get pretty messy with the melted butter soaking through the bread so armed yourself with napkins please!

Despite being lunch time, had super quick service.<br><br>I ordered their golden milk tea with pearls with 0% sugar (the way to do it, even the lower sugar options are cloyingly sweet for me here in Singapore). The pearls are smaller than I&#39;m used to, at least from a US comparison, but the texture was great and this sufficed as my weekly (...err 3x a week) boba fix.<br><br>Nothing golden about their tea-- it&#39;s just the color of the pearls themselves. Lots of variety at Koi vs other tea spots, but you&#39;re also paying about $0.50 more.

Honey boba and egg pudding boba', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Honey boba and egg pudding boba'}]
text: Singapore doesn&#39;t really do boba. And Koi Cafe of Lucky Plaza didn&#39;t blow that statement out of the water either.<br><br>The boba/pearls were not chewy at all and a bit on the harder side. My sister had the pearl milk tea while I tried their honey boba. Unfortunately, the honey boba cannot be adjusted by sweetness, so I just asked the cashier lady to use as little sugar/extra sweetness as possible. However, the drink was still very sweet--probably because of the honey.<br><br>Their service was fast, and we saw a few more customers order from Koi after us. But my issue for this average rating is probably because I&#39;ve been spoiled by quality amazing boba from the home of boba in Taiwan, to the streets of Norcal and Socal. It&#39;s probably on the better end of boba places in Singapore, but overall, I don&#39;t think Koi is worth a visit.

text: A friend of mine that studied abroad in Singapore claimed that KOI Cafe had the best boba in Singapore. I wasn&#39;t going to go out of my way to try it, but luckily enough we passed by this location after our lunch so we stopped to try it.<br><br>There were two lines, one to order, and one to pick up. The lines were decently long but also moved quite quickly. One complaint I have was that they didn&#39;t call out the numbers so I stood around for a bit before realizing people were just going up, showing their receipt, and then getting their drinks.<br><br>Keep in mind that I was completely stuffed and wouldn&#39;t have ordered a milk tea if it wasn&#39;t for my friend&#39;s recommendation. I ordered the Golden Milk Tea with 0% sugar (based on Yelp reviews saying it was too sweet), and honestly I wasn&#39;t too impressed. The milk tea was pretty standard and the boba wasn&#39;t anything special other than the fact that the color was a little more &#34;golden.&#34; If I was to order again, I would probably go with a little more sweetness as well.<br><br>I wish I liked this place more than I did, but I would be willing to give it another try (when I&#39;m not so stuffed) if I&#39;m ever in Singapore again.

text: I love the boba milk tea at Koi Cafe! Chewy pearls and refreshing drinks are perfect for the Singapore heat and humidity! <br><br>This is just one of many outlets throughout Singapore! You&#39;ll find one at almost every mall or corner! They have many tea flavors and you can choose the level of sweetness you want! This was my first boba shop stops in Singapore. I really enjoyed my Honey Green Tea with pearls!<br><br>Service is quick and they have an automated system that calls out your number when your drink is ready for pick up!<br><br>Cash only.<br><br>Nearest MRT station: Orchard

text: Loads of food options, the german rosti with salmon is recommended, comes with a sunny side up for $12.50! You can get also get their lunch specials so for $12.50, you get your rosti with a free drink! Milkshakes are included in the lunch deal!<br><br>the wifi is fast and I spent some time there doing my work during off-peak hours. Their mocha is nice and chocolately. I&#39;ve had it about 4 times  now :) The staff are friendly and accomodating.<br><br>Their pastas are about $10nett and reasonably portioned. I feel that the food prices here are geared towards the students in the neighbouring area, so it&#39;s very wallet friendly!

text: I wouldn&#39;t say this is the best Old Town White Coffee in terms of ambiance. It&#39;s situated in the basement level of the mall, there isn&#39;t any privacy, and it can get a bit noisy if there&#39;s a performance going on at OneKM. I wouldn&#39;t come here to do a coffee meeting.<br><br>Still, the food is standard, affordable, and there are even special offers that are only available at this particular OneKM outlet. I just stuck with the $7.90 nasi lemak set, which came with a drink. As this is $3 more than nearby Qi Ji, I still think it&#39;s worth it because they add more ingredients and the portions are slightly bigger.<br><br>As there isn&#39;t an Old Town in the Marine Parade area, this is now my go-to outlet. A-OK!

text: Loved this place. It has a cute, friendly vibe and absolutely delicious vegan desserts. Their ice cream is vegan, made from brown rice! They also do vegan pizzas and other Italian dishes here.<br><br>I came here after dinner so was unfortunately already massively full, but I got myself a little scoop of chocolate hazelnut and it did not disappoint!<br><br>I really just wish I&#39;d had more time in Singapore to come back and try their vegan pizzas and other desserts, all of which looked incredible. <br><br>Everything here is vegan, which is awesome. Staff is super friendly and they let me kick back and read a book at one of their comfy chairs long after I&#39;d finished my ice cream.<br><br>Even if you&#39;re just visiting Singapore as a tourist, if you&#39;re vegan or vegetarian or not able to eat dairy, it&#39;s definitely worth hopping on public transport to reach the Sin Ming Road area just to try this place. You will not be disappointed.

I was pretty excited about this awkwardly-named eatery when I saw their menu. Ended up with the Tempeh Partay (tasty), Suka Suka Jackfruit Bowl (healthy) and a double scoop of ice cream (dark chocolate and peanut butter, delicious!) - all vegan and gluten-free. Service was exceptionally friendly and accommodating. It was noisy with conversation as the small space was full on a Sunday afternoon. <br><br>The heartbreaker for me was when I went to pay and found out they only take cash and NETS! I wish this had been noted on the door or menu - typically when dining at expensive brick-and-mortar places, I assume Visa and Mastercard will be accepted, saving me the trip to an ATM for cash withdrawal. Given that they&#39;re actually producing tasty, healthy vegan food with gluten-free options, I&#39;m still giving it four stars, but for me personally, not accepting credit cards is a dealbreaker. <br><br>The location is a bit off the beaten path. Still, if you have a NETS card or are not cash-averse, Wellsmoocht is worth checking out!

text: Brownice Ice Cream is the first dessert place in Singapore to serve low-calorie, low-GI, low-fat, vegan-friendly and dairy-free ice cream made from organic brown rice. Guilt-free ice cream at it&#39;s best. Even though it&#39;s dairy-free, you should note that the ice cream does not taste icy at all, though it also lacks the creamy taste, Brownice ice cream still holds the smooth textures.<br><br>The 4 scoops of ice cream we picked were :<br>Coconut<br>Hazelnut<br>Matcha<br>Peanut Butter<br>It might sound like alot of flavours, but they all went well together. First off, if this is your first visit to Brownice, definitely go for the coconut! There&#39;s real coconut fruit embedded in the ice cream! It is slightly creamy, with authentic coconut taste and sweetness. It goes really well with the chocolate syrup topping.<br><br>The matcha wasn&#39;t too bitter, and the sweetness level was just right for me. I don&#39;t like matcha ice creams that taste too sweet or artificial. Over here, the matcha was closer to the grainy texture, as unlike the coconut, the matcha wasn&#39;t able to have a smooth aftertaste. Nevertheless, probably the best guilt-free and vegan matcha you can taste in Singapore! <br><br>The peanut butter was too sweet for my liking, but you could taste real peanut butter embedded into the ice cream. Think of chunky monkey from ben and jerrys. Lots of peanuts too, that adds a crunchy bite in every scoop!<br><br>The hazelnut was almost like eating nutella ice cream! It was a tad sweet, and I probably wouldn&#39;t finish a whole scoop by myself, but give me a scoop of coconut or matcha, and it will magically disappear with a spoon in my hand.<br>The waffle here is of a crispy consistency. I would say, this is one of my most favourite waffle places in Singapore. Despite the waffle not having any fragrance or aroma. The light, airy and yet biscuit like edges makes this waffle so addictive.<br>Overall :  A great place to get vegan ice cream, even if you&#39;re not a vegan, or trying to stay on a healthy diet. The ice creams here are great, and so are their waffles. There&#39;s free wifi too! Definitely download the Entertainer App before heading down to Brownice!

text: I am the type of person who orders the meatlovers pizza with extra cheese and I love myself a glass of ice cold milk (don&#39;t even get me started about my milkshake fondness!). Meat and cheese are my favorite things to eat!<br>Needless to say that when someone told me that we were going to a Vegan pizza and ice cream place I was not happy.<br>I mean: pizza without meat and cheese? Ice cream without dairy? Me no likey! It sounded like a guaranteed one star review to me. <br><br>But in the whole spirit of being open to others people opinions and tastes I tagged along, expecting to go to have a nice juicy burger and shake on my way back home. WRONG!!! This place is great and I liked the food a lot.<br><br>Their pizza menu is quite extensive (much more options than the picture posted in a precious review) and since it was the four of us, we tried out 4 different ones and all of them were delicious, no kidding! Honestly, I really enjoyed it and I did not miss meat or cheese at all... Miracles do exist apparently!<br><br>The crust of the pizza is the really thin and crispy and the toppings taste really fresh and unique...I really loved the ones with the monkey head mushrooms and as with regular pizza I especially enjoyed the ones with extra spice on it. In fact, the staff was nice enough to substitute and remove toppings to tailor my own personal pizza.<br><br>I was not hungry anymore after all that pizza goodness but my friends wanted dessert and I by then, I was curious enough to taste the waffle and ice cream. The salted caramel vegan ice cream was delish! So I left Brownice feeling chock full and did not feel the need to eat any meat or anything at all that night.<br><br>Would I return? Yes, with or without my vegan friends who introduced me to this great place.

text: The outlet is located just off the main road of Upper Thomson and is within walking distance from the MRT station. The place is known for its vegan friendly food such as ice cream and pizza. It offers free wifi. <br><br>What attracts me at the counter is the display of ice cream cakes, which I seldom see been sold as slices.<br><br>I order 2 pieces which are been placed on a plate with some decorations on. So cute.<br><br>Coconut-Gula Melaka &#34;Egg&#34; ($5.50/ mini)<br>Coconut and gula melaka ice cream on digestive biscuit base. Delightly refreshing pairing.<br>The ice cream is smooth with bits of the coconut flesh in it. It would be better if the flavour of the gula melaka has been stronger. The biscuit base gives it a slightly salty taste. Unique combination of the sweet and salty.<br><br>Pure Hazelnut Bomb ($5.50/mini)<br>Thick layer of hazenut ice cream on a fruit and nut chocolate base.<br>The ice cream is very smooth and rich which kind of reminds me of peanut butter. Like this very much.<br><br>Overall friendly staff with yummy desserts. There is also plain water and tissue to help yourself to at the side of the counter. Best of all the place is not crowded.

text: I have to give major props to this ice cream shop. Competition for ice cream is fierce in the Upper Thomson area, with 4 or 5 ice cream/waffle shops all within a 5 minutes walk from each other. However, this place stands out so nicely because its 100% vegan, and they don&#39;t use processed/refined sugar, only a small amount unrefined cane sugar in their waffles and cane juice in their ice cream. I asked :) <br><br>Even their waffles are vegan, using no eggs or cows milk, and yet it was still delicious. I had 2 scoops of ice cream and a waffle, and by the end of finishing everything, I wasn&#39;t like super full or bloated, but I was definitely satisfied. Less guilt, and totally satisfied. That&#39;s a pretty good feeling coming out of an ice cream shop. <br><br>The service is also THE NICEST I have come across in Singapore, shocking to say since this is an ice cream shop. All smiles and super sweet. <br><br>They also serve free flow alkaline water with a high ph. I don&#39;t know any other ice cream shop, let alone restaurant that serves free flow alkaline water. Do you?!

text: The only vegan ice cream place in Singapore.<br><br>The most important thing is that it taste delicious! <br><br>I am lactose intolerant so their ice creams do me less harm.<br><br>Now they have expanded into doing food like Pizzas and some cakes.<br>The pizzas taste legit too so you might wanna give it a try. I find the taste pretty good as well. My vegan wife loves it!

The Upper Thomson area has enjoyed popularity for offering  different F&amp;amp;B choices. Ice cream parlours are no strangers here, with Salted Caramel, Udders, NeLi and Scoopz within the shophouses. One of the earliest tenants of the area, Brownice, is located further inwards, within Sin Ming Centre, which specializes in ice cream made from all natural, egg-free and non-dairy products.<br><br>Satisfying my waffle cravings, I ordered the Waffles with Peanut Butter Chocolate ($7.30; $3.80 for waffles, $3.50 for 1 scoop). The waffles is crisp on the outside and moist on the inside. The Peanut Butter Chocolate accompanying it, while trying to strike a balance between both flavours, tasted more chocolatey than the peanut butter taste.<br><br>Anyone can enjoy the ice cream here without feeling guilty due to the nature of the contents. If you are around the Sin Ming / Upper Thomson area, this is one spot that should not be missed.

Vegan food, vegan desserts and now......vegan ice cream. Brownice, a vegan ice cream parlor with a blue avatar, has kicked out a previous gourmet ice cream shop Ice Kimo at Sin Ming Centre. <br><br>No dairy, no eggs, low fat, suitable for lactose-intolerant...These surely sounds like an attractive health contract. But the sweet treat is not necessarily a low-calorific indulgence. After all, unrefined sugar, nuts and brown rice are still used<br><br>Texture-wise, the ice-cream (two scoops for is not as smooth as most ice cream parlours including below320nitro. Luckily, both the Madagascar Vanilla and Cookies &amp; Cream were not too sweet. Not too sure if coconut milk was used but there was an odd coconut aroma which lingers on.<br><br>Don&#39;t mistake, I love coconut but perhaps I&#39;ll save it for other desserts.Constructed of French Chocolate, Hazelnut Chocolate ice cream and a raw crust, the tri-layer mudpie $9.80 refused to budge despite being left in room temperature for 20min. The ice cream flavours were more tolerable than the individual scoops earlier, and lovely contrasted with the salty biscuit base. The original toppings of caramelized salt almonds which ran out of stock, was a sign that they are likely to be tastier than our chocolate chips and granola. <br><br>Due to the ingredients, the price of Brownice&#39;s vegan ice cream is not very nice. But perhaps its a good investment for our health.

On my first trip to Brownice, I was a wee bit skeptical because of its dairy-free, vegan status.  And I was delightedly proven wrong. : )<br><br>Their ice cream is really high-quality - good texture and natural-tasting flavours despite the lack of dairy and eggs.  I especially like the pumpkin-coconut flavour which is especially festive around this time of year.  <br><br>In terms of range of flavours, Brownice is bit limited compared to the huge ice cream parlours because of the inherent restrictions that come when you take out dairy and eggs, but not to worry - they&#39;ve still covered the greatest hits like chocolate, pistachio etc, and thanks to their high quality control it&#39;s really, really yummy.<br><br>The staff there are lovely and willing to share recommendations and generally help customers out too.  <br><br>Definitely worth checking out if you&#39;re in the Upper Thomson area.

At Brownice, you can have your ice-cream without having to worry about counting your calories. Their ice-cream is low in fat and no eggs (not that I personally care, this is just for the vegans and those who are health-conscious)!<br><br>I first heard of the brand when they opened a booth in a bazaar in school. I like bananas, so I got the banana oats then and found that the oats complemented the bananas pretty well. <br><br>When my friends and I chanced upon this store, we got the ice-cream bowl to share. It consisted of four scoops of any ice-cream flavours and four toppings of our choice and only cost $12.50. It wasn&#39;t a bad deal - we sampled more flavours and the toppings gave us good value for money. The crunchy walnuts, plump raisins, tangy cranberries and caramelised almonds added more oomph to our dessert. If you plan to go down in a group, I recommend getting the ice-cream bowl since it&#39;s much cheaper than to buy individual ice-cream scoops.

Where can a vegan get decent dessert in Singapore? Brownice is the much-awaited answer to that question.<br>Serving up absolutely healthy ice-cream made from organic brown rice milk, fruits and nuts, they&#39;re dairy-free and vegan-friendly. Even non-vegans can give their healthy ice-cream range a shot - it honestly tastes just as good as &#34;regular&#34; ice cream.<br>I like their ice-cream because I&#39;m slightly lactose-intolerant so can&#39;t really stomach too milky ice-creams, so this is a good option. Their ice-cream pops (available at their store and vegtarian friendly outlets like Real Food) are my favourite, especially the Hazlenut Chocolate ($5.80).

The most expensive pancakes of my life - was it worth it?  Depends on how much you like pancakes! :-) But seriously, this isn&#39;t like any other pancake you&#39;ll have and while you need to get there early to make sure you have a place (they consistently sell out of the special pancakes and everyone in your party needs to buy at least one item, though they don&#39;t all have to buy pancakes).

text: If you want to try the infamous Japanese fluffy pancakes head to Gram in Vivo City HarbourFront Singapore!!!!! The pancakes are extremely light, fluffy and really jiggly!!!!! They go great with syrup, butter and a lot of cream!!!!!!! They are extremely flavourful as well!!!! Just make sure that you arrive and lineup outside the store at 11:00, 3:00 or 6:00!!!!!! Every person has to order something as well so try out the mango and green tea frappes if you don&#39;t want too many pancakes!!!! The frappés are very refreshing and extremely flavourful!!!! Go try this place out!!!!

I still don&#39;t really know what Kaya is, but it looks like it&#39;s some type of spread. I suppose I could do a quick google search, but I wanna talk about the food so excuse me! <br><br>First of all, Ya Kun Kaya Toast is everywhere in Singapore.  They mainly live in shopping malls or plazas. There&#39;s one near the Merlion Park too. Seems like a cafe type of place to meet up with your friends or colleagues for coffee and toast. Saw lots of groups hanging out here. <br><br>I ordered the French toast which has a springy texture and eggy flavor. Kaya was served on the side. It was so tasty with it. I also ordered the toast and dipped it in the Kaya. This was also very tasty! It&#39;s so simple yet so good! I&#39;d eat this every day as a snack if I could! I&#39;d suggest trying this place at least once. When in Singapore, do as the singaporeans right?

text: Cheap, Fast-Food Breakfast, that you can eat any time of the day.  This chain is everywhere, especially in food courts in basements connected to MRT Stations.  Conveniently located for your quick snack before or after hopping on or off the MRT.  Nice spot for people watching or meeting friends coming from different MRT routes.<br><br>There is a breakfast set for $4.80 that comes with 4 Slices of Buttered and Kaya smeared Toast, 2 Poached Eggs, and a Coffee.  Better than Denny&#39;s!

text: Being in Singapore, we were told that kaya toast was a must-try since it is basically a national breakfast.  With so many ya kun kaya toast chains around the country, it was easy stop by for breakfast even in the early morning.<br><br>Atmosphere: 3/5  The location we went to was located in a food court within a mall.  It was still early but there were definitely some people having breakfast and a few takeaways.  The stall itself was quite small with limited seating - likely intended for a quick meal before people get off to work.  Overall adequate.<br><br>Food: 3.5/5  I had the standard kaya toast breakfast set.  It came with kaya - a coconut jam, and a piece of butter between two toasts, as well as a set of 2 soft boiled eggs and tea.  Toast was good but the butter and jam were a little too rich and sweet for breakfast.  To me, it seemed almost like a dessert.  The soft boiled eggs were tasty w soy sauce and pepper like the Singaporeans eat it.  Overall I enjoyed trying this popular breakfast but not sure that I would be eating it on a daily basis.  There were also other menu options like steamed bread and peanut butter instead of butter that i would love to try.<br><br>Service: 3/5  adequate - order at counter and bring to your own table<br><br>Price: 3/5  Overall reasonable for amount and quality of food<br><br>Overall: 3.5/5  overall I am glad to have tried this popular singaporean breakfast.  The coconut jam is tasty but together with butter, it is a little too much for breakfast.  I also enjoyed the soft boiled eggs - overall an ok experience!

text: Order at the counter and they will serve you the drinks first- food later. Kaya (jam/sauce) is iconic in Singapore and is made from pandan, coconut, and other stuff. Apparently they only have it in Singapore and its great with toast- hence the Kaya Toast. <br><br>Lemon Iced tea- it was sweet but not too sweet (in my opinion) and I really enjoyed it.<br><br>Kaya toast with two slices of butter- I love butter. When it melted, it created the most delicious combination of kaya, butter, and crispy ish toast. Too bad the toast was cold... my friends said that it should not have been.<br><br>Kaya french toast with egg- you&#39;re supposed to dip the toast in the kaya on the side, and we thought this one was okay. Not our favorite and it was not done very well. The french toast was kinda soggy and lukewarm and ehh. We meant to order the soft poached egg but my friend ordered wrong. oh well. <br><br>My friends said that its usually better, and I believe them. The kaya was super good and unique (I&#39;ve never tasted anything like this), hence the four stars. They also mentioned their hong kong (or chinese I forgot) tea is really good, and I would like to try that next time!

text: Simple yet delicious! When I went to Singapore, I knew I had to get some kaya toast as I can&#39;t get this in LA. With the help of the Singaporean yelpers, I found Ya Kun. They have plenty of locations around Singapore, with this one being the closest to my hotel. <br><br>They have several combos to choose from. I ordered the kaya toast, 2 soft boiled eggs, and kopi (coffee) or milk tea. The kaya toast is actually 2 sandwiches (4 toasts). A decent layer of kaya spread on all 4 pieces of bread, with a nice thick slab of cold butter sandwiched in between. The warm toast slowly melts the butter, giving you a sweet and savory bite! <br><br>The soft boiled eggs are served still in the shell. You need to break the shell yourself. I ended up breaking my eggs completely and making a mess as the eggwhite was stuck to the egg shells. Dip your kaya toast into the ooey gooey egg yolk and you get the yolk&#39;s richness with the sweet and savory of the kaya and butter. So delicious! I came for several breakfasts while I was in Singapore! <br><br>They even sell jars of their housemade kaya. Its more expensive than the brands you find at the market, but its super delicious! Remember to bring some back as souvenirs for family and friends!

text: Food: Kaya is a jam made from sugar, egg, coconut, butter, and pandan leaf.  I tried the kaya toast, sugar butter toast, and kaya french toast. We had some &#34;Sets&#34; that come with coffee and soft boiled eggs.  The coffee is very sweet, tastes good.  The soft boiled eggs are amazing (not really, but it&#39;s because in the US there is so much Salmonella we can&#39;t eat eggs unless hey are fully cooked, so this is a rare treat for me!)!   Note the locals will add black pepper to the eggs and dip the toast into the eggs, which we forgot to do.<br>Also note that the sugar butter toast does not come with kaya!  <br><br>Service: they&#39;ll bring you the toast because it takes a bit longer, you can sip on the coffee and eat the eggs (if you bought the set) while you wait<br><br>Ambience: the seating is in the middle of the mall.  Oh god, we saw a RAT running across the pipes above us while we were eating!  Dust and who knows what else could have dropped into my food!  Anyway, nothing did as far as I know..... that&#39;s why it&#39;s 4 stars

text: This is my regular coffee stop every time I&#39;m in SIngapore. Only today did I decide to try the kaya toast to discover how they skimp on the kaya spread. The kaya was a tiny blotch in the middle with the butter and nothing else on the side. <br>I was basically eating dry toast till I got to the middle. Reconsidering coming here from now on.

text: The cafe was newly opened and it was having a 50% off promotion for its 5 dessert items. Open concept place where people walking past can look into the dine in area and kitchen. The place was decorated in wooden and simple style.<br><br>As it was newly opened, the staff who showed me to a table advised that it would take at least 20 minutes for a order to arrive. It was quite a surprise as it was already 9pm and the cafe was less than half filled with a number of uncleared tables around. <br><br>Cloud Nine 九霄云外 (S$14.90++)<br>miso soufflé, yuzu ice cream &amp; vanilla tuile<br>味增舒芙蕾松饼、柚子冰淇淋、香草瓦片饼<br>There was a 20 minutes wait for this item which I was told by the staff when I placed the order. There was no sauce served with souffle, although it was showed with on the menu. The souffle was pretty airy and soft, but one could not taste the miso in it. Being sweet, it was balanced by the slightly sour yuzu sorbet. It was accompanied with the lavender flowers dusted tuile.<br><br>White Ginger Pear 梨白牡丹茶 (S$5.50++)<br>rarest pai mu tan white tea blended with the sweet taste of juicy orchard fresh pear &amp; the tingle of spicy ginger for a delicate &amp; delighting infusion<br>Not sure why but the taste reminded one of ginseng than ginger or pear. It was light and refreshing.

text: I don&#39;t know whether it&#39;s Taiwanese food in general or this place in particular - probably more of the latter - but the food, while ok, is kind of boring and variety is less than at Teochew or certainly Cantonese eateries here. For a café, prices are on the high side (and they don&#39;t serve water, cold or warm, only bottled water). Without the Entertainer 1-for-1 offer, it doesn&#39;t make much sense to eat here!

text: An unexpected surprise. Came here for New Years lunch and was verrrry happy. Started with a pasta that was cooked perfectly. Followed that with two pizzas that were also delicious. Thin crust and crispy base. Finished with a slice of chocolate pie that was amazing. The quality of all the food was outstanding. This is probably the best Italian food at rob quay. Will definitely be coming back.

text: Great food for everyone!<br><br>The staff is friendly and there is a large selection of dishes. There is Internet and it is clean. <br><br>On the negative, there is only one bathroom which lacks cleanliness.

Pros:<br>- Halal<br>- Friendly staff (at Beach Rd)<br><br>Cons:<br>- They don&#39;t serve tap water here, you have to buy bottled water or a drink<br>- Food is bad<br>- Overpriced<br><br>---- FOOD ----<br><br>Korvstroganoff:  2 stars<br>For $14, to get chicken sausages in gravy with rice and a lettuce salad felt like a huge ripoff.<br><br>Swedish Pancakes:  2 stars<br>Ice-cream was bad quality -- texture was styrofoamy not creamy.  Pancakes were hard and stiff.

text: Believe it or not, I was dragged here by my Swedish boyfriend because he saw the word &#34;fika&#34; along with a picture of Moose outside the cafe. Yes, as you might have guessed it, it&#39;s a &#34;Swedish&#34; cafe, right in the Kampong Glam area in Singapore.<br><br>How Swedish can it be? Well the decor inside is very Ikea-ish and they do have a lot of Swedish dishes like meatballs (halal, obviously), pytt i panna and many other dishes that were on the menu. Since we weren&#39;t feeling like eating Swedish dishes in Singapore (hello, laksa!), we came here just to get refreshments and shade from the harsh Singaporean sun.<br><br>Boyfriend ordered (Swedish) coffee while I got myself a lingonberry-ade that was surprisingly fresh and nice (a little bit sour). We shared an earl gray cake, although there was prinsesstårta in the cake shelf.  <br><br>Overall, it&#39;s a nice ambiance, maybe for Singaporeans who want to try out Swedish stuff, or for the Swedes who miss food from home, but as for me, it&#39;s just another concept cafe that is currently trending in Southeast Asia

text: Comfortable setting.  Fantastic mushroom soup that was creamy without being heavy, fresh, and flavorful. Great selection on the smorgasbord with several delicious highlights, particularly the pickled herring (surprised me too!) and the roasted chicken.  The meatballs and every veggie were notable as well.

text: Ordered the crepe mushroom and and herring fish appetiser. The food was exceptionally good. The floor staff were attentive and friendly. The food came fast and the food presentation was superb. Then we had a waffle ice cream. It was the best I have tried in Singapore!  Will certainly visit again!

text: Yuck! Overpriced and not better than Ikea...<br><br>I&#39;m not sure if it&#39;s because I&#39;m not familiar with Ikea food, but the food just isn&#39;t good? It&#39;s not bland, but it&#39;s not necessarily flavorful nor memorable. <br><br>Given that Fika is pricer than the Hangar across the street and other cafes nearby, I don&#39;t recommend this place. Plus, everything is pre-prepared...meaning I couldn&#39;t ask for for &#39;no onion,&#39; &#39;no mayo,&#39; etc.

Dined at both beach road and millenia Walk outlets.<br><br>Beach road- pretty tight space and the salmon was a tad too salty<br><br>Millenia Walk- attentive service probably due to location? I was real hungry and had their meatballs. I guess in Singapore, we are bound to compare Fika and IKEA but it&#39;s a Stark difference.<br><br>Fika&#39;s meatballs are clearly fresh and robust with meat fillings,juicier.

Nice restaurant with good food. The restaurant itself is super clean and has a modern feel to it. There 2 levels. I actually sat outside as they had tables set up on the curb, which was nice. The food was good; I got the steak, which was on point. I did feel it could be a bit more softer and juicier, but still a good steak. Drinks were good as well. I got the Swedish Apple, which hit the spot perfectly on a hot day/night outside. Overall, a pretty good restaurant and great customer service with friendly staff members.

text: Fika is probably the first, and only, Muslim-Swedish cafe around. It&#39;s run by Muslims and located in the Malay heritage Kampong Glam area, so Malay people who&#39;ve always despaired at never being able to eat Swedish meatballs now finally have an avenue to do so!<br><br>The meatballs are decent, though they&#39;re never going to taste the same without pork in them. I also had the roasted chicken crepes when I was there, which was quite a sizeable portion and tasty. <br><br>It&#39;s got quite a nice ambience, level 1 is a little cramped but level 2 is much more spacious and has a fireplace sitting room like area giving it a nice homey ambience.

text: While the ambience and interior of the cafe looked oh-so enticing, my expectations of the food did not quite match up. It didn&#39;t score that well, in my opinion. I didn&#39;t get the impression that we were eating authentic Swedish food, it was just another general Western food cafe to me. <br><br>I was there on a quiet day and my friends and I were quickly ushered to a table. I had the Swedish Pasta Bake (Fusilli pasta, tomatoes, cream sauce and minced beef, topped with melted cheddar cheese). It tasted okay, but I couldn&#39;t find anything fantastic about it. And for the price, they could definitely could have afforded to add more beef! I tried some of my friend&#39;s Swedish meatballs. They were so tough and tiny! The cheesecakes were not bad, but were so expensive at $7.90 to 8.50 a slice. Prices for other items were just as sky high. <br><br>A not so memorable experience. The uniqueness lies in the fact that it&#39;s the only halal Swedish food establishment in the island.

This place is cute and well air conditioned, but super pricey!!<br><br>I had their aloe vera addiction tea for $8.  It was just ok...my boo had their coffee.  Not much else to say except it&#39;s a good place to take a break, since we were dying from the heat and walking around lots :P

text: So we popped by one day for dinner - this place is evidently very popular, and it was by luck that we managed to grab a table. Ordered up, and due to the crowd, the chow took a while to arrive, which is understandable. At least we weren&#39;t of the party that could only hang around and look about forlornly. <br><br>Had a Toast Skagen, which is essentially a smoked salmon and prawn open sandwich, and Tunnbrödsrulle - a generously portioned bread roll containing sausage, mashed potato and shallots. I quite liked the Toast, though my friend found it a little on the fishy side. He rather enjoyed his sausage dish, while I thought it was very Asian inspired with the addition of shallots and chili sauce. To cap dinner off, we had a serve of Swedish pancakes to share. I completely did not like this, as it&#39;s the rubbery textured sort that I&#39;m not fond of. My friend polished it off though, but he also mentioned that the ice cream was not of good quality, which I agree. Service is prompt and crowds are affably managed. Not bad at all.

text: Fika is a swedish cafe &amp; bistro offers a range of open-faced sandwiches (smoked salmon, shrimps, chicken, meatballs..etc), salads And indeed, the food here are really nice and they really satisfy your cravings for meatballs and others. <br><br>Their meatball is really awesome, juicy and bouncy. when you take a bite, the meatball is very tasty. It goes really well with the sauce. The meatballs were well cooked served with softly baked potatoes Though the price of the food are a bit of the high side, but it is worth a try.<br><br>i strongly reccommend this place for meatball lovers!

Good food and very interesting take on Swedish food which is halal. Ambiance is excellent and we had a great time with a big group. The pricing is high but a good option for parties with a mixed group with different food needs !

text: The first time it opened, Fika was quite the exotic swedish food joint in arab st and I&#39;d go there for special occasions with friends. But the pricey food and the unchanging menu has kind of made it lost its appeal. You basically come here when you&#39;re with a group who are craving for halal meatball (stuff of which you can actually make at home, it doesnt require an extensively skillful technique)<br><br>What I like about this place is ambience and service. The floor upstairs feels like a pop-up restaurant decorated with everything from ikea. It even has a fake fireplace to make it cozier. <br><br>I once had to wait a long while for my order because they served me the wrong dish. But what was nice about it was that I was given a bowl of soup on the house (to quell my hunger and also to join in my other friends who have started eating). I thought that was a nice gesture. The soup was also delicious! (or maybe its coz I was really hungry). I&#39;ve tried the baked rice dish - it&#39;s better for sharing because the portion is big and it gets too filling after awhile.<br><br>Final verdict: The meatball dish is the constant favourite, until I learn to make better meatballs in my own kitchen!

The Skagen Crepe $16.50 is a cold crepe that is filled with smoked salmon, shrimp and fish roe. More fillings might be good to hold up what seemed like a deflated roll. It did not have a notable taste and the mayonaise was slightly diluted.<br><br>This Beef Pannbiff $18.90 consists of two huge beef patties, sautéed onions. They were less greasy than Blu Kouzina&#39;s version but the substantial amount of meat became overwhelming. Best recommended for sharing. Taste is rather similar to the meatballs so it&#39;s perhaps better to order either one instead of both.<br><br>The Chokladballs, or Swedish Chocolate Balls ($5.50 for 3) are refrigerator cakes aka no-baked cakes. Made of oatmeal, sugar, coffee, cocoa, butter then rolled in coconut flakes, this has a grainy, rustic texture similar to a compact wholemeal ball.......

Fika does a homemade Swedish meatballs dish that is quite different from those frozen balls we are used to from Ikea. I suppose that&#39;s our first experience of Swedish food typically. These meatballs are huge and of course made with real meat mash. The texture leans to the powdery and starchy side. I thought it&#39;s more like a meat loaf. <br><br>What&#39;s great about this is that the restaurant is certified halal. This definitely tastes better than those halal meatballs at Ikea. If you have Muslim friends and are sick of dining at the usual Halal restaurants, I&#39;d say this is a good option. <br><br>Fika is located in the cultural rich Beach road. Head on over to Haji Lane for some shopping after. :)

Stepping into the cafe on a sunny early afternoon, we were greeted with a spot casually bustling with people. The indoor seating area was adorned with white furnitures, clean lines, the omnipresent blackboard menu and was lit with a stylish chandelier.<br><br>M had the Aglio Olio. It was enjoyed muchly and quickly, notably having the kick needed for the dish but isn&#39;t painfully spicy. This will be perfect for people who prefer to do without the numbing heat from chilli padis is most Aglio Olios. The Aglio Olio at Fika is served plain and additional ingredients that goes into it will be charged.<br><br>I had Swedish Meatballs which came with cream sauce, lingonberry sauce and sides of half a potato and salad. The meatballs were more floury than those at IKEA, which I felt gave them a more homemade feel.<br><br>We also had the Lingonberry cheesecake ($7.50). Go for this if you&#39;re on for rich decadent cheesecake. I felt this had an interesting slightly powdery aftertaste, which I&#39;m not too sure what to make of but I enjoyed it enough.<br><br>I returned on a separate occasion for their crepes which are delish too!

text: Totally love the smoked salmon open-faced sandwich! Fika is a place i frequent visit for their varieties of desserts. It&#39;s a great place to catch up with friends over a cup of hot tea and a slice of cake. Their service is warm &amp; friendly, The meatballs are good but i would go for their other dishes such as the Aglio Olio that you can choose from chicken, meatballs, shrimp or smoked salmon. They serve really good savoury crepes too. The crepes are light and fluffy. <br><br>For those who love to hunt for a good breakfast spot, you want to try it here. My choice will be their Raggmunk. It&#39;s rally good and sure fill up the stomach! It&#39;s a traditional Swedish breakfast set comprises of potato pancakes, shredded carrots, turkey bacon and the lingonberry jam. The set comes with your choice of drinks, either the Swedish blueberry or rose hip drink.<br><br>For parents who wants to enjoy these Swedish delicacies, fret not, Fika offers kids meal too!<br><br>For those coming in groups, do inform them in advance like what I did and we were all seated at the comfy second floor.<br><br>It&#39;s definitely a place worth going and great for those who are on their first date. ;)

Fika was the place I really enjoyed some good Swedish food. Though the place is a little small, its very cosy and its perfect for a nice dinner. Its usually quite crowded so reservations are recommended!<br><br>Personally, I&#39;m not so much of a meatball fanatic but the ones at Fika are actually really enjoyable. Quite unlike a certain other Swedish meatball eatery. They&#39;ve a nice crust to it that retains the juice from the meat. Do give their Pannbiff a try as well. Its the same meatball mixture but made into a larger beef patty.<br><br>I also had the lobster and seafood pasta which i thoroughly enjoyed. The sauce was excellent, the seafood was fresh and the pasta cooked perfectly.

text: Food here was mediocre and certainly not authentically Swedish. I ordered the Raggmunk, which was quite bad: soggy, gluey potato pancakes with plain shredded carrots on the side, plus turkey bacon. My partner&#39;s meatballs were OK, albeit dry and extremely salty.  Coffee was so-so. <br><br>On the upside, the ambience is very nice and they have a great selection of Swedish sodas that we have really missed from home. We would come back for the sodas and possibly bread or a snack, but not for a meal.
Blueberry loaf cake - 3 stars<br>Amazing, soft texture but it lacked flavour. Didn&#39;t even taste like butter! The frosting was probably just icing sugar since it just tasted sweet.

text: Guys I almost cried when I saw this food court, it&#39;s the most beautiful and harming food court ever.....located in the Shops at Marina Bay Sands.<br><br>Let me start saying that this food court has such beautiful background music and it the one they use for the attraction called; CANVAS.  <br><br>I went so many times and each time I approached the food court and start listening to the music I was happy instantly.<br><br>They have a huge variety of food vendors, all clean, with delicious looking food, and affordable prices.

Coffee from Liberty roasters but it was served way too hot burning it. I had it made up in a keepcup and there was an obvious thick dried coffee stain on side of the cup when it arrived and it remained too hot for me to pick up for several mins. But having said that when I gave this feedback to the staff, she immediately volunteered to remake it. No proper foam to speak of both times. Still too hot I&#39;m sure but it didn&#39;t taste as burnt as I thought. As it cooled, a cocoa note did start to come through. More practice!<br><br>Food portions were small but bread was good and fresh, eggs doneness perfect and came with nice prosciutto ham $15. It was pretty quiet in the morning and the coffee costs more than Kith and they took longer to get things out. I suppose they need more time to settle in. Service staff were humble and nice.<br><br>They bake their own bread apparently but for $8.90 a loaf to takeaway..they&#39;ll be having competition soon from Baker &amp; Cook opening up nearby. In any event, as I type this, my own butter rolls are baking in the oven...and I&#39;m not sure what&#39;s so special about their bread that it warrants a premium over other premium breads (Usually 6 to 7.50?) from the slew of bakeries around.

text: One of the best &#34;char siew&#34; pau in Singapore. The meat is tender and sweet and perfect when eaten hot out of their steamer. My only complaint is that the pau is a little small for the $0.70 it costs. If not for the price, I would have given them 5 stars.

I was pretty happy to discover the famous Tanjong Rhu Pau in the coffee shop near my new workplace! It&#39;s located in a traditional poky little place and its hot as hell just standing around there; I can&#39;t imagine how one can stand in that oven heat all day!<br><br>But the paus here are really quite good - I usually get a large meat pau, juicy with an egg, which helps to fill up after the wanton mee, but one unusual pau is the yuan yang pau, which consists of lotus paste and red bean.<br><br>You can buy the buns freshly steamed, or get them unsteamed and bring them home to steam them yourself.

text: Tanjong Rhu Pau fortunately for me is within the estate I live in, and even if it wasn&#39;t I would travel here from across Singapore to sample what they have to offer.  Im a massive fan on their Char Siu Bao, there is about 4 uncles in the store making varieties of steamed buns furiously to keep up with the never ending queue. The Char Siu Bao, pastry is light, while the filling moist and packed full of fragrant and tasty Char Siu. They do a variety of other dim sum dishes though Im only ever here for Char Siu Bao, or their wonton noodles. Their wonton noodles too are my favorite in Singapore, the char siu is tasty and moist, while the wontons themselves have a fantastic flavor. The soup is easily the best ive tasted in Singapore, no heavy hints of flavor enhancers in this one, just a good clean flavor with a well balance white pepper tone finishing it off. Glad I live within walking distance.

I grew up eating pau from this stall. Their char siew pau (Honey BBQ pork bun) is my favourite and has always been. I have tried searching for Paus from other shops to replace it but none have succeeded to this date. I love the small bite-sized paus they sell that are packed with tender, flavourful char siew. The buns are steamed to perfection, soft and sweet, simply a taste of heaven. They hand make their pau in the small coffee shop they occupy till this day, keeping the traditional method alive. Going back to this stall these days brings on waves of nostalgia of the good old days. <br><br>I believe you can sense my undying loyalty to this stall by now. However, the paus are pretty expensive for their size (70 cents each) and I have noticed a recent dwindling in the amount of meat given in eat pau. The taste and texture is still there though, so it is still very yummy to me. The stall also sells a number of other dim sum dishes that I have conveniently ignored over the past years for my heavily favoured char siew pau.
3.5 stars, had stopped here for a coffee. Decent brew, good ambiance, Ok spot for a coffee if you&#39;re tired of shopping on Orchard and need a break!

3.5 stars. Easy brunch / lunch spot with several branches in the city. Had the crab pasta which was surprisingly delicious (didn&#39;t expect a good pasta from a brunch place) - right balance of spicy and savory with a generous amount of crab.<br><br>A good spot for meeting up with friends. Vegetarian-friendly.

The Iced Cappuccino is disappointing. The coffee was bland as the taste of the coffee was not strong, even the milk taste wasn&#39;t apparent.<br> <br>The Flat White&#39;s blend came from Toby&#39;s Estate, so you know what to expect. Great coffee!<br> <br>The Roasted New Potatoes with Rosemary and Romesco Sauce was well sauteed and roasted to perfection, its enough to be eaten on its own. Have it, however, with the Romesco sauce for a mild spicy and tangy taste.<br> <br>The Spatchcock Chicken is a chicken that had their backbone removed so that it can be flattened before roasting it with lemon &amp; thyme, garlic &amp; shallots, verjus &amp; Creme Fraiche sauce. This resulted in a crispy skin and each piece of chicken tasting juicy and flavourful. It is one that must be ordered here!<br> <br>The Red Velvet Cake had disappointed a bit. The cake did not crumble easily, the taste of the cake were alright, but the taste of butter/cheese was in near absence in the cream used. Nonetheless, the quantity was enough to delight both of us.

text: Great brunch food with a view of Orchard&#39;s hustle and bustle.  Service is a bit hectic, though, and it can get a bit hot sitting outside.

This place is just around the corner from the office, so an obvious choice. It is a nice place to sit: you see the tout-Singapore parading by - or at least part of it. One must say that the serving staff is very friendly (although when I asked what time it was, one gave me the Philippines time ;) Not cheap but this is not a cheap location. Count about 16 S$ for a sandwich. The quality is variable: I had a few times the cheese/ham sandwich which is quite good - a bit better than a croque monsieur. A few days ago, I had the slow baked salmon sandwich which unfortunately was veeeery slow (a group of local women may have been the reason). But it also tasted poor: the tapenade was barely noticeable, the salmon had no taste and the other things - what were they again?
