text: This place looks nice from the outside. <br><br>The Providore charges more and gives you less than the competition that it is so obviously copying.  <br><br>Case in point: $12.50 (!!!) for two (of the smallest I&#39;ve ever seen)  eggs on ONE slice of (insufficiently) toasted bread that is cut twice to look like two pieces.  An insidious move that fools no one.<br><br>The BLT was tiny and overpriced. <br><br>We have way too many better choices for the same fare better executed, as the other reviewer mentioned. Good review, Irene was overly generous about them not being able to, as she says, muck up breakfast. <br><br>For some, Toast can be a difficult thing to master.

text: After reading wonderful reviews we thought this would be a fun place to try. We were quickly sat which seemed to be a good start on the perfect Saturday morning. After taking our order with relatively few hiccups the poor and unbelievable service started. The table next to us waited and hour for drinks which never came. As we sipped our coffee for the first hour I decided to check on the status of our food. A very wonderful server (I think named Edward who can def find a better place to work with his warm character) asked if we would still like our food as there had been a problem in the kitchen. He went to get the manager at my request as he checked the timing of our order. The manager first refused to speak to me because he was busy. Then informed me it was my problem because I came at a busy time. When I said it had been an hour and I had seen other tables turn over multiple times he yelled &#34;well if you want your food I need to go work&#34;. When the food did arrive one dish was over cooked, one was undercooked and there were egg shells in the eggs. I asked for the manager and he yelled &#34;what do you want?&#34;  I asked for the card to his supervisor and he yelled fine. Edward tried to apologize as the manager stormed off. We did not stay to eat eggshells....

text: The menu looks delicious and was full of promise, but my dinner here fell flat.  We had the lobster mac and cheese, tuna tartare, choux buns, mackerel crostini, beetroot and goat cheese, and stuffed pork.  The flavors for the most part were there and the presentation was good, but nearly everything was overcooked (with the exception of the beet which was cut too thick and not quite roasted long enough) - the lobster in the mac and cheese, the mackerel on the crostini, and the pecorino stuffed pork were overcooked and really dry.  Decent service by Singapore standards.  I also took a peek at the desserts and they really didn&#39;t look up to snuff - too rough around the edges and not appealing at all.  If I had to choose between here or Foodology for some western small plates, I&#39;d pick Foodology by a mile - better value, more extensive menu, and better execution.  That said, I&#39;m willing to give them another try once they worked out the kinks.  Breakfast looks promising and should be more difficult to muck up.

A pager was given which would light up when food is ready for collection.<br><br>Shepherd Pie ($9.90)<br>Available in both beef and chicken.<br>Served with a glass of iced lemon tea.<br>Only chicken version was available when I placed order. It was served pipping hot. Tasted not bad although I heard that the beef version was better.

text: Really laid back Korean pub serving your standard fare soju for $14 a bottle, maggeoli (sweet cloudy white rice wine - delicious) served out of a a quaint wooden bowl with scooper for around $27.<br><br>The food here is pretty average but really reasonably priced. Recently came with a couple of friends and had 3 bottles of soju and a variety of munchies like kim chi stew, beef soup, and kim chi pancake. Our bill came out to a shockingly low $77.<br><br>Drop by when you&#39;re in the neighborhood.

Who would have thought KoKo RooLoo is a Korean Restaurant? To add, the store front is brightly decorated and I walked passed a few time thinking it is a dessert shop.<br><br>KoKo RooLoo is opened by a Korean and the food sold are very authentic. Entering the store, you will find around 6-7 4-seats table squeezed in a small area. Ordering food from menu may be hard for someone who are not familiar with Korean dishes. The first time I ordered, the english names are all translation of the korean pronunciation making you not able to make out what the food really is. I can only see from the pictures on the menu. Most of the dishes are seldom seen selling in Korean stall in foodcourt and is a totally new experience to me and my tongue.<br><br>In the night, the store become a place where people enjoy Soju (Rice wine) with Kimchi, pork meat. It open all the way to 12am. Quite unusual for a restaurant.

Located in Tanjong Pagar Plaza next to a bunch of local restaurants and coffee shops, Koko Rooloo serves up reasonably priced Korean food. The restaurant is nothing special, a place to get a quick fix on food and get out of there. I ordered the U-Dong noodles ($8) for takeaway and was pretty happy. These are vegetarian noodles with egg strips, seaweed and skewered tofu, although a small-small-ish portion for the $8. Check it out for something different.
They mess up complicated orders a lot. Also, they mess up simple orders a lot.

text: Located along Haji Lane, and a sister cafe of The Working Title, famed for their burgers, is a British style cafe that serves up Halal food. There&#39;s both outdoor dining as well as an air con dining area on the second floor of the shop house. I had been meaning to try this place, but just never found the time, this time.<br><br>Get seated, comfy and grab a menu. At one glance, you will spot numerous fish and chip items, including Haddock, Cod, Dory, as well as Deli items, pastas, and Sarnies. Your usual big breakfast is also available. Comfort food for any occasion really. Most of the mains are priced from $18-$24. All prices are nett.<br><br>1.Bangers &amp; Mash $18<br>Served with Beef, this is prolly one of the few Halal bangers and mash I&#39;ve seen in Singapore. The beef was so juicy and tender. The skin of the bangers were so thin and almost crispy. The mash was so light and melted in my mouth. This was a rather light main in comparison to the fish and chips, a great choice for young ladies who are watching their diet.<br><br>2. Haddock Fish and Chips $20<br>Golden brown, two huge pieces of freshly fried haddock slices of fish. Serves with chips and slaw. The batter was crisp on the outside but slightly doughy on the inside. The same was noticed in the Cod Fish and Chips. At least, the oil they used was fresh, as there was no lingering aroma of oil. The fish itself tasted reasonably fresh, though slightly bland. The chips were great! Definitely worth the calories!<br><br>3. Cod Fish and Chips<br>To be honest, I couldn&#39;t really taste the difference between the cod and the haddock, except that the cod fish meat was softer and slightly mushier.  The fried batter was exactly the same. I wish that the fish could&#39;ve been cooked a bit more, so that the batter would be firmer.<br><br>4. Gravy Train $20<br>Probably the best main we had. This was packed with so much flavour and meat. I am now excited to go to try The Working Title, for their burgers. Just like The Mad Sailors, The Working Title also takes the ENTERTAINER app! The bacon here wasn&#39;t as skinful as your typical pork bacon, it was extremely flavourful. The brioche here was done perfectly, crisp in areas you need it to be and fluffy in other areas. On point!<br><br>5. Banoffee Cake $8.50<br>Made in-house, this cake was screaming my name! Banana and Coffee, both my personal favourite. There were actually banana fruits embedded in between the cake sponge. The cake sponge itself was drenched in coffee, but the coffee flavour couldn&#39;t be picked up. Though, you could smell the coffee fragrance. Elsewhere, the banana cream was a tad too sweet for my liking.<br><br>6. Truffle Chips $12<br>You would think that after ordering so many mains with chips, why am I ordering Truffle Chips?! Because the chips here at The Mad Sailors is awesome!<br>Overall :  A lovely cafe, with rustic notes, great service from the staff and comfort British food. Definitely go crazy with the carbs here!

Muddy mud pie", 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Muddy mud pie'}]
text: I used to love Coffee Club for its coffee, especially mochaccino, and then for its light bites (country pie, wedges and burgers). Over the years the menu has been updated and as with any changes, somehow it is no longer as good. Or maybe as I get older, my palate has changed too. <br><br>The muddy mud pie is still a huge block/wedge of ice cream (chocolate and coffee), drizzled with chocolate sauce and topped with crushed chocolate cookie crumbs (looks like oreo). Best to be shared. But the taste of the ice cream is not heavenly, it tastes like what you get from Magnolia ice cream. <br><br>The food is average. I do miss the wedges as they have been taken off the menu and replaced by baked potato skins. <br><br>Thankfully the coffee is still alright, or at least the cappuccino and latte I had are ok. <br><br>Sit outside by the walkway if you want to people watch. Otherwise there are pretty comfy seats inside. This is probably one of the few places in Paragon which is not so crowded. <br><br>Yelp Feb 2014 Challenge: 18/28

text: The cafe used to be a pop up, and recently it took over the courtyard cafe space, which was located in the far end of the museum. It offered local dishes and snacks. One of the cheaper choices for dining in the museum. It was self service system here - order and wait for buzzer to light up before collecting at the counter.<br><br>Mix and Match Kuehs Set Meal ($5)<br>2 choices of kueh from the display shelves and a choice of coffee or tea.<br>Selected Ondeh Ondeh Gula Melaka ($2.70/ 3pcs) which were soft although preferred the skin to be thinner, and Kueh DaDar ($1.80) which was packed with juicy coconut filling. <br><br>Kid&#39;s Set Meal ($4.80)<br>Egg &amp; Cheese Sandwich + OWL Bubble Orange Soda<br>The sandwich was served on a wooden board. Cheesy and packed with thick slices of tomato.

text: Artisan Boulangerie Co. is a fun cafe style restaurant that offers an interesting blend of drinks and/or quick meals. <br><br>For those of you who know Killiney Road you know that there are a number of coffee houses and cafes in this area. Many of them are outdoor or open air cafes. That&#39;s great if you wish to embrace the elements but if you want to sit in air conditioned comfort this is the place for you. <br><br>The food here is as you would expect. They offer numerous bakery items and quick meals like various egg-based dishes for breakfast and salads and sandwiches for later in the day. Of course, they do a great job on their lattes and various other coffee-based drinks.<br><br>The seating is nice here. The staff is friendly and helpful. Overall, it is a great place to grab a quick meal or sit back with some coffee, cruise the internet, or talk with friends.

text: I&#39;m not sure why I didn&#39;t wander into this restaurant sooner since it&#39;s so close. Paleo? They sure make it easy to follow the lifestyle. Their menu features salads and meats with veggie sides in addition to the typical bakery delights. Good luck avoiding the breads and pasteries...they look delicious! <br><br>So far, I&#39;ve had the beetroot, pumpkin and feta salad (skip the feta for the Paleo folks), and it was awesome. Very fresh. I&#39;ve also sampled their omelet with peppers, mushrooms and ham, which was also good. My favorite so far is their peri peri chicken ($22) because it couldn&#39;t be more Paleo with seasoned, grilled chicken breasts and veggies. Don&#39;t love too much spice? They put most of the sauce on the side. <br><br>In the Killiney Road area and looking for something healthy? This would be my first recommendation. I&#39;d go here daily if it was a bit less expensive!

Roasted chicken baguette', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Roasted chicken baguette'}]
text: I live down the street from here, so I cant believe this place has been open for over a month and i didn&#39;t notice... Until yesterday, when i happened to walk down this way after coming back from town. Anyway, i came here for lunch so i didn&#39;t try the pastries (next time!).<br><br>I had their roasted chicken sandwich, which was more like a baguette since that&#39;s what they used instead of soft bread. This was simple and really good! I don&#39;t normally finish the bread part of sandwiches in my feeble attempt to save some carbs, but i definitely gobbled up every last crumbs of this sandwich. The baguette is actually what makes it delicious, it&#39;s laced with different types of nuts and seeds which gives it that nice crunchy texture and savory flavor. I do feel the price is steep for just a simple baguette though. It was $11.80, I think i would have been more ok if it was $8-9.<br><br>I got a long black and, like other reviewers, was disappointed. I expected such place to serve quality coffee, but it tasted like the coffee brewed in my office pantry and costed $4.80. I&#39;ll go somewhere else for my caffeine kick next time.<br><br>They also have a brunch menu from 8am - 2pm!

text: I cherry picked my pastries based on visual-appeal. I swept sweet bakes like Vanilla &amp; Raisin Swirl $3.50 &amp; Orange Brioche off the shelve, and the former wins slightly but with low marks. The Danish presented in burnt rims, has a notable buttery flavor but not rich enough to remember. The sweet glaze blend gently with the flaky pastry partnering some scattered candies raisins. I wasn&#39;t really impressed with the taste, just mediocre.<br><br>The Orange Brioche $5.00, was weaker in taste. It didn&#39;t sing any buttery tune like other artisanal brioche, no signs of flakiness and rather dry in its texture. There was a small helping of citrus scented custard piped in the middle of the dough, mildly sweet. The orange fruit slice hindered my chewing - simply aesthetically pleasing on the the sweet bread.<br><br>The Madeleine $2.00/pc, was a decent piece. Not exceedingly sweet with a soft interior. I&#39;d prefer it to be served warm like db Moderne Bistro so that I could taste the rich buttery structure in its comforting warmth. This one was left in the open, atop the pastry glass cabinet, side-by-side the Financiers. Obviously, it has been overpriced.<br><br>The Kumara &amp; Bleu Tart $6.00/pc, champ the fleet in my whole selection when its rivals failed to compete well. The soft and crumbly tart shell adapted quite well to the sweet orange-pigmented kumara cubes gelled together in a pool of coagulated cheese - buttery rich and very delightful. Noticeable flavor is seen coming from the flaky tart, less from the filling.<br><br>The battle field continues to be less interesting when the limping Roast Chicken Sandwich $11.50, hit the ground. The fillet slices were dry and fibrous, no traces of flavor until my taste buds met up with the sweet onion chutney above the fresh lettuce. The hard-like-rock baguette made things worst, it was a total shame!<br><br>When I thought nothing will be praised, I was charmed by the healthier fare, $8.50 - Quinoa &amp; Lentil Salads. The power grains are executed in perfection along with a mixture of soft lentil which is often undercooked. Carefully seasoned with the right amount of tang lending from the balsamic reduction and some sweet hints from the fresh apple slices, the rehydrated dried cranberry fruits, the heap of rocket greens woke my taste buds with a striking saltiness from the accompanying shaven Parmesan. Just as the episode starts to climax, I felt a cold gush of water came splashing down - the 2 sesame rolls that served alongside was rockier &amp; rubbery than the earlier baguette! What&#39;s happening to the breads here? I let out a heavy sigh!

text: Saw a friend check in on Facebook and it sounded interesting, so I dragged my companion for the day on Sunday to give this place a try.<br><br>The decor&#39;s real fancy, and the entrance felt more like I was entering a bank than a bakery. The theme continues, with a lot of glitzy and posh throughout the place.<br><br>We had a pain au chocolat (mediocre, good but not better than the other famous places like Maison Kayser or Tiong Bahru Bakery) and a raspberry tart (my companion like this but I was unimpressed).<br><br>The coffee was decent, but nothing to go back for. I&#39;d really like to try their sandwiches the next time I&#39;m there, the breads and pretzels looked quite enticing.<br><br>Overall I&#39;m excited at this new place. It&#39;s just a ho-hum first impression taste wise, but that counter was stocked with other things I&#39;d love to go back and try.

text: The ambience, decor and gorgeous display of baked goods and pastries was what attracted me to ABC @ Somerset when I first stumbled across it. I had the latte and it was good. <br><br>Subsequent visits to the Somerset and Asia Square outlets were really disappointing. I really wanted to like this place but the bread and pastries here are not worth the effort. <br><br>On one visit I bought a loaf of bread after asking the staff to recommend one that was soft &amp; fluffy in texture, instead it turned out to be dry and crumbly. On other visits, we have tried the pear tart, chocolate eclair (twice!), chocolate lava cake. The tart and lava cake were average, nothing to shout about. The eclair pastry was surprisingly dry and hard. I would rather pay a few more dollars to have a delicious Paul bakery eclair than waste my calories here. <br><br>If you are looking for a chill out cafe to have a coffee and a chat with friends, this would be the ideal place.. But i wouldn&#39;t go out of my way to eat here again unless the quality of the food improves.

text: I live down the street from here, so I cant believe this place has been open for over a month and i didn&#39;t notice... Until yesterday, when i happened to walk down this way after coming back from town. Anyway, i came here for lunch so i didn&#39;t try the pastries (next time!).<br><br>I had their roasted chicken sandwich, which was more like a baguette since that&#39;s what they used instead of soft bread. This was simple and really good! I don&#39;t normally finish the bread part of sandwiches in my feeble attempt to save some carbs, but i definitely gobbled up every last crumbs of this sandwich. The baguette is actually what makes it delicious, it&#39;s laced with different types of nuts and seeds which gives it that nice crunchy texture and savory flavor. I do feel the price is steep for just a simple baguette though. It was $11.80, I think i would have been more ok if it was $8-9.<br><br>I got a long black and, like other reviewers, was disappointed. I expected such place to serve quality coffee, but it tasted like the coffee brewed in my office pantry and costed $4.80. I&#39;ll go somewhere else for my caffeine kick next time.<br><br>They also have a brunch menu from 8am - 2pm!

text: I cherry picked my pastries based on visual-appeal. I swept sweet bakes like Vanilla &amp; Raisin Swirl $3.50 &amp; Orange Brioche off the shelve, and the former wins slightly but with low marks. The Danish presented in burnt rims, has a notable buttery flavor but not rich enough to remember. The sweet glaze blend gently with the flaky pastry partnering some scattered candies raisins. I wasn&#39;t really impressed with the taste, just mediocre.<br><br>The Orange Brioche $5.00, was weaker in taste. It didn&#39;t sing any buttery tune like other artisanal brioche, no signs of flakiness and rather dry in its texture. There was a small helping of citrus scented custard piped in the middle of the dough, mildly sweet. The orange fruit slice hindered my chewing - simply aesthetically pleasing on the the sweet bread.<br><br>The Madeleine $2.00/pc, was a decent piece. Not exceedingly sweet with a soft interior. I&#39;d prefer it to be served warm like db Moderne Bistro so that I could taste the rich buttery structure in its comforting warmth. This one was left in the open, atop the pastry glass cabinet, side-by-side the Financiers. Obviously, it has been overpriced.<br><br>The Kumara &amp; Bleu Tart $6.00/pc, champ the fleet in my whole selection when its rivals failed to compete well. The soft and crumbly tart shell adapted quite well to the sweet orange-pigmented kumara cubes gelled together in a pool of coagulated cheese - buttery rich and very delightful. Noticeable flavor is seen coming from the flaky tart, less from the filling.<br><br>The battle field continues to be less interesting when the limping Roast Chicken Sandwich $11.50, hit the ground. The fillet slices were dry and fibrous, no traces of flavor until my taste buds met up with the sweet onion chutney above the fresh lettuce. The hard-like-rock baguette made things worst, it was a total shame!<br><br>When I thought nothing will be praised, I was charmed by the healthier fare, $8.50 - Quinoa &amp; Lentil Salads. The power grains are executed in perfection along with a mixture of soft lentil which is often undercooked. Carefully seasoned with the right amount of tang lending from the balsamic reduction and some sweet hints from the fresh apple slices, the rehydrated dried cranberry fruits, the heap of rocket greens woke my taste buds with a striking saltiness from the accompanying shaven Parmesan. Just as the episode starts to climax, I felt a cold gush of water came splashing down - the 2 sesame rolls that served alongside was rockier &amp; rubbery than the earlier baguette! What&#39;s happening to the breads here? I let out a heavy sigh!

ABC special : came w a basket of roll which is really yummy with e butter and jam spread. it&#39;s addictive and we finished e whole basket of it. forget carbs diet! Everything else on e main plate was just OK. Sunny side up + bacon + salad + shrooms. <br><br>Next time ill just stick to their pastries!<br><br>yes its as easy as ABC. like it? come again!

text: Fab decor and ambience but pastries are a bit meh. Came in on a Saturday for brunch and place was buzzing. The staff are all quite young, perhaps that&#39;s why they&#39;re all bustling very busily to little effect. <br>Tried the boeuf bourguignon pie - dug in and found peas and potato. Perfectly ok but that&#39;s not boeuf bourguignon so they should just label it a beef pie lah. Have to say they&#39;re very generous with the beef and the chunks were tender, not chewy. Good quality balsamic on the accompanying salad. <br> The portobello sandwich had generous stuffing of well seasoned portobello, but it was cold. Would be much better warm. The chocolate croissant wasn&#39;t buttery enough although it was ok. Chocolate eclair wasn&#39;t too sweet but again ok, no great shakes. Best thing was a lemon curd tart with a bracingly tangy curd - but then again I can make lemon curd, so um not blown away. <br>Long black coffee tasted a little sour like it&#39;d been percolating a while so I&#39;d advise coffee aficionados to go for the lattes and mochas which have to be made fresh.

text: Saw a friend check in on Facebook and it sounded interesting, so I dragged my companion for the day on Sunday to give this place a try.<br><br>The decor&#39;s real fancy, and the entrance felt more like I was entering a bank than a bakery. The theme continues, with a lot of glitzy and posh throughout the place.<br><br>We had a pain au chocolat (mediocre, good but not better than the other famous places like Maison Kayser or Tiong Bahru Bakery) and a raspberry tart (my companion like this but I was unimpressed).<br><br>The coffee was decent, but nothing to go back for. I&#39;d really like to try their sandwiches the next time I&#39;m there, the breads and pretzels looked quite enticing.<br><br>Overall I&#39;m excited at this new place. It&#39;s just a ho-hum first impression taste wise, but that counter was stocked with other things I&#39;d love to go back and try.

Coastes is a bar/restaurant in Sentosa that is conveniently located right on the beach. They&#39;re open for breakfast through late night, and even have day beds that you can rent for only $22 SGD a day. <br><br>I came specifically for the day beds, as it was my last day in Singapore and I wanted to have a nice relaxing day on the beach. I arrived around 9:30am and there were plenty of day beds available. The beds can definitely fit two people if you want to share with a partner or friend.<br><br>If you want food, you order at the cashier and someone will bring the food to you. I tried an iced latte ($7) and the Greek salad ($14). The salad was a decent sized portion and a refreshing combination of cucumbers, cherry tomatoes, red onions, feta cheese, and croutons in a light dressing.<br><br>Definitely get here early if you&#39;re intending to tan! The restaurant quickly filled up around 11am and all the day beds were taken by the time I left around 2pm. Would definitely come back here again for its prime location on the beach and great food.

text: Pretty pricey for the quality of food - but to be fair it&#39;s lunch with a view right on the water. I had a basic burger with fries and a beer. Food came out decently quick once you pay at cashier.

Tried/unable to get service here on a slow Wednesday morning with 10% capacity.  It was cloudy and totally dead. We just wanted a drink at the bar but they have a $25 minimum per person for service.  I completely understand on busy days and times but oh well- Just FYI.

text: This is my second visit to coastes and instead of going there during mid day. I learnt my lesson and decided to go there during dinner when the sun has set and you can enjoy the outdoor ambience.<br><br>1. Fish and chips $22 <br><br>The portion of the fish and chips is really just for one. The fish seems big but it&#39;s really not. I was a bit upset with their portion of fries. I&#39;ve had a side of fries before and they were way more generous with the fries then.<br><br>But with the sea view and sounds, the taste of the food is improved some what.<br><br>The fish meat was tasteless and the exterior wasn&#39;t crispy but rather mushy. It was very upsetting with my first cut into the fish fillet. Don&#39;t waste your money with this dish. Their pasts were better.<br><br>2. Big bad wolf pizza $24<br><br>This is big enough to share amongst 2. The bacon was very fatty and wasn&#39;t crispy but still added a lot of flavour into the pizza. They were pretty creative in this dish and in every slice you get all the ingredients. I enjoy thin crust and I liked this however it could&#39;ve been in the oven for a short while more.<br><br>3. Coastes wings $10<br><br>$10 for 3 whole wings is probably the most expensive wings I&#39;ve ever bought but it&#39;s cooked hawker style. BBQed with lime wasn&#39;t what I was expecting but the wings were juicy and sweet with the barbecue sauce. <br><br>All in all, an okay place for food. Definitely expect to pay more. Hits and misses but I think their pastas is what I will go for if I ever visit again.

text: Nice ambience - next to the beach and semi-outdoor dining.<br><br>Came with Mel. Y. here as there was a promotion on one of the food apps we use and we decided to try this place out. <br><br>At around 5pm on a Saturday, this place was packed pretty fast. Quite a number of long communal tables and smaller tables to accommodate small or big groups. <br><br>We looked at the menu and hence decided on getting the Creamy Pesto Pasta and Calamari Rings.<br><br>The Creamy Pesto Pasta was in a bigger portion than we had expected. The pasta contains Spaghetti with asparagus, mushrooms, bell pepper and Parmesan cheese in pesto cream sauce. The pesto sauce left lingering taste on the tastebuds and I enjoyed the mix of ingredients in the spaghetti. <br><br>Calamari Rings was a little expensive but the tartar sauce that accompanied it was one of the best condiments I&#39;ve tasted so far. Without squeezing the lemon on the calamari rings, you can taste the citrus while chewing on the calamari rings. The calamari was also chewy and the flour they used to fry made the dish crispy. They even sprinkled a good amount of pepper inside the rings so without the tartar sauce it was also perfect. Definitely a recommended beach bite.<br><br>Overall, I enjoy the ambience that this place has to offer. And the prices of the food was pretty reasonable too considering it to be located in a touristy spot. Do try the calamari rings out if you are nearby :)

text: I loved Coastes! It was one of my favourite places on Sentosa Island - so much so I insisted on coming back!<br><br>Firstly, the location is incredible. Siloso Beach, while man-made, is a really fun and beautiful place. Coastes provides the perfect place to have lunch, watch the sunset or spend a relaxing afternoon. I really love the blue and white beach theme they have - it&#39;s very well done and very appropriate. They also have sun beds available for hire, complete with tables and umbrellas for private use. <br><br>Moving on to the food. We stuck to the burgers on both visits just because of how amazing they were! They would have to offer one of the best burgers I&#39;ve ever had. The patty was thick, juicy and so full of flavour. The bun was soft and tasty, and the sauce was incredible! Honestly, the thought of this burger, coupled with Siloso beach and a beautiful sunset is enough to make me want to drop what I&#39;m doing and get back on a plane to Singapore! We also tried their take on a creme brûlée, which was a little different, but still very tasty and I really enjoyed the biscuit base. <br><br>The staff were all friendly and helpful, and prices were pretty standard. For me, it was definitely the standout bar along the stretch of bars at Siloso beach. I&#39;d definitely recommend spending an afternoon here.

We all have a favorite beach, but what about a favorite beachside cafe? Coastes is a great one in Singapore. <br><br>You&#39;re paying quite a bit for a nice view/location, but the food is standard, the service is great and, again, you&#39;re on the beach. <br><br>In the end, I would say that Coastes is a perfect spot for enjoying a cold and refreshing drink overlooking the water but I would avoid their brunch and please, don&#39;t look forward to a really good meal if you&#39;re a foodie (are you?).

I was here last Monday afternoon with my 2 girlfriends, we wanted to get away from the city and enjoy the beach but my afternoon was ruined by the rudest staff I have ever met in my life.<br><br>We rented 2 beach chairs, ordered food and drinks and were just sitting there minding our own business until this one staff came over and start attacking us with some serious attitude: &#34;You cannot eat here lah!!!&#34; We had 2 boxes of strawberries with us, we thought we paid $40 the chair so outside food would not be an issue, we have been here a few hours and no one said anything and honestly we didn&#39;t know! <br><br>So we said &#34;Okay, we didn&#39;t know, we won&#39;t eat anymore&#34;<br>- &#34;No you have to put this away lah, or I have to hide this lah&#34; <br>- &#34;But we have no where to put this, our bag is full&#34;<br>- Guy start collecting the 2 boxes, took them and put them on my side table, away from us behind my bag &#34;I&#39;m being very generous cleaning this for you lah!&#34;<br>There were many lah and his attitude was just shocking.<br><br>My whole life I have never encountered this kind of attitude from a service staff. &#34;Generous?&#34; No thank you, you can keep your generosity to yourself and your bar.<br><br>5 mins later, he came back, took away the padding on the other chair, and started unfolding it, we told him &#34;My friend went to the bathroom, please leave her chair there&#34;. He replied: &#34;Why didn&#39;t you tell me?&#34; and managed to give us a nasty look and walked away with more altitude.<br><br>Are we supposed to announce to every staff there &#34;My friend went to the bathroom, please do not take her chair away&#34; every time one of us go to use the washroom??? <br><br>Feel like our peaceful afternoon got ruined by someone who is untrained and PMSing, we asked another staff for his name and said that we would like to talk to the manager. The staff refuse to give us his name, that&#39;s fine, the manager came over, apologized, saying he&#39;s got regulars (mind blown)<br><br>I do not expect 5 star service at a beach bar, and I am quite used to bad customer service here but this is ANOTHER LEVEL of rudeness, a whole new level. We did not come there to pay money for chairs, food, drinks and be treated like that, so you can take out your miserable life on us, we were not told no food allowed so we did not know, if you tell us we will just stop eating. You do not have a right to mistreat your customers just because you feel shitty.<br><br>If you can&#39;t do your job, quit! Don&#39;t treat others like we owe you. I wonder if all the other 1 star reviews are thanks to this gentleman &#34;lah&#34; <br><br>This make me doubt the hiring, the training of your staff and Trust me we won&#39;t be back to pay money to be treated like this again. Sincerely

My colleagues and I dropped by Coastes for a company dinner last week. The ambience was quite good though our seating area was relatively warm. We could even see the fireworks from the adjacent water show.<br><br>Among the things we ordered and I tried were chilli crab dip, seafood stew and lobster spaghetti. The chilli crab dip was spicier than expected which went down well with a couple of my colleagues. However it could certainly do with more crab meat. It also did not come with mantou which was slightly disappointing. As for the seafood stew, it could have been fresher. The lobster spaghetti was distinctly average as well.<br><br>The wine was actually the highlight of the evening as we ordered a good red. The dessert of brownie and ice-cream was also hard to miss and made up for the meal otherwise.

text: Good service and good food!<br>We tried the honey beef, the guineas beef stew, and the seafood platter they were all great! Highly recommend!<br><br>The chicken sandwich was just your any plain old chicken sandwich.

Went there on Christmas day for brunch. For its location and proximity to the beach it&#39;s super value for money compared for other brunch places in SG. The eggs benedict was great and very generous with the ham. <br><br>Cappuccino was more of a shot and quantities should be improved.<br><br>The waiter tried to balance 8 glasses and dropped them when all he had to do was wall 20 steps an extra time which was quite shabby. The showers are a nice touch.<br><br>All in all a nice place and worth going to but please be early so you can get a sand bench which is nice. Take your swimming trunks and make the best of the private beach as well.

Crazy busy with lots of screaming kids. Beach view is obstructed by tankers. Relatively pricey for what you get.<br><br>Food was disappointing: club sandwich was dry and flavourless with no mayo or sauce on it, Greek salad looked great but lacked basic seasoning and bbq ribs were fall off the bone without any flavour or sauce to it. Will not be eating here again.

text: Another Sentosa chill out fave of mine, Coastes doesn&#39;t get large crowds when I visit and is quiet so I can just peace out. <br><br>The food is decent and prices are affordable. One thing I keep coming back for is the calamari rings. Its usually that and a drink, my laptop and I can spend the entire day till dinner before I leave.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/VxeS8Ccehi2VllncTqMfiA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/coastes-singapore?reviewid=HBVj9Remru6mKbjOYb33og&select=VxeS8Ccehi2VllncTqMfiA', 'altText': 'Photo of Coastes - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: It&#39;s never too crowded and rowdy here at Coastes. The ambience is perfect for a chillout by the beach, soaking up the sun and getting a tan.<br><br>To top it all, the food is decent and affordable. The breakfast sets are pretty good and come with a sizeable portion and available till about 2pm in the afternoon. A basket of calamari rings is a definite must-have as well to snack on. <br><br>For couples looking to suntan, you can rent a sunbed too. Prices start from $15 for a single and $20 for double. It&#39;s a day rate, so once you rent it, it&#39;s yours till you leave Coastes.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/1j8fvxC17F8XXfeWaTuQIQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/coastes-singapore?reviewid=pKf4sKkcYzPEIklV0bo2tg&select=1j8fvxC17F8XXfeWaTuQIQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Coastes - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Phnijnq1Wrkg6UkXwPjWnw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/coastes-singapore?reviewid=pKf4sKkcYzPEIklV0bo2tg&select=Phnijnq1Wrkg6UkXwPjWnw', 'altText': 'Photo of Coastes - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: If you&#39;re heading to Sentosa, this is ideally where you would go eat. A really casual, right-on-the-beach spot that enables you to enjoy the tranquility of the waves without all the commercial antics of the rest of Sentosa (at least based on what I saw as we drove/walked past everything else to get here). The food is decent, but it&#39;s really the casual charm of this place that had me hooked. After days of working a big event in a conference center, it was just wonderful to be outside and enjoying the cooler evening air, the sand between our toes and the beautiful setting for a meal to celebrate. I had the burger, which was good. I should have probably ordered a Tiger beer instead of the Singapore Sling, but figured I had to try it at some point, so why not do it in a tropical setting...just realized it isn&#39;t quite my thing, so the beer would have likely been better. It appears that they have live music on the weekends, so that likely makes it more vibrant and could lead to longer waits. They do take reservations and were prompt in responding to my online inquiry and flexible when the number in our party changed. All in all, it was a good evening out, so thank you Coastes!

Probably one of my favorite places in Singapore.<br>This is a beachfront restaurant, that doesn&#39;t rush you through, has good food and nice bathrooms.<br>I&#39;ve been coming to Coates for years, and before they remodeled a few years ago I didn&#39;t enjoy it as much, it felt small and cramped and had small, not good for changing, bathrooms. Really difficult with sandy children or anyone. <br>They have since remodeled, expanding and opening up their kitchen into a show kitchen style. And they seriously upgraded their bathroom facilities, it now has two shower/changing areas, one that is big enough for a family of five or more. The advantage of this is that you can spend many hours here and a place to shower and change is most welcomed. <br>I know there are many different experiences at Coastes, I have never been there in the evening, or during the week, I am only there on a Saturday or Sunday morning with kids. Get there early and claim a table and then let the kids loose in the sand and the water. I say to get there early because once you have a table you can just camp out and enjoy the beach. But, while you are there make sure you order some food because it is very good as well. It has a large variety, with western and Asian food, more western, and a full bar with great mixed cocktails as well. They have recently launched their own mobile ordering app that is great which lets you order and pay from your table without waiting in the ordering queue, then just sit back, and wait for the food to come out. <br>The beach is nice and clean and even has some lounge chairs you can rent for $20/day. For all of the comments about the view being ruined and all of the ships spoiling. Find another country, anyone who has spent more than a day or two knows you can not look out of Singapore without seeing the ships, that is the nature of the country and the busy port.<br><br>I highly recommend this place for families with children, just not when I am there because they are already filling up ;)

Six of us checked in to Coastes and after initially just ordering drinks, and then spending some time swimming, we decided to order lunch. Service was OK, certainly better than many places at Sentosa, but the food quality was very good. From a simple burger and fries to their pasta, garlic prawns and chicken curry, there was nary a sound from the six of us as we ate the food. <br><br>Definitely will be returning.

Nothing really special from my mind in terms of uniqueness: the view lacks quite a bit considering that i&#39;m viewing a couple tankers just sitting there, ruining the view but guess in Asia, this is as good as it gets.<br><br>the sand&#39;s nice, peace and quiet when i was there, but their blue and white wooden &#39;lounge&#39; chairs ---far from CSI Miami&#39;s comffy ones haha---means you better bring out yr own cushions unless you don&#39;t mind a sore bum after 15 minutes.

Great management. Had a small issue with the food that was served. Very promptly they took it away, send a manager who handled it with pure professionalism that normal you don&#39;t find in Singapore. Great afternoon at the beach, and much thanks to the Coastes team!

text: I ordered a green curry speghetti. It definitely had green curry flavor, but everything was pretty bland.  I ordered calamari rings also, and people were right, the rings were okay, but the tarter sauce was pretty good.

text: I am not usually a fan of Sentosa, largely because I am uncomfortable with its recent evolution into an ostentatious playground for the rich.<br><br>Coastes, however, has a strong family-oriented vibe during the day, and the set-up by the beach is casual and pleasant. It has a great beach shack feel, and I love the combination of white and blue. The crowd during the weekends is a good mix of tourists, local youth and families. <br><br>Being part of the Emerald Hill group, the biggest draw is definitely the food. We had the burger and margherita pizza which were good and satisfying. The array of cocktails is also diverse, and we were pleased with the ones we tried. <br><br>The only annoying bit is their odd policy of requiring patrons to order and pay at a central counter. Besides that, I would certainly return to Coastes for the occasional escape from the city because of the food and feel-good vibes.

A brilliant chill out spot at siloso beach. Great for families, pets, kids and groups of friends. The menu is seriously nothing to shout about. But the location and relaxing vibe more than makes up for it.

text: We brought our large dog with us for a dinner on the beach after his first outing at Sentosa. We arrived at Coastes after 6, the place was not busy and we got a lovely table next to those on the beach. Without asking, our waiter brought a large bowl of water for our dog, which he was happy about. Then he settled down and we proceeded to enjoy a meal of seafood platter, wings and cocktails. Service was great, we (dog included) felt very welcome, and the view of the sunset was beautiful. All the waiters we encountered seemed right at home with our dog so I highly recommend this place if you are looking for a good dinner spot to bring your large dog. The only reason for deducting a star is that the wings really can be better, hopefully they will improve!

text: I really like this place despite the fact that you pay a premium price for alcohol. Whatever, it&#39;s still an attractive beach side bar located on Sentosa Island. We went on a weekday evening and once during the day and it wasn&#39;t crowded. They have old fashioned wooden lounge chairs down by the water where you can enjoy a beer and contemplate the meaning of life or whatever&#39;s on your mind. I&#39;ll go again on my next trip.

Coastes is probably the closest you&#39;ll get to beach front dining in Singapore with tables and lounge chairs laid out across the sand metres away from the waves. Week nights in my opinion would be the best time to visit Coastes and  enjoy the sea breeze while sipping on cocktails. In terms of food, a must try dish would be their signature ribs which are cooked perfectly with a generous side of wedges. Definitely a place I would visit again but not over the weekend.

My little pony !!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'My little pony !!'}]
text: I&#39;m always amazed at how much effort Kumoya puts into transforming this small cafe into such a whimsical experience. I&#39;ve been to Kumoya for Miffy, Tokidoki and My little pony themes and I will be heading there Soon in Jan 2019 for the Pusheen cat theme as well.<br><br>The food is okay to good in terms of creativity, they get a high score and simple food dishes like soy glaze karage (deep fried chicken) or truffle fries tasted really good!!.. Unlike some other themed cafes that you are really paying money just for the cuteness. I feel that Kumoya does have some decent food qualities and standards.<br><br>I love their waffles, it&#39;s not the crispy type but their batter is sweet, and for the salad, you get star shaped cheese! Their desserts are pretty okay, just order the right ones, some of their cakes like the galaxy cakes are really small for $21.90+ but you do get a freebie, but as I usually visit at the end of each themed period (usually for 2 months), most of these freebies are out of stock. But then again, there&#39;s less queue. I usually get there around 1130-1145am on a sat or Sunday before the shop opens at 12pm. As the cafe is really small and there&#39;s only 1 table for big groups, if you are dining in groups of 2 or 4s, it&#39;s quite easy to get a table.<br><br>there&#39;s 10% service charge and no gst.

text: While we were disappointed with the Gudetama themed cafe experience, we still wanted to give it another shot and tried Kumoya, which was a pop up themed cafe. We came here when they were featuring Pusheen. <br><br>We only got iced drinks here. But, let me tell you, they were overpriced and bland drinks. Too much ice in both of our latte and frappe drinks. Same pattern like Gudetama cafe - you come here only for the pics. And just like Gudetama Cafe, the customer service was awful. They didn&#39;t even tell us that my iced latte needed sugar, and didn&#39;t direct me to where the sugar was. If you love Pusheen, though, and you come in time to see Pusheen, this spot is definitely picture worthy. I wished I could&#39;ve taken a Pusheen stuffed animal home with me, but they&#39;re like $45 each. Anyway, you should just come here once to get the Pusheen experience.

text: From 5 October to 31 December 2017, the cafe was reopened as a Miffy character pop up cafe. Besides food, the cafe also offered Miffy products for sale. There was a 10% service charge and only cash and NETS was accepted for payment. Ice water was not served here.<br><br>Miffy Hot Latte ($8.90++)<br>Handcrafted and brewed to perfection from Premium UCC Japanese Coffee Beans.<br>The drink looked quite cute with sugared ears but tasted average.<br><br>Miffy Hot Chocolate ($8.90++)<br>Kumoya&#39;s popular Belgium Hot Chocolate served with a cute floating Miffy Marshmallow.<br>Another expensive but tasted average drink.<br><br>Splashing Good Fun Japanese Seafood Curry Rice ($24.90++)<br>Fluffy Miffy Japanese rice served with fish kamaboko, cheese stars, steamed broccoli, breaded calamari, breaded ebi, breaded scallop and fresh tempura salmon in Japanese curry. <br>The breaded seafood and tempura were cold and seemed to have been lying for sometimes based on the dryness of the meat. The curry was not served pipping hot.<br><br>Matcha Mountain Azuki Shibuya Toast ($23.90++)<br>Shibuya toast served with fresh churned creamy Hokkaido soft serve, buttery Miffy cookies, fresh matcha cream with fruits, matcha sticks, dango, azuki, crunchy pistachio bits and matcha sauce.<br>The toast was a bit too crispy and dry as it was a bit too hard to cut through. The cookies had turned a bit too soft and not too fresh. The dish got quite jelat halfway.<br><br>Overall felt that the meal was way too expensive with sub standard dishes.

text: Well.. visited the second time for the cute theme again. Their menu are the same just that the food are being decorated with another theme. Food wise is okay still. Visiting maybe it&#39;s just for the theme. Ordered their Smoked Duck Cold Pasta. This time, they also have their merchandise but the plushie was too expensive to get. Just to take nice food photos I guess

text: You know what you came here for and what you&#39;re paying for and it&#39;s not the food. Staff is polite and helpful but not sophisticated servers, don&#39;t expect exceptional service and you won&#39;t be outraged at the prices on the menu.

text: We visited the current theme : Tokidoki Popup Cafe. The decor is absolutely to point! Very cheery and happy feeling. On higher end of most theme cafe. Food presentation one of the best we seen in Singapore. Only accept cash and nets at this cafe.

Ya Kun is Ya Kun. It&#39;s pretty much a Singapore staple for cheap snacks when you&#39;re hungry during the afternoon. Food wise, it&#39;s the typical coffee shop dishes - kaya toast, thick iced milo, soft boiled eggs - served in a slightly more upmarket atmosphere. The decor maintains the traditional basic necessities expected from a coffee shop, though the air conditioning is a great welcome in humid Singapore. Ya Kun is manned by old school aunties who either take great care in serving you, or have a slight attitude. Go to Ya Kun to hang out with your friends when your wallet is suffering at the end of the month.

all you can eat? awesome. all you can drink? AWESOME.<br>this hidden gem in cuppage plaza has great pork shabu shabu. i wouldn&#39;t bother with the beef as i&#39;ve heard that is not quite as good. <br>i enjoyed all 3 cuts of pork that came, although my fit friends did not like the pork belly cut as the fat would detract from their adonis physiques.<br>all you can drink seemed to include beer, hot sake, and cold sake. quality was decent, quantity was superb.

text: The food is average and the only reason to buy food here is because of convenience.<br><br>It is just next to Aljunied MRT so you can just stop to buy your morning breakfast (economy fried bee hoon or noodles) on your way to work/school or to buy your dinner on your way home.<br><br>Besides the many types of noodles available with toppings, you can also get chicken rice here. <br><br>The food used to be cheaper but has since increased.<br><br>If you order a mixture of noodles, they will up the price to $1.50. <br><br>Nothing really stands out here. It is halal. <br><br>You can either dine in or get the food to go.

The Greek', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The Greek'}]
text: This place gives off this cool/hipster vibe, you just wanna sit here, get a cup of coffee and do work on your laptop. They make all the food look really nice, definitely good for a picture. I&#39;m giving this place 4 stars because it was pretty pricey, and the food was just okay. I got the greek which was supposed to be a moussaka, but it was just eggs with tomato sauce, some minced meat and feta cheese. I mean, it was good, but not what I expected from reading the menu and also not the best I ever had. <br><br>I would say this place is good for if you just wanna have chill time, be able to sit down for a while, get a few coffees and maybe if you wanna get some work<br>done too.

text: Went here for brunch a couple of weeks back, was packed even though Singapore is apparently on dorscon level orange, so people&#39;s appetite for brunch is still going strong. <br>Came here with a group of friends, we got a variety of dishes, the standout was the waffle and eggs benedict, as well as the blueberry shake. Ambience is great, service is prompt as well.

text: I went to this restaurant during Christmas time 2015 with my friend at 9am in the morning haha. I remember my friend told me it was the only available time they had that were not booked. I actually think the food was really good. Don&#39;t really understand why the reviews here are kinda low. <br><br>My friend had the NORWEGIAN (eggs Benedict with smoked salmon, avocado and grilled asparagus), and I had the I LOVE NEW YORK(scrambled eggs with smoked sturgeon and sesame bagel). You must be wondering why I remember so clearly LOL. Its because I had the Instagram picture. I also ordered a latte/ mocha I think(don&#39;t remember exactly what I ordered), and it was pretty tasty too. I love the decorations in this cute restaurant too! Many locals came here for food I believe. Mostly young adults and teenagers.

text: Of the many restaurants in the Mandarin Gallery building (Mandarin Orchard hotel) in Singapore, Wild Honey stood out - with its buzzing atmosphere and delectable brunch menu - this is a good spot to enjoy brunch. <br>Not many restaurants in Singapore served champagne and this one had Taittinger on its list which was positive. <br>I had the European breakfast - essentially poached eggs, prosciutto ham &amp; grilled mushrooms on toasted brioche topped with hollandaise sauce. <br>A glass of champagne + breakfast + cappuccino came up to SG$55 so it wasn&#39;t cheap but go ahead and treat yourself!

text: Go early in the morning if u wanna skip the lines. Breakfast is over priced and the food quality has decreased over the years. I like their eggs benedict but so far the menu has stayed the same over the span of 7 years.... not impressed. Still a cozy place to catch up with friends over breakfast

The Italian ($24 after GST and service charge) - 3 stars<br>The portion is fairly small - I was surprised when it arrived with just one slice of ciabatta. It filled my stomach, but I wasn&#39;t too hungry to begin with. There was barely any buffalo mozzarella on it, but ample mushrooms and artichoke. The Italian salad that came with it fit into a tiny ramekin - one you&#39;d use for holding ketchup or a sauce.<br><br>Like I&#39;ve probably mentioned in my review for the outlet at Scotts Square, I like it for the ambience. I love the quirky furniture and plush armchairs. But it&#39;s a much better brunch place at least for me. It&#39;s a bit too dark for my liking at night and almost all the items on the menu contain poached or scrambled eggs, salads, or sandwiches, which I seldom crave for dinner. Having said that, the prices are more suited for dinner.
Good food good service good ambience.  The salad we had was a wee bit too sweet for our liking otherwise all good.  Heading back again next Tuesday.

text: Good brunch place in Orchard. British-style brunch options - our favorite is the classic English breakfast - a simple dish but well-executed. We also like the pancake overall despite being slightly too sweet. Coffee was so-so. Ambience is nice / lively and a good family/friend brunch option

The vibe is great! The brunch menu is pretty nice, a little bit pricey but nice. I ordered the &#34;European&#34; dish and the egg benedicts came perfectly cooked with smoked salmon. Services are fast, from sitting to ordering. Pretty convenient too because the Mandarin Gallery is less crowded than other malls.

text: A very nice brunch place in town.   Came here and ordered the tunisia and alex la sandwich, both food was very good.  Place is nice and cosy as well.

text: Wild Honey is located in Scotts Square upstairs in a shopping center. It was a little tricky to find... but good things come to those who wait. :) <br><br>Calling all breakfast lovers!!!! Wild Honey has a treat for you, and it&#39;s called Sweet Morning. Here is a description of the dish, &#34;twice cooked signature brioche French toast stuffed with grilled mango, vanilla-bean mascarpone, and hibiscus-berry compote&#34; ... Need I say more? This dish blew me away. It tasted even better than it sounds. Very happy I visited Wild Honey.
What a ripoff... Lunch for two, some eggs and bacon with a drink each for $90, you have to be kidding me! Much better places to eat at Orchard.

text: Wild honey was so good! It&#39;s the perfect place to get weekend brunch.  I ordered the waffles and vegan bacon.  (I cheated on my vegan diet when I ate the waffles.) if I go back I probably won&#39;t get the bacon.  It was made out of dehydrated eggplant.  It was more chewy than crispy.  But those waffles??? That&#39;s a must have for sure!  It&#39;s topped with the freshest sweetest mango that I&#39;ve ever tasted.

text: Food is so so only.<br><br>The long black I had is very bitter and acidic. Same for the cappuccino.<br><br>The poached eggs on the Portobello are over-cooked. The yolk is more or less solid and not gooey.<br><br>Music is too loud, not able to hold a decent conversation at all.

I&#39;ve had brunch and breakfast-for-dinner here a few times, and I love the wide range of breakfast plates they have.<br><br>I&#39;ve had the English, Canadian, and Norwegian, and I absolutely love the English brekkie. I am very impressed by their very own baked beans that don&#39;t come out of a can, unlike most places.<br><br>I wouldn&#39;t recommend the Norwegian, just because the eggs are iffy and get cold very quickly. It&#39;s sort of overpriced for just two strips of smoked salmon enveloping two eggs on very thick-cut toast. When it gets cold, the toast feels like cardboard with the weird, cold yolk/sauce on it. <br><br>Canadian - not everyone loves the sweet-and-salty combination, but I do! Pancakes and bacon - yes yes yes!<br><br>My pet peeve on the weekend is the excruciating waiting time for brunch, so go on a weekday for dinner, and book a place online on the webpage. Eat well, and expect to pay!

text: Was not impressed with this establishment. Over priced, and the food is trying to be too trendy but really it failed to please. Don&#39;t waste your money eating here. Service was a little slow, and they are unable to make small changes. I wanted eggs Benedict with bacon instead of salmon or prosciutto and wouldn&#39;t make the change. It was difficult to find as well. Limited menu.

text: Love it ....<br><br>This place offers a wide variety of Breakfast style ..... Late wakers like me still get to taste awesome brunch at any time of the day.<br><br>My Girlfriends treat me Brunch for my Birthday and i heard lots rave about this place. 3 of us order 4 dishes to share as its our 1st time visit. Sounds greedy ya.<br><br>I couldn&#39;t really recall the name of the dish we ordered but when the food is served we are amazed by the portion as its really big.... 3 ladies + 1 young kid finish all the food and its really yummy. The table were alittle to small for us to place our food.<br><br>Please do note that its alittle cramp so pls do not go with big groups like 4 to 8 pax.<br><br>Been there twice till date, can&#39;t wait for my 3rd visit .....

I can&#39;t say I&#39;m impressed with the prices coz it really isn&#39;t cheap.  But the deserts and drinks are quite good and clever.  I just cannot wrap my head around matching the prices and menu items.   But if nothing else, the ambience is sublime!  nice get away from the heat and sit down for a cold beverage before getting onto orchard again.

text: Well loved by everyone, need me say more? The food is good though I&#39;m always pretty disappointed with their eggs benedict cos the egg yolk dont flow! :( But overall taste is good and servings are HUGE. I can never finish a set on my own.<br><br>Compared to their other outlet at Scotts Square, this original outlet is a lot smaller and tables are really close. The last evening my friends and i were there, we could hear 2 guys talk about molecular science topics so passionately beside us. While we werent really entertained (sorry, molecular science isnt really our cup of tea) but we were very happy that they actually found each other having such great interest in a topic that few would really like to talk about over dinner. Isnt that sweet! :)<br><br>They also have a new queue system now so you could key in the no. of pax into this tablet at the entrance of the restaurant, leave your name and contact no and you will receive a e-queue no via your HP. Instead of having to wait at the door, you can roam ard the mall till you receive the phone call when your table is available.<br><br>Till the day i finish all the breakfasts on the menu, every dining experience will be an adventure!

text: OBSCENELY overpriced, fancy food, breakfast only<br><br>I ordered the &#34;Tunisian&#34; - which oddly includes a pork sausage, something I&#39;m pretty sure you&#39;d never find in Tunisia.  It was SGD20 (all prices here are 17% higher for service and tax).  Coffee for SGD6 and OJ for SGD9.<br><br>After waiting 15 minutes, they brought out a &#34;Parisian&#34; - not at all what I ordered.  I was famished and did not want to wait 15 minutes more to get it right, so I got a refund and left.  The Parisian looked nice, not a generous amount... but really, breakfast for SGD35 + 17%?<br><br>I suppose it is culture shock.  Yesterday I had a fantastic bowl of laksa with chicken and cockles for SGD4.5 and no extra charges added.  The problem is finding the local food is hard if you&#39;re not local, and Singapore seems determined to bulldoze the local places and replace them with ridiculously expensive luxury places.  I would have had to take a taxi both ways to eat local, and being hungry, I was looking for a faster solution.

text: Excellent food me excellent service...  When first arriving it gave off a cool hip environment with its modern style and its unique colors. I highly recommend this place to everyone that comes and visits. My wife found this place now it looks like I have to trust her taste in food more often..

Wild Honey does a great breakfast, no matter what time of the day you visit. This is just fabulous for not-so-early birds like me, who can&#39;t get enough of their Caribbean waffles, eggs benedict, or Norwegian smoked salmon bundles. I think they cater to the true Foodie, who has a soft spot for rustic comfort food, yet craves that extra little je ne sais quois. <br><br>The only downside I have ever experienced with this chain is their sub-par customer service, long lines (but you can make reservations at Scotts!), and inordinate prices. Perhaps if the waitstaff were more attentive, I wouldn&#39;t feel as bad hashing out so much dough for breakfast...but they&#39;re not, so don&#39;t expect to be waited on courteously or promptly. If you&#39;re just there for the nosh, then you&#39;re all set!

text: Fantastic breakfast. The NORWEGIAN eggs benedict with asparagus and avocado was amazing. The MEXICAN vegetarian breakfast burrito was also amazing. They should think about a version with meat. The atmosphere was great. The service was drinks was a bit slow but not too slow to make me reduce a star for it. They also have a good selection of teas.

text: Met up friends for brunch at Wild Honey but we couldn&#39;t book a table so we had to wait in the queue. But the good thing is they would text us when the table was ready so we could walk nearby to do more sightseeing of Orchard Road.<br><br>There are a range of Western breakfast from around the world - English, European, Tunisian, Italian, Mexican..etc. As well as sweet and savoury dishes to suit whatever taste buds you have that day.<br><br>I had the egg benedit which was okay but not as good to what I can get in London. I thought the other dishes such as the Tunisian was more interesting. But I found it spicy and not my preference to kick start the day with fire!<br><br>I had the grapefruit juice with my breakfast. It was refreshing and a nice alternative to having the usual orange or apple juice.<br><br>Overall I think it is a nice concept to have breakfast from around the globe.

text: Breakfast is the most important meal of the day. Sadly, it&#39;s a meal most of us go without. The solution? All day breakfast! <br><br>Their meals range from the traditional eggs and bacon to salads to steak sandwiches, and don&#39;t forget the coffees. <br><br>The quality of food is pretty decent. All that you would expect from a cozy restaurant located in a higher-end mall.  Oh and if you prefer your toast thick, then you&#39;ve come to the right place. However, if you can cook a half decent egg on toast, then you might want to give Wild Honey a miss. $20 for eggs on toast isn&#39;t my cup of tea.<br> Just a heads up. <br><br>Expect to wait at least 15 minutes for a seat if you come on weekends.

Wild Honey in Mandarin Gallery is one of these places that seems to be extremely popular with a lot of people and when I finally visit I can just not really get what all the fuss is about. The focus is on all-day breakfast and that is something I am a fan of - we were however here early in the morning as we were meeting friends who have kids waking up early. That also fits well with us believing they do not take reservations, apparently they do that now (they previously only done it at their other location but now also here)<br><br>The style of the place is very much that I would expect to see in an American franchise of restaurants but at least we had comfortable seats. When I started browsing the menu I did find a  lot of things that sounded interesting. The concept of having different types of breakfast menus from around the world is a good one. I tried the English with scrambled eggs, bacon, sausages, mushrooms, breakfast potatoes, grilled tomato and brioche.It was also coming with beans but I asked if it could removed and that they could add something extra of the other things - response was that it was not possible to add anything but they would try to remove it but could not promise. Still decided to go for it and that was a mistake. Bacon was soggy, scrambled eggs felt pre-made and the mushrooms and tomatoes did not feel fresh. Sausages and brioce were however ok. Others around the table were more happy but cannot for sure say if it was a result of lower standards or better food but I will admit that the Canadian looked good.<br><br>For the coffee I ordered a French press and it took forever and then it appeared on the table. My first question was how long it should still brew (when to press it down and pour into the cup) - waitress was just looking at my as if was crazy and said it does not matter and this had been standing around for a while. I tried explaining to her that coffee may taste differently depending on how long it actually is brewed but just got the response that she does not drink coffee. I tasted it and it was just so over-extracted and bitter so it was undrinkable. Had to send it back and instead asked for a cappuccino - that was actually pretty good.<br><br>We also sampled some of the pastries and those were better but nothing special. In general I was not very impressed by food nor service and then taking into account it is hugely busy and prices are a bit higher than other brunch places I cannot really see any good reason to visit again unless I am dragged here with friend.

I love the idea behind Wild Honey, a fusion of breakfast and brunch items from around the world. We ordered three items, everything was pretty good, but the waffle was amazing! We couldn&#39;t get enough. A Belgium waffle, topped with crispy coconut and syrup made from passion fruit. I highly recommend it! Also the service was really good and quick to meet our needs.

I had brunch here once and I loved the concept of this place where they try to replicate breakfast meals of different countries such as American breakfast, English breakfast etc. It is breakfast dishes inspired me from the west. But it works because it has a good variety of choices. <br><br>I had the Spanish hash and I loved it! Although I found it a little pricey I still enjoyed my experience there.

This is an outstanding place.  3rd time yesterday. The food and the service never disappoints. Have tried quite a few things on the menu- Flinder&#39;s Lane,  Norwegian,  Parisienne, the French Toast,  coffee. Always have the Languedoc wine with breakfast and love it. Family came to Singapore and took them there. They loved it. The Norwegian -  poached eggs with salmon was just out of the world.

text: 5 of us + 3 year old boy went for brunch on the last Sunday of 2014. Had reservations so were seated promptly. 2 of us shared the following:-<br><br>EnglishBfast- Scrambled eggs, back bacon, Cumberland pork sausage, sautéed mushrooms, baked beans, breakfast potatoes, grilled tomato &amp; brioche. Everything was delicious esp. the eggs which I usually find quite &#34;heavy&#34; after a while but found these to be &#34;light&#34; although still very tasty. <br><br>Breakfast Hangover-Scrambled eggs, back bacon, roasted pearl tomatoes, Swiss cheese &amp; spicy tomato chutney on grilled ciabatta with breakfast potatoes - tasty!<br><br>Also shared a starter which had fried &#34;sticks&#34; of goat cheese - very tasty.<br><br>My flat white was just perfect as well. We all also had a couple of glasses of sauvignon blanc each which went very well with our meal.<br><br>Extra star is for the good service and de rigueur bustling brunch vibe.

So, I made a pact with myself when I arrived in Singapore that I would not have any western food while there. My friend convinced me that if I didn&#39;t have breakfast here I would regret it. I tell you what....he was right. <br><br>I had the Parisianne breakfast. Three thick cut pieces of ham and cheese stuffed toast with a hollendaise over it. That wasn&#39;t even the best part. My friend had the Hangover Sandwich. I tell you what I never seen a croissant loaded so well.  My buddy had ordered a side of bacon. When it came out it wasn&#39;t the two or three pieces that that the US usually has but a literally boat dish full of fresh cut bacon. The only down side of the experience was it took forever to get our coffees. <br><br>The decor is great. I loved how comfortable the chairs were. The furniture was more chic hipster than traditional which made the whole place jive well.

text: This store has a very homely atmosphere as the cafe comprises a mix of armchairs, normal chairs and benches. Its other outlet is newly opened at Scotts Square!<br><br>The Norwegian is highly recommended with its generous portions and solid ingredients. The fresh sweet smoked salmon is paired with ikura, grilled asparagus and two poached eggs, and drenched with well-made hollandaise sauce and served on two thick whole-wheat challah brioche.<br><br>The Tunisian ($18) which is distinctively Middle Eastern is a must-try here. It consists of Shashouka, and its basic ingredients consist of a thick spicy tomato stew cooked in a skillet. A few eggs are then poached in the tomato stew and it&#39;s served piping hot with some salad and fresh bread.

text: When i first arrived there, i was taking some time to decide on what to eat. I ordered English Breakfast. Portion looks small at first but it was really filling. <br>Moreover, fod is abit overpriced.<br><br>I would have to say the service at wild honey was really bad. Even when i asked for an extra plate, the waitress gave me an attitude.<br><br>I mean like after hearing so many review on wild honey, no doubt the food is nice. But with the service provided there, i seriously doubt i will be back again for their food.

text: This place is pretty fantastic! Being American, I sometimes just miss traditional breakfast food from home. I ordered the Belgian waffles with coconut cream and grilled mango- perfection! I also loved the ambiance of this place, very cozy feel. The only downside is that I wanted to order a side of scrambled eggs and of course because it isn&#39;t &#34;on the menu&#34; they could not accommodate me, even though I could see other dishes contained scrambled eggs in them. Pretty typical of Singapore, pretty hard to get things customized or get people to think outside of the box. But, overall, very positive experience! Be ready to pay though, for two of us the bill totaled 71 SGD.

Great breakfast / brunch food! So many amazing options it&#39;s a real struggle to decide. <br><br>The English Breakfast was the popular choice at my brunch on Sunday, and everyone was satisfied (and stuffed) after eating it. The toast was thick and fluffy, scrambled eggs perfectly done (not too runny, not at all dry).<br><br>I chose the Californian which had a healthy-but-still-yummy feel. The tofu gave the scramble a nice creamy texture (if you like tofu, that is!). <br><br>Also tried the Sweet Morning which was delicious and not too sweet. French toast slices were nice and thick.<br><br>The table got some donuts to share which had raspberry filling. Good fluffy donuts, not overwhelmed by the filling. We were all just too full from our mains to finish them...<br><br>Only downside was the timing of the service... meals arrived spread out over the course of 20 (or more?) minutes. One friend received her french toast at least 10 minutes before anyone else got their food, and my dish arrived 10 minutes after everyone else had already been served. Made for a very disjointed meal. But, have to say the food was good enough to make me want to come back. Maybe I&#39;ll just try a different location next time, and hope we fair better!

text: I love breakfast food.  Just not for breakfast because I don&#39;t really eat breakfast, I eat brunch on occasion, just not breakfast.  <br><br>So, in my quest for a place to have good breakfast food, I discovered Wild Honey.  My process for making the decision to go to a new restaurant is actually quite intense and I do a fair amount of research which involves looking at reviews, yelp and others, blogs, and the restaurant website.  As I took a look at the website for the restaurant (which is very well designed, bravo - you can tell a lot about a place by the attention to detail on the website) I realized there are actually two locations and they both do not offer the same menu, there are some differences, which I didn&#39;t particularly like because it added another decision I had to make.  Ugh, decisions.  I am fairly decisive when it comes to work, but when it comes to my personal life that is a completely different story.<br><br>So, we go to the Mandarin Gallery location.  It is packed, and the wait time at 3 pm on a Saturday for two people is about 30 mins, but they give us the option to sit at the bar area and we take it because we can be seated immediately.  We go in, sit down, gulp down some water, and then go back to the front counter to place our orders.  The week we went they were offering the crab cakes Benedict special, which is called something else I can&#39;t quite remember now, so, my husband, true to form orders that and I finally decide on the English breakfast.  Both turn out to be pretty good choices.  As someone that was raised in Maryland, which is known for Chesapeake Bay, blue crabs and all cuisine which involve them, I am quite the discerning crab cake connoisseur and actually can&#39;t say the crab cakes were what made the meal, but it was good.  The English Breakfast was very good and I highly recommend that to anyone that finds themselves in a situation where they just simply can not decide.  <br><br>In addition to our two entrees, I ordered a caramel latte.  It was a little too sweet for my taste, but that didn&#39;t stop me from drinking it.  Just be prepared for the level of sweetness if you order it.    <br><br>I am not sure if we will go back again, there are so many restaurants to visit in Singapore, but we did enjoy our dining experience and suggest to anyone looking for a good place to have breakfast/brunch food make a stop at Wild Honey (Mandarin Gallery).  Can not say anything about the other location.<br><br>Also, note, if you plan to take away your food because you have leftovers, they do not allow you to take your eggs.

text: This is the place to be in Singapore if you like some of the best food at the lowest prices.  <br><br>Had a traditional Hainan chicken dish, along with a few other dishes, and a lime sugar cane juice, at various vendors around this center. <br><br>The soup and satay were good also.  Wish I could remember all the names of the places I visited, but the food was amazing.  A great place to explore. <br><br>The government gives lower income citizens an opportunity to run the stall, and the government owns the center and the stalls.  Once every three or more months, they close and do a thorough cleaning.  Each stall gets a letter grade (look for the &#34;A&#34;s or &#34;B&#34;s).  Each stall usually specializes in one dish, so mix and match. <br><br>Genius and a great way to try several dishes by exploring multiple stalls.

text: Nice lunch<br>Favorites<br>Healthier salad<br>L1<br>2 salad stores.<br>Lots choices.<br>Best nearby market

My schedule during my trip to Singapore so I was rarely around to try out the different stalls during breakfast and lunch hours (which was when most stalls were open).<br><br>Though I did manage to try two stalls:<br><br>-A Noodle Story: I think it was overhyped honestly. It was like a dry ramen? Maybe I just didn&#39;t really get to enjoy the dish because I had mixed the chili into my noodles not realizing how spicy it would be..but at least the pork belly is flavorful!<br><br>-Char Kway Teow: one man operation. The old uncle cooks, collects your payment, handles deliveries on his own (when I visited during the evening). It was a super saucy dish with lots of oysters too! Not to mention how can 3 sgd be beat?

text: One of my favourite Hawker Center in Singapore, with many award winning options. While the layout can be confusing, once you learned how to navigate the space, you can easily go to the second level for the infamous charcoal grilled Kaya Toasts. <br><br>My favourites stalls are Ah Seng (Hai Nam) Coffee and Ah Ter Teochew. Ah Seng is known for its charcoal grilled french kaya toast. Delicious golden toast with Kaya at the side for dipping!  Ah Ter Teochew has traditional teochew handmade fishball and mushroom minced meat noodle!<br><br>Visit Amoy Street Food Centre for a delicious good time!

text: Amoy Street Food Center is &#34;muther&#34; of hawker food stalls in Singapore.  Located near old Chinatown neighborhood, Amoy has not just one but two floors of food stalls.  Amoy has everything: lots of rice dishes/bowls, soup, noodles, satay, etc. Frankly, everything at the Centre looked good, and validated by the large lunch crowd.  <br><br>Famished after 17 hour flight, I came here during weekday lunch hours and the Centre was packed with locals (which is always a good sign).  I went a little crazy with two meals.  First I had the black chicken soup with rice and the had Teochew fishball soup with mushroom minced meat noodle.  Both were yelp-a-licious and cheap. <br><br>A note to visitors: check the hours because most of the stalls at Amoy seem to be open only during lunch hours 11am to 2pm.  Enjoy.

text: One of my favorite hawker centers in Singapore. They have a huge selection of food styles and cuisines available and you will surely find something that suits your palate. I&#39;ve been here multiple times for different meals and have never been disappointed.
