text: Lots of hawkerpreneur (new generation hawker) here. Weekday lunch time super crowded but this place most stall only opens on weekday breakfast and lunch time. <br><br>Recommend this level 2-157 stall named Gyu Nami<br>Wagyu beef  Donburi for $10 only. The bowl is a bill small and hence lesser quantity. However , food is of good quality and quite tasty. The beef is thin and tender, about 60% cook, just nice. Recommend to try it. <br><br>*Tips: Use Favepay to get 10% rebate for next use. So one person pay with the same favepay account 1 by 1, this way the 2nd person that is the 2nd bowl only pay $9. This way you&#39;ll save $1 for the 2nd person / bowl straight away rather than have to wait for next time coming back to be able to use the $1 rebate. Because you might not come back again before it&#39;s 3 months expiry. Enjoy <br><br>Cheers

text: Great Hawker food experience.  Lots of choices.  I especially liked the Fried Fish Lor Mee from Penang Kitchen.  Wonderful noodles in an excellent umami flavored sauce with crispy delicious fried fish - all for 4 Singapore dollars (3 USD September 2028 exchange rate).<br><br>I also enjoyed a refreshing and delicious iced coffee prepared efficiently by an elderly couple at Xiang Chang Coffee.<br><br>I also had the Fish and Meat ball soup with noodles served by Fishii.<br><br>The Soybean milk at Amoy Street Food Center was the best version of cold Soybean milk I&#39;ve had in a long time.

text: One of Singapore&#39;s best hawker centers! There are a variety of foods to choose from and seating.<br><br>I had the pleasure of trying some fish noodle soup, cendol, and teh tarik from three different stalls. The fish soup had a nice and flavorful broth and huge chunks of fish meat over bouncy noodles. It was extremely filling for a small size and a small price so I can&#39;t imagine myself ordering a large. The cendol was a medium sweet dessert which gave me comfort from the Singaporean heat. I guess I could&#39;ve done without the teh tarik but why wouldn&#39;t I take up the chance to get authentic tea from the Bismi tea stall? The tea was so smooth and delicious I wanted to bring the whole stall home with me.<br><br>It can be super hot in the blazing sun as there is no air conditioning at the hawker center but I would still come back because this was a great experience.

Big hawker center by Chinatown -- two levels with at least as many stalls upstairs as on the ground floor.  Was mostly closed down when I stopped by in the mid afternoon; I did manage to find a noodle stand open (was ok), but not much in the way of cold drinks.  Probably better at lunch or dinner time.  Interesting area around the center.

2 floors of delicious options by a heritage rich neighborhood. 4.5 stars<br><br>Highlights:<br>- Black pepper beef hor fun: looked for the long lines and stood in this one. Loved watching them stir fry it in the big wok. Beef was tender, noodles were fresh, and gravy was peppery. 5 stars.<br>- Carrot cake: this version seemed to have larger rectangles of the rice cakes, bit more sweetness, and eggs more in big pieces than mixed in. Loved it. 5 stars.<br>- Chicken and rice: I&#39;m not a fan of the traditional boiled version and here got the roasted and cha sui versions. Tender chicken was delicious and rice extra flavorful. Cha sui non pork to be halal was a trip with only difference in taste being thinner slices. 4.5 stars <br>- Tonkatsu: my son loves this dish so we were excited for this find. He ate it all and hub said it was good too. 4 stars<br><br>Lowlights:<br>- Layout: hard to navigate with the upstairs and downstairs. Lots of short rows with tables in between so lots of squeezing around.<br><br>Love the hawker&#39;s fare and would be happy to try more here.

Tried the famous ramen mee pok, bak chor mee and curry puffs at this food court.  All were good enough for me to visit again, but not sure I would the extra trip to get there. 30 min wait for the ramen even when got there at opening.  This is a downtown workers destination so very very busy at lunchtime.  The best bite was the ramen wanton.

All I can say is you have to come here! Try the Han Kee fish soup!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'All I can say is you have to come here! Try the Han Kee fish soup!'}]
text: This has to be one of my favourite food centres. It&#39;s a double story building, with many choices of food for your taste bud. My personal favourite is the Han Kee&#39;s fish soup stall at level 2, it&#39;s probably the best fish soup place in Singapore. If you see long queues at certain stalls, you know they are favourites among the office staff. <br><br>Go there before or after peak hours. (11.30 to 1.30) to avoid long queues and frustration when finding seats. <br><br>Place may be quite warm especially if it&#39;s crowded, so be prepared to get &#34;roasted&#34; especially during a hot day! <br><br>Enjoy!

This hawker center has TWO levels! I went at lunchtime and this place was just packed with people. It is a really popular place to eat. I looked around and looked at the stalls on both floors. Noodles, fresh juices, hainan chicken rice, they have everything! I wanted to eat everything but the stall I really wanted to eat at was Noodle Story. Walking around you can tell by the lines which stalls are the best ones to go to. Noodle Story was one of them and it was totally worth the wait. There are tons of tables and seats but it&#39;s packed during lunch. I noticed people leaving a packet of tissues or a lighter or something to indicate that they&#39;ve claimed that spot. So simple, but the system works. Hawker centers are great places to find cheap eats in Singapore, which is great because everything else is so expensive!

text: Lots of yumminess!!! :) As fellow Yelper Julian C. has recommended, the wonton mee and ipoh hor fun on the second floor (second row of stalls from the entrance further from McCallum St) are delicious! <br><br>Ah Liang Ipoh Hor fun, #02-122. $3 for 4 fried fish dumplings (never tasted before!) and a few sad pieces of veg (sigh, I always bemoan the lack of veg in hawker centre food), mushroom. The chilli and silky smooth hor fun went together so well with the crunch of the fish dumplings! Not a huge portion of food, but yumm :)<br><br>Anyway, the wonton mee was pretty good, definitely value for money!! 7 wontons in soup, with 3 fried wontons, and quite a bit of char siew for $3! The noodles I thought were okay, got a bit soggy/chewy (and not really in an al dente kind of way, more like a floury sort of way). Anyway, delicious!! :)<br><br>Of course, long lines at fish soup/fish porridge stalls on 2nd floor - guess they must be pretty good. Also noted long line at char kway teow stall on 1st floor at McCallum St entrance.<br> <br>Also like the fruit juice stalls!<br><br>Bf and coworker recommend the hor fun from the cze char stall on the first floor (somewhere in the middle). Called Good Day. Okay, I tried the beef hor fun from Good Day today (4/3/13) and it was phenomenal! Well, I wish there were more veggies but that&#39;s a constant wish wrt hawker centre food.. Anyway, delicious black bean beef hor fun! $4 gets you a huge portion of noodles and beef.. I usually get a little hungry somewhere in the afternoon but this was so scrumpilicious that I devoured it all and am still full 5 hrs later. The fish hor fun also looked pretty good, but I&#39;ll save that for next time!<br><br>Apparently black pepper beef hor fun from Pepper bowl is good too! But coworker says service is kind of slow..<br><br>I bought a muffin from the Bake Of shop in the third row of stalls (I think). $1.10 for an apple crumble muffin! Really cheap and fairly filling. It was somewhat dry though, but good pieces of stewed apple inside. I do prefer more moist muffins, but maybe this was more healthy/less oily.. Haha.<br><br>More updates since I come here fairly often now - Soon Heng porridge (on the first floor, opposite from Good Day) - has pretty yummy porridge! Also yusheng porridge, which I have yet to try. <br><br>B Salad Kitchen (#01-37) has gd salads for $5! I love their roasted pumpkin and tempeh and sweet potato, mm :)<br><br>Noodle Story (featured on Sunday Life recently) has pretty good noodles and lots of ingredients in it!

Good hawker center surprisingly close to Maxwell.<br><br>I like that it&#39;s 2 stories and I like that it&#39;s just lots of rows of a few stalls so it&#39;s easy to explore and it never gets too suffocating. I had the Char Teow and it was good but a bit too greasy for my taste.

text: Amoy street hawker centre get packed at lunch time but still worth it. I always eat A TER fishball noodles on the first floor. Its so good! I never get sick of it and this is why i always eat a Amoy Food Centre. Even though it&#39;s kind of dirty, you have many options of food here so you will definitely find something you will like. Amoy street hawker centre serves really good food,

text: This is my favourite regular food center in Singapore. Despite its smaller size, it has more great stalls than Maxwell or Lau Pa Sat.<br><br>Favourites are:<br><br>&#34;Cafe B&#34; run by Chef Boris -- Singapore&#39;s best $4.50 pastas done properly al dente and generously sized. Aisle two. <br><br>Chicken rice on aisle three with photo of Lee Kuan Yew visiting. $2.5/3.5/4.5 prices. One of the best Chicken rices in CBD.<br><br>Costa Rican food &#34;Mamacita&#34; on aisle four. Good CR style burritos.

text: This is such an awesome place! I would rate it as the best hawker center in Singapore.  Of course there are other good hawker centers and we can debate endlessly which serves the best chicken rice or prawn mee or popiah but the reason I love Amoy Street Food Centre is the diversity and sheer range of options it offers.  I feel truly blessed to be working in its 5 min radius and so spoiled too!<br><br>For S$5.50 you can get a big bowl of salad (from any of the 4 - 5 salad shops operating there) when the same bowl of greens can easily cost you 15 or more in the fancy cafes around telok ayer and raffles place.  Or if you want something different you can go for costa rican chicken rice with tacos.  It was here I tried my first &#34;lei cha&#34; - the Hakka &#34;thunder tea&#34; which is another healthy choice apart from salad.  &#34;Noodle story&#34; seems to be another recent favorites judging from the line.  And then of course there are the stars of the show - the famous piao ji and han kee fish soup / fish porridge. Lines are quite formidable every day from 11 am to 2 pm so pick your time wisely if you want to try.  Fancy some dessert after your meal? There is Koko Icecream - the popular coconut icecream served in a real coconut.  Or you can venture to the second floor for some baked goodies at Bake-of Muffins at very reasonable price. There are also fruit juices stalls aplenty so take your pick.  If what you crave is Japanese, Thai or Korea they have it too! It&#39;s probably the most international hawker center and the food options itself is a reflection of the changing demographics in Singapore so definitely a great place for people watching as well!

text: This two-storey hawker centre is one of my favourite haunts whenever I&#39;m in the city. It&#39;s smack in the middle of Tanjong Pagar with lots of office workers nearby flocking over for lunch. Needless to say, you should avoid lunchtimes for your sanity&#39;s sake.<br><br>I won&#39;t go too much into detail about the kind of food you can find here, but rest assured that whatever local food you can think off, I&#39;m willing to bet you can find it here. The Thai food here is excellent too, and don&#39;t forget to check out the char kway teow. There&#39;s also a muffin shop which is pretty good.<br><br>Unfortunately, it isn&#39;t that clean. Used cutlery can pile up really quickly during peak periods, and cleaners seem to be in short supply. Plus, Singaporeans don&#39;t have the habit of clearing their own plates, so that makes things worse.<br><br>Also on the downside, most of the stalls close really early, with some shutting down for the day as soon as the lunch crowd disperses. If you&#39;re looking for dinner, you probably won&#39;t find it here.

During our travels in Singapore, a friend recommended that we go to Amoy Street Food Center for lunch.  There were many stalls and it was difficult to choose.  We walked several rounds before we decided which stalls had the longest lines.  We went to the Han Kee stall for fish noodle soup.  I got the fish head noodle soup.  It was very flavorful and did not have any fishy taste.  Price was fair and portion was good.  It actually had a lot of pieces of fish.  They don&#39;t skimp!  I highly recommend this place if you are from the states.  This is something you can&#39;t really find in the states.  Line gets long around lunch time.  <br><br>Amoy food center is 2 stories and there are many options.  Fried rice noodles, chicken rice, wonton noodles, fresh fruit juice, various noodle soups, rice dishes, popular breakfast stall, and deserts.  There is something for everyone.

Just started eating here after my office moved to Robinson Road two weeks back. Love the balance of price and variety of food at this place, definitely better than the other nearby ones like Hong Lim (where you&#39;ll be hard pressed to find Malay and Indian food) and Lau Pa Sat (which is more expensive as its so touristy).<br><br>I would highly recommend two stalls which are next two each other and located on the second floor. The first is a wantan mee stall that sells very yummy wantan mee with uber generous servings of wantans. I got 8 wantans (4 fried, 4 non-fried) for just 3 bucks in addition to my serving of wanton noodles. So, imagine what 4 or 5 bucks can get you.<br><br>The other stall, right next to it, is the hor fun stall whose most popular dish is the fried fish dumpling hor fun. For 3 bucks you get four pretty sizeable fish dumplings, but the hor fun serving is not too big and you might get hungry in a couple of hours time. Nevertheless, still very much value for money. If you love the fish dumplings so much just go on and order a plate of 6 of them for 3 bucks.<br><br>Just a note that both stalls are very popular amongst the regulars and expect to see long queues during lunchtime on weekdays. Both are closed on weekends unfortunately.

text: Amoy St is a great place to grab lunch if you work nearby in the CBD. It is a two storey food center that has every kind of local food you can imagine. Most of the stalls are good. <br><br>My favorite are the ones on the first level. There is a fruit juice stall with a really nice aunty that has many different kinds of fruit juice combinations. The vegetarian stalls on the first floor are also pretty good. My favorite place though is the chee chong fun uncle. $1.20 for a plate of really good and fresh chee chong fun. This place opens as early as 6:30am. <br><br>Most stalls close pretty early though and are not open on the weekends.

text: I don&#39;t know about you but I love black coffee. <br>Taste the latte and flat white are not so bad either. <br><br>Check out the scramble egg on the big breakfast, that runny egg is unexpected but I love it. I had better sourdough though. Sausage is okay too. <br><br>Place is tight and crowded. I like the fact they are freshly bake. Service consider good despite the crowd.

Grain Traders makes for a clean and healthy lunch, but the price prevents it from being an everyday go-to meal like Chipotle can be. <br><br>The system is pretty simple and it&#39;s very well explained. You can choose a ready-made bowl or customize your own with a grain, a protein, one hot veggie and one hot or two cold veggies, toppings, and a dressing/sauce. The gains were very healthy options such as quinoa, brown rice, soba noodles, etc. The proteins all looked very appetizing with options such as sous vide salmon, seared tuna, slow-roasted pork, roasted chicken and a medium-grilled steak. <br><br>The combo I chose was bulgur wheat, sous vide salmon, grilled beets and carrots, charred veggies, topped with furikake and a miso caramel sauce. Delish! Too bad the portion of protein was quite small though, and I was hungry around 3-4 hours later.<br><br>You can&#39;t really go wrong with what you order, but S$16nett a pop makes it difficult to eat here everyday. However, it&#39;s definitely a healthier yet tasty option and could also work for dinner.

Soba + tuna + beets &amp; carrots + bean sprouts &amp; cucumbers + snap peas ($16) - 2.5 stars<br>I like the idea but it is pretty pricey and everything was too salty unfortunately! Not terribly impressed.

text: My newfound love! <br>Healthy slow-cooked meal made fast in the form of westernized mixed rice with price fixed at $16 nett for each bowl. Add-ons are available with prices from $1.5-$3.<br>Choose your grains, meats, veggies, sauce and toppings! My fave combo is brown rice, salmon, mushroom, beans, pumpkins and cucumbers with miso caramel sauce and furikake as toppings. Really delicious meal for lunch &amp; dinner. Generous portion and extremely filling!!!! The place is so spacious as well. You can have your coffee too supplied by Papa Palheta what a nice collab!<br>This branch operates on weekend too!<br><br>I&#39;ve been back 3 times in 2 days. :D

text: Ordered the chicken bowl ($16)<br>When i arrived at dinner time on Sunday, the store was pretty empty and almost all the food had ran out. So i had to go with food i didn&#39;t really want as they had ran out of the ones i wanted. Portion was quite small and for $16 i think they would serve more protein and sides. I was still hungry after my meal. Also, the staff was pretty unresponsive and unhealthily for a first timer. Food tasted pretty good and home cooked and healthy.

text: Prices are not cheap, felt that only the meat were probably a little bit special, the sides such as veg and rice etc were normal. Got this because of the hype queue during every lunch hour. Wouldn&#39;t go back actually.

This is the &#34;chipotle&#34; of bowls.  Lots of choices for people seeking low carb, high protein and veggie dining option. My review will focus on these options. <br><br>$16 gets you quinoa or salad as a base. Several low fat protein including salmon, tuna, and lentil.  About a dozen cold and hot veggie options.<br><br>Perfect for after a workout.

They started the hype and it&#39;s probably here to stay. Still one of my favourite go to spots for a healthier lunch option offering a good selection of restaurant level selections for you to mix and match. With the likes of Daily Cut right around the corner though, I would only wish they could lower their price just a bit to contend with the almost negligible difference in quality.

If you&#39;re tired out by the buzz of orchard (like I was), this place is a nice hideout. Good chill music coupled with comfort food. Don&#39;t mention their ice cream, it&#39;s heavenly. You&#39;re welcome ;)<br><br>Oh, did I mention? It&#39;s also halal. Now I&#39;m tucking into my Mac and cheese and laughing at all rushing around after work. This is the ultimate place to curl up with a book and escape the rain as well.<br><br>That said, it is 6.30 on a Wednesday.

Set upon a lush, peaceful backdrop of the reservoir, this place as a sleeper vibe. Staff was super attentive. The fish tacos and waffles are good. Decently prized and portions are not measly for Singapore&#39;s standard. Get your face into their fish tacos and ice cream waffles, they&#39;re good! The rendang burger is average.<br><br>Positive vibes and them treating customers like friends won me over. Definitely supporting this small business!

text: We stay in the area. The food is great, I love it. One of the reasons I come here is their selection of &#34;craft beer.&#34; The reason I&#39;m marking Burp low on this rating is because they don&#39;t replenish their stock of actual craft beer. The past 2 times I&#39;ve been, they have been out of stock on 2 out of 2 IPAs that they advertise on their menu. They deserve a 4 out of 5,  but will not get that to me until they up theirs craft beer game.

text: Burp Kitchen &amp; Bar? That sounds filling already. When I heard that they are located in the East, I was even more excited, because the east side is my &#39;hood. Less than 5 months old, their bistro is situated at a quiet corner of a bustling area (nearer to Bedok Reservoir), well known to residents around who probably shops at the nearby Sheng Siong supermarket. <br><br>The host shared that being in a neighbourhood area, they also do not believe in charging for GST and service charge. That&#39;s definitely a plus point for me. :)<br><br>I loved the healthier airfried chicken wings they serve up, as well as nice burgers. I like the crabby patty burger, most of my friends like the burp beef burger. Most of what they can make in-house, they do. At least they try to make it more healthy for their patrons! They also serve brunch, so thats cool!

text: The zi char here is pretty decent (though not the best 5.5/10) and affordable. Love the salted egg bittergourd though its a little soggy but still, its a must try if you love anything salted egg. I&#39;m not a fan of their sambal kangkong as it felt overcooked. Another list worthy dish, their claypot crab noodles.

text: I don&#39;t know why people gave this place such bad reviews. In my opinion, it&#39;s just another Starbucks. Situated in the middle of a busy mall, adjacent to the convention centre. <br>Got my much needed morning caffeine fix from here and it was pretty good, albeit a bit on the weak side - but I think that&#39;s an asian thing (I thought Taiwan coffee was weak, but Singapore Starbucks is worse), but the coffee wasn&#39;t burnt, and the foam was fine and moist. &#34;Latte with extra shot&#34; was an actual item on the menu so guess I&#39;m not the only one who thinks their latte could do with more of caffeine. I&#39;ll know to order that next time!

text: Starbucks is usually a great place to meet people and have a nice cup of joe in the process. However, this Starbucks is not the best place to meet up, if you don&#39;t want to be seen. It is situated right in the middle of Millenia Walk where all your co-workers can easily spot you, particularly if you work in Suntec or one the nearby office towers. In short, don&#39;t schedule an interview or meet your headhunter here. ;D

text: Mr Bean has started to venture into exciting flavours that will tease your taste buds in case you know, you get bored with the whole soya thingy.<br><br>Besides selling WASABI beans in a packet, they&#39;ve recently launched a Apple Pie Sundae. THIS IS YUMMEH. You&#39;ve got to try it. It tastes like the insides of the McDonald&#39;s apple pie all laid out into squarish cold versions and added onto the soya bean ice cream. And on top they sprinkle some random peanuts or something that really adds to the texture of every mouthful. It is a wonderful concoction of intense sweetness and fresh flavours. <br><br>We liked it so much my colleague asked the counter girl (Kelly) if she could get only the apple pie without the soya bean ice cream. Kelly - whom by the way has excellent service every time we visit - was so worried about her sugar levels, she said &#39;But it&#39;ll be so sweet!&#39; Amusing.

Eastern wind food house', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Eastern wind food house'}]
text: I just stumbled into this one and it wasn&#39;t until I crossed the road that I realized I was wrong to assume Eastern Wind lacks an English translation of the Chinese characters Tong Fong. However as an outlet still operating on the &#34;5 ft walk&#34; (as in overflowing into the street) on Joo Chiat road it is hard to miss.<br><br>The manager, usually behind the drinks counter is a friendly man in his sixties and is proud to offer &#34;better than average&#34; coffee and tea.<br><br>Managed for the past 10 years in this building the set-up has always been simple and straight forward. The space is also home to a Vietnamese hawker stall, one of any in the area, and a seafood stall. The word to pass on is that the buttered crab and the fish head are both dishes that need to be tried.

text: Date/Time of Visit: 18th Dec 2012, 4:20pm<br><br>It&#39;s a Starbucks. They have prided themselves in almost identical standards of service and F&amp;B not only throughout the countries but in the region.<br>I&#39;ve always enjoyed the Starbucks Experience as most of us would call it. <br><br>There were, a couple of kinks with this outlet at The Central though.<br>1) The barista asked me if I wanted to &#34;upsize to a medium&#34;? I mean, it&#39;s a small kink, but seriously? Did you jump over from CBTL or something?<br>2) I ordered a Dark Chocolate Log Cake for my girlfriend. I&#39;m not exactly sure what it was supposed to be like. It was way too mushy, and looked like it was condensed out of vaporized chocolate fudge. Not sure if many will like it.

Ordered an Americano and it is nothing compared to the Americano in the states. It&#39;s disappointing because most Starbucks in the other countries are very consistent to the US. My coffee tasted nothing like coffee, just like tea.

text: Friendly server who attempted to make small talk and actually smiled.<br><br>I only wish their coffee tasted better. The latte I had was way too weak. Not sure if it is my imagination or did they used to serve a much better cup of coffee.
Quick service. Iced coffee hit the spot on a sunny humid afternoon. Thanks for the consistent quality. Clean bathrooms. Quick service. Staff were on point!

This is one of my favourite Starbucks outlets in Singapore and it has recently been refurbished. I like it primarily for the ample space, comfortable armchairs and large windows by which you can sit and people watch for hours.<br><br>On the negative side, this Starbucks appears to have some of the slowest service I&#39;ve encountered on the island. This is a problem because during the day it is often jammed with office workers. The poor bastards have to wait for 10-15 minutes to order their caffeine hit before scurrying back to their cubbyholes. Come on guys, speed it up!

text: I found this place in one of those random older malls that you find in Singapore, where the stuff inside is lower quality goods that you wouldn&#39;t normally find at normal malls, and with a ton of restaurants and random food stalls.<br><br>This place though ended up being quite tasty. I had the rendang beef, and I was quite surprised how flavorful and pleasant it was. You go in and choose your main course in a buffet like area, and then add some vegetables on top for the meal set.<br><br>The coconut roll deserts were quite good as well. The food overall had quite the Indonesian flare to it, and was overall good and fairly priced.

text: A little easy to miss as it is located around the back of Bras Basah Complex, somewhere near Food For Thought . The food court is one that opens for 24 hours, so it&#39;s pretty shiok to be able to grab a bite at night if you&#39;re around the area - say if you&#39;re clubbing at Loof. <br><br>In terms of the seating and interior, it&#39;s pretty clean as far as food courts go.<br><br>My friend claims that one of the popular stalls is the Japanese one, which sells really good Otaku Don. So we went there after working at the National Library and my friend convinced my other friend to order the don. I chose the salmon teriyaki and chicken karage bento set - my friends loved it, except the &#34;miso soup&#34; which tasted a bit like sewage water. I&#39;d recommend this dish if you have to eat at this stall. As for my friend who order the Otaku Don - it looked nothing like the picture - very bleak, and he hated it . <br><br>Still, you  cant expect much in the way of Japanese fare at at food court - I&#39;d just recommend the salmon teriyaki + chickebn karage bento... you&#39;ll be safe.<br><br>The desserts : I got pulut hitam and cheng teng... very mediocre, - the pulut hitam was very watery and had no substance. I wouldn&#39;t get either dessert again.

text: My husband and I were walking around Dempsey on a Sunday, wanting to try a different place for lunch. We were in the mood for burgers, and although we heard Huber&#39;s Butchery serves some good ones, we weren&#39;t interested in eating al fresco because it was so frikken hot!<br><br>Hungry and desperate for air conditioning, we spotted Go-Go Bambini and liked what we saw on the menu. In addition to burgers, they also had salads and pizzas. Walking in we were a bit confused- why are there so many children here and OMG that&#39;s a huge playground! (Then my Italian brain popped in- bambini means children... ah, I see what they did there.)<br><br>I think Go-Go Bambini&#39;s concept is genius here in Singapore, and I&#39;m surprised there aren&#39;t more places like it. It&#39;s a family friendly establishment in upscale Dempsey that allows children to run around freely in an indoor playground as the adults chow down on gourmet food offerings! Of course, they also have a children&#39;s menu, and all items from it are served on durable plastic plates and cups so nothing breaks.<br><br>My husband ordered the GGB (go-go bambini) burger, which is basically a bacon cheeseburger topped with a fried egg. It&#39;s quite epic, and good if you&#39;re super hungry! I had the cheeseburger. I found it juicy and well seasoned. I also liked the fries that came with it.<br><br>If I could change one thing, it would be the glass sizes for adults. They served us water in what could be a considered a big shot glass in certain bars. Since you pay when you order, the staff didn&#39;t really check on us after our food was served. We had to work to flag them down so they could refill the glasses for us.<br><br>Other than that, this is a nice spot to check out. If you&#39;re single, don&#39;t let the children scare you away- the food here is worth checking out!

text: I like to share my first experience with my grandson at Go Go Bambini on 14/08/18. I accompanied my daughter &amp; my baby grandson of 7 mths plus &amp; was in the play area for Toddlers aged 3 yrs &amp; below.Practically the place was a sorry site.There were very few thngs to play.Th drums set &amp; other musical instruments had strings that were really short even for a 3 yrs old to play let alone a 7 mth baby.There was no pit ball  as shown on the website. I spent more than 1 hour in the area as no other toddlers were interested to play there.They came ,saw the place &amp; ran off.I don&#39;t blame them,there was nothing of interest for hat age.  We spent an entire time to ourselves &amp; no other toddlers of 2or 3 yrs came to play as they were all more interested in the pit ball area for older kids .I hope there will be more improvement for added useful toys &amp; a pit ball for the younger toddlers .

text: I&#39;ve never heard of the Saintmarc Cafe brand; apparently it&#39;s a huge chain in Japan. We discovered this place as we were walking around East Coast Park (which by the way, has a ton of new eateries that need to be Yelped!)<br><br>We were drawn into this outlet because it looked super new, spacious, and it was operating during the first day of Chinese New Year. Looking at their brunch menu, they had a good mix of dessert-like breakfasts and savoury pastas.<br><br>The matcha pancakes piqued my interest. They were described as 2 pancakes with some red bean sauce and a dark brown sugar syrup. For about $10, I wasn&#39;t expecting much but was surprised at how thick the pancakes were. I definitely couldn&#39;t finish them; it&#39;s a dish best shared with someone! It&#39;s also a good choice if you&#39;re looking for something that&#39;s not too sweet.<br><br>Service still needs a bit of work, unsure if it&#39;s because they&#39;re still training staff. Although our server repeated our order back to us, someone managed to enter one of the dishes incorrectly and we were initially served something we didn&#39;t order. They even suggested that that&#39;s what we marked on our sheet, but we were able to show them that it wasn&#39;t the case. Also, they charge $1 for a pitcher of iced or warm water, so this place will not sit well with those who hate charges for water!

Just simply not food people.  Strange texture of spaghetti.  Noodles basically has a texture of one of those korean style noodles?  Totally not worth the price u pay if u can make better with instant ingredients. Hopefully their dessert is still good.  Sadly this is a cafe that will not last too long if this keeps up.

Excellent!!!  If you love ice cream and or homemade DELICIOUS things, THIS is it!!<br><br>I wanted to bottle up the honey comb topping and bring it home to Seattle, it was so perfect. <br><br>The ice cream is very creamy and the waffles fluffy and crispy (though two was unnecessary).  The toppings are generous and SO great.  Fresh marshmallows, where have you had fresh marshmallows at an ice cream shop?!  <br><br>The only regret I had was we went here a couple days before we left so I couldn&#39;t enjoy it more than once.  With the heat and many humid days, this was an amazing experience I wish we had close to home. <br><br>It is also VERY air conditioned in here.  So much so I had to move tables to comfortably enjoy my frozen treats. <br><br>Service was very polite and portions are indulgent, so plan to share or eat it for a meal. <br><br>Side note: The Hawker stall at Holland Village was the worst of any I had on the island (really the only bad one but it was REALLY bad).  I would opt for a restaurant if you want something decent in the area.

text: Because there is always space for dessert! went on a Tuesday evening at around 7:30 and there was still a line. It was quick though, took us 10 minutes of waiting before  we got sested. Order and pay at the counter, and they will serve you your food. Food wise - the lavender earl grey soft serve ice cream is THE BEST and their waffles are great. My only complaint is the loudness inside the store. By virtue of it being so popular, the tables are packed such that I was back to back with another person and it was hard to move around at all in the store. I would say the soft serve and cakes are definitely worth it only if there&#39;s a short wait.

text: The cafe was by the people behind creamier. Instead of ice cream, the cafe specialized in soft serve. Only cash and NETS payment was accepted here. Help yourself to the water from tap from the counter. This christmas the cafe offered 2 limited desserts and 3 dessert sets.<br><br>Winter Yuzu Ice Cream Trifle (S$12)<br>Limited to 10 servings per day<br>The dessert used Japanese Yuzu which is a lemon sized fruit with a distinctive, delicate citrus perfume, in season during winter and traditionally used in Japan during the winter solstice. Layered with soft sponge cake and citrus cookie crumbles, the rich indulgent taste of the Madagascan Vanilla ice cream contrasts with the citrus zing of Yuzu gel and light acidity of fresh strawberries. Crowned with a stalk of fresh edible Shiso hanaho flowers. Freshly prepared upon order.<br>Looked simply pretty, it tasted with a zing.<br><br>Pistachio Chocolate Ice Cream Gateaux (S$12)<br>A double layer of dark chocolate and roasted pistachio ice cream with a red berries sorbert surprise. Encased within an intense bittersweet dark chocolate shell and bedecked with a dallop of Varlhorna Azelia ganache, gold flakes, burnt caramel rice puff brittle and crushed roasted pistachio nuts.<br>A mixture of flavours in the mouth with the rich creamy ice creams, and the intense sorbert.<br><br>Lemongrass Cucumber Infusion ($6.50)<br>Rehydrate with this refreshing infusion packed with chia seeds, fresh cucumber peels and lemongrass.<br>Tasted like the usual lemongrass drink but with the crunchy chia seeds.<br><br>Best come early. Although it was just noon, the place was packed.

text: Decided to check out Sunday Folks on a sunday rainy afternoon at 3:30pm. I managed to find a parking spot along the limited parallel parking spots on the road alongside sunday folks. Free parking on sundays! Yay!<br>The minute you step within 10m of the shop&#39;s entrance, you see a snaking queue of people seated and standing outside. This iPad system is what greets you at the entrance, and it is your enemy!!!! Based on your party size, it will tell you roughly when, you will get a table. Enter your phone number.. walk back to your car and take a 60 minutes nap.<br><br>45 minutes later and HURRAY!~ The iPad system will text you a link that queries your queue number.<br>We finally got a table about 50 minutes after we had entered our particulars into the iPad.<br><br>Sunday folks isn&#39;t very big, still bigger than Creamier but it can be quite loud as the tables are placed quite closely to each other.<br>Walk up to the counter to make your order and you will have to make a choice between waffles and cakes or BOTH! Which is what I ended up ordering!<br>Hipster cafe menu.. gotta love the super tiny font.<br><br>1. Matcha Cake $7.90<br>I loved every bite of this cake, it was so moist, soft and the cream wasn&#39;t too sweet. You could taste the green tea bitterness in this cake. For $7.90 it was a taste of heaven!<br><br>2. Seasalt Gulamelaka waffle with lavender konnyaku jelly and caramel popcorn $15.20<br><br>Here is what I was waiting 50 minutes for, an extremely &#34;instagrammable&#34; waffle. You have like seconds to maybe 1 minute to snap all the photos you want, before the soft serve melts and vapourizes!! I loved the taste of the sea salt gula melaka. You can definitely taste both sides of this soft serve!<br><br>The caramel popcorn and lavender konnyaku jelly were beautifully decorated around the plate. The jelly had a strong lavender taste and I enjoyed the chewiness of them all. The caramel popcorn was a great choice, to offset the saltiness of the soft serve.<br><br>And the bill.. shared amongst 2 adults and a 4 yr old, I think it was okay, I wouldn&#39;t say sunday folks is cheap. Not to mention, you&#39;re gonna need to patiently wait around 45 minutes for a table.<br><br>**Free parking on sundays! If you can parallel park!! because if you suck at parallel parking,..... everyone outside sunday folk will be watching you!!!. Sorry.. but it was a fact that someone sucked at parallel parking and everyone starred at the poor kid in the Z4.

text: If you like going to places that specialize in 1-2 things rather than offering a wide range of choices, Sunday Folks is your place. They specialize in Belgian waffles and homemade ice cream, both of which are distinct and close to perfection. Ingredients are fresh and beautifully presented. <br><br>Sunday Folks has one of the longest queues in the holland village area, but they make the wait less painful by having you check in and calling you when your table is ready. There are several cute shops and cafes nearby that you can kill time with. <br><br>Would definitely go back to eat the Earl Grey Lavender ice cream again!

text: I thought going for waffles at 9.15pm was a brilliant brainwave. Turns out more than 50 other Singaporeans had the same idea as me, and my family and I were faced with one of Sunday Folks&#39; infamous queues. Thanks to people leaving and opting for takeout, we were seated within 15 minutes. Hurrah! <br><br>We obviously gravitated straight to their waffles and soft serve (gula melaka with sea salt and roasted pistachio flavours). I threw in their sticky toffee cake as well for good measure. Their closing hour was met with a rush of teenagers getting takeout ice cream cones so it took a while for our order to be served. <br><br>Full marks for presentation. There is a reason why their waffles are so popular on Instagram. The plates look like works of art, with the toppings scattered prettily along the side. They have even slid a charcoal wafer between the ice cream and waffle to keep the latter warm and fresh. I love the thought that has gone into this and it really shows. <br><br>Taste wise, the gula melaka&#39;s flavour wasn&#39;t as strong as I was hoping. I definitely didn&#39;t taste the sea salt either and this was a big let down. With every other ice creamery in Singapore offering this flavour, SF needs to step it up on this front. The pistachio fared much better and was devoured quickly (after the requisite photos had been taken from ALL angles obviously). <br>Their topping game is strong. Wide and varied selection from chocolate honeycomb to granola. An additional topping doesn&#39;t even cost you much extra. <br><br>As for the sticky toffee cake, it is forgettable. The sponge was alright but when you think sticky toffee you think gooey, caramel goodness. In comparison, the cake was dry sans the bit of syrup they had trickled on the top. Disappointing slice. <br><br>Regardless, will definitely give it another try, at least for their gorgeous waffles.

text: 3.5 <br><br>Came here at 4:30pm on a Sunday afternoon after a late brunch and it was nearly empty. I guess we were lucky though, bc just half an hr later after being seated, the line started to form out the door! Located amongst the shops of one of our favorite streets in Holland Village, this cute cafe boasts a cute minimalist decor and beautiful signages written in calligraphy.  <br><br>We ordered their popular homemade Caramel sea salt Gula Melka ice cream with waffles (double). From the name, we wrongly assumed that it&#39;d be two scoops of ice cream and one waffle, just the way we preferred it, but it was actually one scoop of ice cream somehow balancing on top of two waffles.  The ice cream fell sideways shortly after digging in, soaking the waffle and melting fast on the plate. Minor complaints though, the waffle and ice cream were both decent, and the price tag justifiable at around $8~12 depending on the size you get. <br><br>But given its popularity with the long wait, it was just okay. It&#39;s not a place we&#39;d wait over five minutes and crave regularly. will come back though on date nights, as there are not enough good cafes in the area!

text: Seeing the queue, looking at the menu, I thought this was another one of those hypes that would just die and just a part of some crazy Singaporean thing in going to a place as long as there is a queue.... <br><br>So I decided to try this place immediately after work on a Thursday - meaning I was there about 630pm. No queue. There were people but not overly packed. Looked at the prices and it was not as crazy as I though it would be. And because it&#39;s a weekday, they had tea sets. So among the three of us, one tea set (coffee plus cake of choice) and of course, their waffle. <br><br>I went to the counter to order (since I&#39;m generally the crazy one when it comes to ordering food, the other two would just follow instructions...). Asked for their best seller and was told it was the lavender and tea thingy or the caramel sea salt with Gula Melaka. Ordered the Gula Melaka with two waffles, and asked them to recommend a topping. Best seller topping of honeycomb and ... Err... Can&#39;t remember but it was really good! When paying though decided to change the ice cream flavour seeing that the people I was with may not be as adventurous. Settled for strawberry instead. Choose Yuzu tea cheese cake for the set. <br><br>Coffee was nice. Yuzu tea cheese cake was a lighter form of cheese cake (not as dense as ny baked cheese cake, but not as light as the mousse or jap cheese cake type. I like!) but friends were saying that the tea taste is not strong enough, which I have not agree. Love the texture though. <br><br>The waffle - presentation win full points. And I would like to credit the person who put so much thought into this. All the toppings were places on the side, so as to not dampen or soften the waffles. The waffles were hot and o-so-delicious on its on. The soft serve ice cream laid on top of a chocolate coated thin wafer - purpose to prevent the ice cream from melting, and keeping it away the hot waffle but at the same time making the whole plate looking so yummy. This wafer also allowed you to move the ice cream to the side, while being able to eat the waffle and ice cream together without messing up the rest of the plate. And enabling you to enjoy the warm waffle (yes, took too many pics and appreciating the waffle that is is now warm instead of hot) with the ice cream. Kudos to whoever who gave so much thought to this :)    <br><br>Definitely going back, would love to try their cone and their signature soft serve ice cream flavours. <br><br>P/s strawberry flavoured soft serve was a delicious choice!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/7PvRoaG8oUz_wrlxtOwggg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/sunday-folks-singapore?reviewid=7Dxfx2iHLW1nzfSF_-HpOg&select=7PvRoaG8oUz_wrlxtOwggg', 'altText': 'Photo of Sunday Folks - Singapore, Singapore. dark chocolate soft serve (with toasted marshmallows, caramel popcorn, chocolate drizzle)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'dark chocolate soft serve (with toasted marshmallows, caramel popcorn, chocolate drizzle)'}]
text: Finally there&#39;re no longer hipsters and excited girlfriends dragging bored but placating boyfriends lining up outside Sunday Folks...now I can consider this for more regular, low-key visits! Previously I was one of those that once waited 2-3 hours for the waffles topped with soft serve ice cream. (Or let&#39;s be real, the main point was to get photos of those beautiful painstakingly plated dishes.) When I was there from 1pm+ earlier today (Sunday), there was no wait at all and plenty of empty tables. <br><br>Founded by the folks behind Cremier, Sunday Folks in Chip Bee Gardens is a little more upscale and trendy, and of course pricier as well. It&#39;s the type of place to hang out with friends, not quite the place to read a book and enjoy some solitude. The waffles - crispy and perfectly browned - are most popular, but tbh you can make good waffles in your own kitchen if you care enough to. The toppings include creations like lavender jelly, gula melaka mochi, toasted caramel popcorn, etc and adorn the waffle dishes very attractively. <br><br>The stars to me are the subtle, inventive soft-serve flavours. The earl grey lavender and sea salt gula melaka are the standouts - I personally love the floral, light taste of the earl grey ice cream. The sea salt one goes very well with the waffles. I tried dark chocolate today, served in a cone with toasted caramel popcorn and marshmallows ($7.90), and it was nothing very special. <br><br>The cakes looked good (when do they not?), and I may try them along with the coffee the next time I visit. The only complaint/slight inconvenience is that they provide free tap water, but the fancy bird-shaped tap only releases water at a trickle. So you&#39;ll see many people waiting patiently for quite awhile just to fill a teeny cup. <br><br>I&#39;m betting Sunday Folks will continue doing well in the years to come, and give the Daily Scoop some good &#39;ol competition!

text: Confused this place with Daily Scoop (at the same street).<br><br>It was pretty crowded when I stopped by here on a Saturday evening. We had to wait for approximately 1/2 hour.<br><br>We ordered the Earl Grey Lavender soft serve with waffles, almond flakes and konnyaku jelly. The soft serve melted quickly. Was expecting it to have stronger taste of earl grey or lavender but unfortunately it was mild. The waffles was alright but the jelly came in generous scoops and it did give the dish flavors.<br><br>Will give this place another try.

Matcha cake and mocha afternoon tea set ($10)<br>The matcha cake is light and flavorful but there&#39;s too much cream. 3.5 stars. The mocha was good, but do note they only have whole milk - no soy or low-fat milk. 4 stars.<br><br>The soft-serve ice cream is terribly over-priced though. 2.5 stars.

text: This is a really cute ice cream place. I was living in Holland Village during my work assignment to Singapore. Found out about it while walking in the neighbourhood and decided to try it out.  Tried the Earl Grey Lavender ice cream, and the Sea-Salt Gula Melaka on my second. Both are good, but I&#39;d recommend the Gula Melaka. The ice cream is always served with toppings. <br><br>The place is always crowded especially on weekends. People actually wait in line to get a table. Just have it to go and enjoy it while walking in the Holland shopping area.

text: I had their waffles with Sea Salt Gula Melaka ice cream and also tasted my friend&#39;s Earl Grey Lavender ice cream.<br><br>The waffles is nicely made with just the right amount of saltiness. Goes vey well with the maple syrup and chocolate hazelnut sauce drizzled on the peripheral of the plate. <br><br>The sweetness of the gula melaka ice cream was a good complement to the savory waffles. The earl grey lavender ice cream is lighter in flavor- very floral and had a nice tea taste. I preferred the heavier favored gula malaka ice cream for the waffles! The earl grey lavender ice cream might be nicer as a stand-alone in a cone.<br><br>The waffles also came with small pieces of strawberries and blueberries. They did not go well with the other items on the plate as the taste (sweetness/sourness) of the fruit pieces was a bit too strong. I ate them up after I had finished my waffles.

text: Irresistible soft serve ice cream. <br>I now understand why Sunday Folks is so popular. The interesting ready mix ice cream with topping is a full meal in itself. I particularly enjoy The pistachio flavour. Not many places can make good pistachio ice cream that doesn&#39;t taste like essence but this was pretty light and fragrant at the same time.<br><br>Want something more? Try the waffle! Paired with the popular ice cream, they really make a great dessert. Looking for brunch, tea or just some supper snack, try Sunday Folks! Don&#39;t forget to also check out the quaint neighbourhood as they have other pretty interesting things around, like the Monocle Store.

text: Came here on a Saturday around 4 pm, but saw quite a long queue (30 mins wait) so decided to walk around the area and go try somewhere else. However by 6 pm, there was no queue at all and in face there were like 5 empty tables. So decided to stop by to see what the raves are all about.<br><br>To enjoy the ice cream on a cone or cup is S$7.20. You&#39;d get to pick one of these 6 flavors (Summer Strawberries, Roasted Pistachio, Earl Grey Lavender, Madagascar Vanilla, Sea Salt Gula Melaka, Dark Chocolate). One of the employees told me that the most popular flavor is earl grey lavender, the second one is sea salt gula melaka, the third one is roasted pistachio.<br><br>The person I came here with already tried the earl grey lavender and roasted pistachio. Cos we were gonna get something to share, so we decided to get sea salt gula melaka instead. Just fyi, the ice cream here is soft serve style. We wanted to eat it with the waffle.<br><br>To buy only the waffle is 8.00, but to enjoy the waffle with ice cream of your choice with petit size (single size) waffle, you just need to top up 80 cent more which I think is definitely worth it. I am picky when it comes to the waffle&#39;s texture and taste and I think Sunday folks nailed it. However, the ice cream taste wise I&#39;d say that it turns out to be very disappointing - judging that sea salt gula melaka is the second best seller, I don&#39;t expect it to be SOOO sweet to the point it made my very very thirsty and has quite bitter after taste :( I think I&#39;d need to give a second shot for this place to try their other two best sellers. Maybe I&#39;d change my mind then.

text: Finally!! Try some dessert place: sunday folks is just a couple miles away from holland village MRT.. This place serve you waffle ice cream and also nice taste of lemon cake.. U have to try this one!! Not to sweet..just nice!!

I have been hearing about this place for so long and personally been there 3 times but could never get in because there was always a long line and finally one time when there was no line, we found the place closed at 4pm for a private event. doh...<br><br>anyways this time i was determined to get a table and delighted to find that they have installed a new queue system for easy management. after you get your queue number, you will be notified by phone call when your table is available; they share the same system that&#39;s being used by a mookata place in katong so i found myself being recognized after i put in my cell phone number. the wait was an hour so i stayed comfy by hanging out in Phoon Huat next door instead of melting in the humidity on a Friday afternoon. to be fair i bought birthday candles in exchange for the AC.<br><br>the service at Sunday Folks was great throughout and we even got a special plate of dessert because it was New Years (so sweet of the lady bosses). but i have to say they do have awesome soft serve ice cream and waffles - we had strawberry fields and gula melaka. Delicious!! waffles were crispy and they stayed that way because the soft serve were served on a piece of biscuit to prevent soaking the waffles while you take your time in snapping pictures. smart! we paid extra for toppings but it didn&#39;t really make a difference because there wasn&#39;t much of it to see or taste or even remember about. i wish they gave us more toppings for what we paid.<br><br>I will return for sure but hopefully on a day when the queue isn&#39;t long.

Waffles and soft serve were cool five or six years ago, so I was skeptical of the place. Thankfully Singapore, you&#39;ve proven me wrong.<br><br>This is an evolved version of the waffle-yo I used to get circa 2009--this is the upgraded, hipster version. They even have birds as decor (re: Portlandia &#34;Put a Bird on It&#34;). The waffle/soft serve combination is like chicken/waffles, most places excel with one and ignore the other, but Sunday Folks is spot on. The waffles are cooked to a golden brown, long enough that they&#39;re firm and stand up to the weight of the soft serve. These cooks are smart, there&#39;s a wafer between the waffle and soft serve that prevent melting and sogginess.<br><br>The soft serve flavors are creative without sacrificing taste. I will definitely come back to have more.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/J6d82Y2nn1ocuWY8xjDJew/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/sunday-folks-singapore?reviewid=nL0YI_QpWQ8lgpLdpr66QQ&select=J6d82Y2nn1ocuWY8xjDJew', 'altText': 'Photo of Sunday Folks - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: For a type 1 diabetic who had a low blood sugar that turned me ravenous, this place is great. But seriously it is one of my new favourite spots in Singapore. The cakes were fluffy and fresh. While the ice cream was some of the best I have had since Messina in Sydney. One word Go! You can see care is put into the desserts here.

Definitely get the waffle here WITH the ice cream. We tried the earl grey lavender and the pistachio ice cream. They were both good, but I prefer the earl grey ice cream. I just wish they were more generous with the toppings. <br><br>Be prepared to wait to get seated. We waited almost an hour for 2 people.

Oh why oh why did the management decide to sell soft serve ice cream? Is soft serve the new hipster? Is making me pay for high overrun (i.e. air) and water the latest in dessert trends? Are operating costs too high to use more quality double cream at $11.80 a pop (waffle + ice cream)?<br><br>I had such high hopes as this place hails from Creamier (Toa Payoh) fame. Creamier&#39;s waffles were paired with delicious super-premium handcrafted ice cream - Earl Grey, Pistachio, Sea Salt Gula Melaka, Black Sesame, Lemon Yuzu, Satsuma Imo and more, countless wonderful flavours backed by a rich and thick texture with excellent mouthfeel.<br><br>Alas, Sunday Folks only offers soft serve. Do not like. Soft serve affect flavour. Soft serve melt too quickly on warm waffle. Soft serve like cheap McD&#39;s cone.<br><br>I would have given them the full 5 stars had they only served the same super-premium ice cream from Creamier. It wouldn&#39;t matter that Sunday Folks carries only 6 flavours since the waffle itself is still decent, and they also have cakes (not available at Creamier).<br><br>But instead of choosing to rise above the height of all their competitors since Daily Scoop and Island Creamery (in Holland Village), Sunday Folks has chosen to fall into cost-cutting darkness with all that is left of their kin.

text: A dessert store!  A dessert store in Holland Village! Fresh churned ice cream, homemade cones, really gourmet toppings, waffles for dessert with all of that delicious CAKE.  It&#39;s a sweet tooth&#39;s heaven, really.  My friend and I had two slice of cake--I had a matcha roll cake, which sounds like not much but was actually AMAZING.  Perfectly spongy with the lightest sweet cream in the middle.  My friend had the butterscotch banana cake, which was also phenomenal. All around I saw people ordering fresh made waffles (so fragrant) topped with their fresh churned ice cream.  <br><br>Standard drinks also available but this is a great late night treat!!

text: Nice cozy place for ice cream, cakes and coffee. Ice cream topped with a choice of fruits and nuts. Great range of cake to complement with their frozen yoghurt and coffee. Unfortunately the crowd is just too overwhelming at the moment,  so can be rather trying on your impatience. Service although not too fast, is generally pleasant.
The Belgian waffles were well made and served warm so it was still crispy on the outside and moist in the inside. Goes very well with the hula melaka ice cream which I tried :)

I am very torn about this place. The price is painful; $13 for two small slices of waffle with ice cream and no additional toppings. The waffles are not very good; they end up being too crispy and tasteless by the time you get to them. You get a meagre serving of fruit on the side and they are oh-so-conservative with the chocolate drizzle and maple syrup. The redeeming quality is the ice cream. The earl grey lavender ice cream was stupendously good and rescued this cafe from being another over-priced 3-star joint.

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=72C5Ctf5HBhbaTwNDYf5kg', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Aurora B.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Aurora B.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=72C5Ctf5HBhbaTwNDYf5kg', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 0, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 2, 'eliteYear': None}
text: Read about the long queues but it must have been a lucky day for my band of merry folk, we simply strolled in. The place was crowded, noisy and cosy... if this combination is even possible. Lol.<br><br>Had the sea salt gula melaka ice-cream on waffles, dark chocolate (iirc) ice-cream on waffles and a slice of the yuzu cheesecake shared among 4 after dinner. The ice-cream was smooth and flavourful, the waffles was crispy on the outside but soft on the inside (not your floppy pancake-like waffles a-la Polar Cakes). Don&#39;t get me wrong I love-love-love my Polar Cakes waffles with peanut butter. Even though we started with polite nibbles, we were all soon attacking our desserts in earnest. You should see the how cleanly we mopped up the melted ice-cream puddles on our plates! If you think the yuzu cheesecake was blah because there was nary a mention, you are sorely mistaken. It was dense, the yuzu flavour was evident, the cake was on the whole delightful but it played second fiddle to the waffles simply because you are talking about a group of ice-cream mad folk + the waffles was way more visually appealing. We&#39;ll be back for sure.

text: I love their breakfast special - thin clear noodles, egg, porky hash brown patty, cabbage - $3! Thank you, Attap House!

Good selection of all-time favorite comfort food. Quality is good, portions are ok but you may need to order a side dish if you&#39;re extremely hungry. I have tried the curry chicken, which was OK.  Colleagues had pork chop and fried rice, which were also good.<br><br>The tables have barely any space in between, and the acoustics are not good, so expect to hear other conversations while barely able to have one with your friends.

text: A nice, air-conditioned shop amongst this not very air-conditioned area of Joo Chiat Road!<br><br>You can find a mix of food, medicine, and beauty products here. A lot of the products are from Indonesia and Malaysia; knowing a little Bahasa could help so you can read some of the product labels. <br><br>As this is an ethnic store, you&#39;ll see items like camel milk coffee, super spicy ginger tea, and herbal remedies native to Asian countries. I&#39;m very new to these types of products so I always get excited when I see them! I also found the display of Middle Eastern dates quite enticing.<br><br>Great place to take a break from the Singapore heat if you&#39;re walking up hipster Joo Chiat Road!

text: The service here is quick and efficient while a bit unfriendly, but as expected for such a high turnover place. <br><br>Got the combo with the (i) kaya toast with better, (ii) poached eggs and (iii) milk tea. The kaya toast with butter is my favorite. I love the balance between the savory butte and the sweet kaya. As much as I would like to, I don&#39;t think I could eat this everyday given the amount of butter thats in it. The poached eggs were good, but a bit cold/lukewarm. I would prefer it if it was warmer. <br><br>Overall, I really enjoyed Kaya toast and this is definitely the place to have it.

text: This is one of the busiest Ya Kun Kaya Toast&#39;s location I have been to especially during the morning breakfast rush.<br><br>Quality definitely not as good as even the eggs are prepared ahead with the busy turned over of the business. My poached eggs were a little overcooked and lukewarm. <br><br>The Coffee though was served hot and fresh.<br><br>Since the turnover is so fast here, it is easy to get a table. Great location near Bugis MRT!

text: This was one of the first places I had yong tau foo and even though the first time I had it was probably 10 years ago, I can still fondly recall the taste of the soup when I first drank it. It was something new to me but I really enjoyed the food.<br><br>That was the first of many occassions where I would go back just to eat the yong tau foo. I even brought my family to try one day and they loved it as well. The selection of ingredients is quite normal but it really is the soup that makes the dish special. Its flavoured wonderfully with the soya beans and not overly salty.
Good seven item noodle open early morning  coffee next door thick and flavorful.   It&#39;s kind of in a food court on the bottom corner of Katong

text: I love this chain from London and was excited to hear that it was here in Singapore. Of course you get the peri peri chicken, it is just a matter of what size and heat level. For me and my sister we ordered the 1/2 order of chicken with cole slaw and chips (fries) as well as a side salad. We get mild and that is pretty tasty. They also have 8 different sauces in the front that you can choose from. <br><br>My niece got the children&#39;s meal which was a good portion of chicken breast, rice and veggies with apple juice. The apple juice has little aloe bits which I enjoyed and the rice tasted like this Vietnamese rice (xoi). Chicken was actually very moist which is difficult for chicken breast.

I really like the Nandos at Bugis MRT but this one can&#39;t compete with it. It&#39;s the same name and also the menu is the same but that&#39;s about it.<br><br>We came in nobody is interested, we sit at a table still covered in dirty dishes no one cares, we ask to clean it and bring us the menu, we get funny looks....  It went on like this. The food was good as expected for Nandos, but the appetizer only made it after the main course and our inquiry.<br><br>I will eat at Nandos again, as I like the food. But won&#39;t come back to this one, as I expect a bit more from the staff then funny looks....

text: We stopped in for dinner after doing a quick trip to Tanglin mall last night. We ordered a full chicken meal (mild) with 2 sides for $43. We settled on veggies and the sweet potato mash. Food was good, service was prompt and the place was clean. It fit our Paleo needs, but we still prefer Caveman Food in Novena.

text: This is a pretty good Coffee Bean &amp; Tea Leaf.  What this location has going for it is that it is nicely situated on the lower level of Orchard Gateway. From this, you are well protected from the elements.<br><br>What is nice about this location is that it has some good seating. It has several individual tables as well as some couch type seating. This is ideal if you are with several of your friends.<br><br>The service here is pretty good. Of course, there away seems to be a person who gets the order wrong but that is what can be expected at one of these locations. The one thing I think is nice is that if they do mess up your order, they are very kind and apologetic about fixing it. <br><br>What is also nice about this place, particularly in the morning, is that they have a nice selection of foods. In fact, they have several very nice breakfast sets. I would recommend checking this place out, to have a nice morning latte and one of their breakfast selections.<br><br>Overall, pretty good place. Nice place to grab a latte, some other drinks, a small meal, or a snack.

text: Not a big fan of CBTL anymore as they often don&#39;t have my favorite drinks: Chai Latte.  And even when they do, sometimes it&#39;s a tea bag which tastes very different than if it were an extract or brewed.  Not sure what they are thinking but they make it anyway without informing and I often have to cancel and get my money back.  A complete waste of my time.

The Tiramisu here is horrible. Dry and super sweet. Try it if you like being disappointed. This branch of coffee will be closing for good tomorrow so maybe they didn&#39;t replenish their cakes with fresh ones. Awful.

CBTL started in the early 60&#39;s, even before Starbucks.  I go here when I am travelling, and want something different from Starbucks but still a dependable taste of home.  I like this place, convenient when visiting.  Their coffee and tea are good, and I know that whichever location I go to I will be treated about the same.  The only real difference in locations is some have a different vibe, some are staffed a bit more generously than others, you need to find one that fits you.  This one is great for me, because it is close on Orchard road, generally hasn&#39;t been over-packed (at least the times I go), even given the location.

text: Everyone was telling me to go to this small breakfast/lunch spot as it is known for its amazing food. I went there for breakfast and it certainly didn&#39;t disappoint. It was pretty busy and after I ordered it was hard to find a table (but luckily one opened up!). <br><br>Due to the corona virus some places were blocked for people to sit on, they also changed their utensils and plates to throw away ones as it would be more hygienic. They did choose utensils that were sourced sustainably which I thought was nice as they did not forget about the environment. <br><br>The service was good and the food was just amazing. Would recommend the pink lemonade for a nice refresher. I am excited to go back!

Sangaria milk shake and milk coffee', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Sangaria milk shake and milk coffee'}]
text: After buying our breakfast buns at Crystal Jade My Bread nearby, we came here to get some drinks to go.  Ooohh...  a huge store full of Japanesey stuff!!  But at Japanesey prices.  :(  Everything seemed a bit expensive, but I suppose that&#39;s the norm for authentic Japanesey stuff.<br><br>We got Sangria milk shake and milk coffee.  The bottles were pretty pricey at $3.50 for the coffee and $3.00 for the shake, but it was worth it to try something new.<br><br>The shake tasted like egg nog, and the milk coffee was a standard milk coffee.  Both quite sweet.<br><br>I saw green tea Kit Kats at the counter and was really tempted to pick them up, but I resisted and saved a few calories and dollars so I could pig out on something else later.  ;)

It used to be that only when you visit Japan could you buy super cool stuff like green tea Kit Kats or multi-flavoured Ritz crackers... Now you can save on that plane ticket and just spend it all here. Yes, I did say spend it all here. I actually think it is possible to do that. <br>I used to be that guy marvelled at all the cool Japanese snacks friends would buy as souvenirs after coming home from Japan, or on the odd occasion that Takashimaya had a Japanese snack sale - come on, how do you not marvel at all the creative things they put in food!? Pudding flavoured biscuits? Check. Wasabi flavoured soda? Check. Oh there&#39;s so much more. Sometimes I thinking about stalking the shelves to see what stuff they can come up with... they don&#39;t call me &#34;adventurous eater&#34; for nothing.

Take my money and give me the calories!<br><br>Ahem. <br><br>So this is my go-to spot for Japanese snacks, such as made-in-Japan (or rather made-for-Japan) Pocky, Oreos, etc. Now that even NTUC sell seasonal editions of Kit Kat, Yamakawa Super is still a good place for all sorts of stuff. Currently I have in my office pantry 2 versions of chocolate-chocolate McVities, as well as cheese-candy. Strange and strangely moreish. Do take note that a) things are expensive (the McVities were $4.50 for a pack of 8 pieces) and b) a lot of the stock is seasonal or limited edition, so those those sea-salt McVities may never come back again.<br><br>There are also drinks, including tea (my favorite genimaicha tea bags!), canned and bottled drinks, as well as a small selection of savouries (crackers, furikake, soup mixes). Come explore!

text: Ya Kun is not just an outlet or a joint, but a collective entity, like the Borg, but in a good way...goooood Borg. <br><br>While it had  considerably more modest  and decidedly traditional and humble beginnings as a hawker stall in a local coffee shop preparing and serving local breakfast fare; runny eggs which you&#39;d slurp clean off a saucer after dousing with dark soy and white pepper, and Balsa light sheets of a toasted local loaf slathered with kaya(sweet coconut jam) inlaid with bright yellow chips of cold butter, it has morphed into an entity that is permanent part of the Singaporean gastronomic consciousness.  <br><br>Ya Kun is as ubiquitous as the Golden Arches and as recognizable.  But also stop to consider that this is a chain of restaurants or fast food joints that serves food that punctilious food-crazy Singaporeans would consider good and worth their time and coin.  You see, in Singapore fast food is not necessarily bad food or even mediocre food. Expectations are no lower just because you may not have sit down service or table linen, in fact expectations may be higher!<br><br>Simple, tasty, and inexpensive cuisine is so pervasive in Singaporean culinary culture, that nobody thinks twice about expecting good food from a chain restaurant.  Ya Kun is certainly no exception and has continued to serve up what it does best, traditional comfort food quickly, hygienically and in an environment where diners can relive fond childhood food experiences in air conditioned comfort. Add a touch of business savvy and an effective marketing and franchising strategy and you understand why Ya Kun has become a  Singaporean institution and a pioneer in one of the possible evolutionary paths for Singaporean hawker culture.<br><br>I adore Ya Kun for serving up food that makes me feel good. It&#39;s not just that the food tastes good, the flavors are so true and traditional that it instantly brings back fond childhood memories of mornings in a neighborhood coffee shop tucked behind a shady five foot way, it&#39;s cavernous interior redolent of carmelized coffee beans cooling after being roasted with margarine and sugar, and the feel-good miasma of toast hanging thick all about you.  Thank you for the memories, Ya Kun!

I was unimpressed by my kaya and eggs here (one of my favourite foods). The toast was slightly cold and the amount of kaya was minimal, normally I like lots of spread with thick slices of butter. The eggs were alright although slightly too stiff for my liking. Best kaya and eggs in my opinion are still served at Changi airport!

I didn&#39;t like Black the first time I tried it because the drinks were quite average. In fact it was kind of watered down. I gave it a shot more recently and found it alright. Well, at least it&#39;s better than your regular Starbucks. Plus it&#39;s hard to get a seat at the more popular cafes in town, especially on weekends.<br><br>Black does some breakfast food, sandwiches and scones to cater to the working crowd at Somerset. It&#39;s not fantastic. Actually, don&#39;t get the food here. Get it from the imperial treasures bakery next door. Then get your coffee and chill by the glass windows. <br><br>Black is an average cafe but I would go back to when I want to sit down at somewhere quiet, without the noisy kids, and do my work. PowerPoints are available too.

Cappucino.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Cappucino.'}]
text: This cafe is conveniently located within the shopping area of town so you may find it easy to pop by for a pitstop at a slightly quieter part of town. <br><br>I ordered a capp which came in a nice black cup (naturally) and two cookies. The capp was alright, not particularly outstanding. I heard that their other branch at Hitachi Tower does better coffee too. So there.<br><br>I also tried on different occassions their lemon bar and red velvet cake. I mustn&#39;t be running very good lucky with this spot because the red velvet cake I had on my first visit was rather dry and crumbly. Their lemon bar had a slight tartness to it which I found pretty enjoyable.<br><br>I&#39;m quite sure Black has their fans but I&#39;m not quite convinced as yet.

text: This open-spaced joint located at the first floor of 111 Somerset just as you enter the mall, has some very charming vintage furniture and decor. You can see old tv sets and you could be sitting on a very vintage 70&#39;s furniture your parents or grandmother probably once owned. There is also a nice huge board behind the counter with the menu hand-written on it. <br><br>Besides the decor, the food and drinks were not as charming. I had the green tea latte, while it looked really beautiful with the latte art and all, the taste didn&#39;t quite match it, I found it quite bland. Also had the red velvet cake, it seemed like its been in the chiller for awhile, wasn&#39;t the best.<br><br>Final verdict: It doesn&#39;t feel or taste as good as it looks!

It is pretty much a no frills cafe serving Malaysian food. The chicken rice with rice balls were nothing fantastic. The chicken curry mee was not too bad though there were probably better versions out there. The only dish I liked was the popiah. It did not fall apart when picked up with the chopsticks and the chili and sweet sauce made it taste good. <br><br>The coffee and tea were strong and decent.

Very bad wanton mee.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Very bad wanton mee.'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/on9drUwzOcdLUlVrnlgVLg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/the-old-malaya-cafe-singapore-2?reviewid=cj_cL5GNKck2YK_-LilujQ&select=on9drUwzOcdLUlVrnlgVLg', 'altText': 'Photo of The Old Malaya Cafe - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Tragic.<br><br>Located in the basement, and decked out in the style of an old-school Malayan / Singaporean cafe. It has shutters that have no view as it&#39;s in the basement of a shopping mall, and fans that rotate even though there is aircon. If they&#39;d put half the effort of decorating the place into the food, it might still be save-able. Unfortunately not.<br><br>I have tried the pontian wanton mee twice and was sorely disappointed both times. On both occasions the wanton was stale and cold ... not lukewarm, but cold. The noodles were dangled limply in some way-too-salty sauce and the vegetables were half-cooked. I left my uneaten plate of noodles there and tried to wash it down with a teh - o peng (not bad) .<br><br>My sister who was with me and ordered the pohpiah hated it as well. <br><br>Verdict: Avoiding forever.

This space is incredibly quirky and I feel like they need better pub.<br>A Malaysian brand &#39;theme&#39; restaurant, walking it is a series of unexpected surprises.<br><br>When you first step in the space looks almost like a kids playpark, step further into the dining area and the first thing that caught my eye was an entire corner decked out as a bridal studio! Gowns, mannequins, flowers, and cutesy stuffed toys... After I sat down I then realised there was also a live band setting up!<br><br>The decor feels like a combination of a maid-cafe, garden themed restaurant, and bridal studio! Apparently it&#39;s also a wedding hall. I hope so, since they don&#39;t look like they do very well on walk-ins for the cafe part of the space.<br><br>I was just meeting a friend so I can&#39;t comment on the food, but service was polite, and the space was just so charming!<br><br>Really hope to come back in the future! :)<br><br>OH AND THERE&#39;S FREE WIFI! :D
