text: This Starbucks outlet will forever be special to me. Why? Because this was where I bumped into a Bollywood superstar, Hrithik Roshan -- 12 February 2011. A fellow Capricorn who&#39;s a Starbucks lover like I am. *sighs*<br><br>...Anyways! I am impressed with the services here so far. But nothing unique here, really. It&#39;s your everyday Starbucks. Though it&#39;s easy to spot as it&#39;s located just beside the escalators at the basement. It&#39;s also near another exit which I find to be quite convenient if you just wish to grab and ciao! <br><br>Seats are a bit tough to get since they&#39;re almost always occupied. Never had the chance to actually sit here before. *pouts*

Drink of choice is usually an iced soy caramel macchiato. I rarely drink hot drinks in Singapore for obvious reasons. Starbucks at Paragon is really a place you come to grab a drink and go. It&#39;s hard to find a seat here. If you really want to sit to rest from the shopping or grab a slice of cake, it&#39;s best to head to Bakerzin, TCC or PS Cafe. <br><br>Starbucks is usually buzzing with people who are people watching or working on their laptops so chances are you&#39;re not going to have a table vacate while you&#39;re around. That said, its location just beside the escalator means that you aren&#39;t going to walk far to get here from the rest of Paragon.

This is truly a tiny place but what it lacks in size they make up for in quality of coffee and friendliness of staff/owners. They can perhaps seat a handful of people and I have actually seen some people sitting here although I would not say it is the place to hang out for longer periods of time.<br><br>They use beans from Papa Palheta and when I have been here these have been put to good use and the espresso based beverages have come out really well. They sell nice bottled cold brews (if they are not sold out) both black and with milk. The black ones are my favorite and they are really good, even compared to the stiff competition in Singapore.<br><br>They also serve some simple food, mainly hot sandwiches to take out as well as some really nice looking fresh fruit juices. A great place for a caffeine fix on the go.

text: A quiet and affordable cafe to chill at/study especially on a weekday! Check out their set lunch/students deals or their occasional fave vouchers which make their meals really value for money :)<br><br>Had the aglio olio with tiger prawns while my friend had the chicken steak aglio olio. I&#39;d recommend just getting the original one without prawns or get the chicken one if you&#39;re a fan of chicken. The chicken aglio olio comes with a generous serving of chicken chop, while the prawn one was served with three small prawns at the side. Though it&#39;s listed as &#34;tiger prawns&#34; on their menu, it did not taste much different from the frozen prawns you&#39;d get from the supermarket. <br><br>The coffee here is average, and better options are available in the vicinity with the wide array of cafe choices in the Somerset/orchard area!<br><br>Overall, worth visiting if you happen to be nearby/come around during lunch hours/are a student!

text: Recently FoodPanda had added this restaurant as one of the choices in its list of restaurants which it offered delivery. And there was a promotion code &#39;FPCOFFEECLUB15&#39; which gave a discount of $15 with minimum order of $30. This promotion was limited to the first 300 orders. I placed an order at 11am for a Buddy Meal ($25.90+), which consisted of 2 mains and 2 drinks, with topup of $2.90+ each to upgrade the drinks. There was also a delivery fee of $3, with 7% GST in the bill. The order was accepted by the restaurant at 12noon and food was finally delivered to me at 1pm.<br><br>Baked Yakiniku Chicken Thigh ($13.90+)<br>Chicken thigh baked in Yakiniku sauce, mashed potato, steamed broccoli.<br>The chicken was a bit dry and the mashed potato tasted like the instant type, but the sauce made up for it.<br><br>Garlic Prawn Pasta ($15.90+)<br>Sauteed pasta, prawn, Asian pesto and chilli flakes<br>There was juicy prawns and tasted quite garlicky, but also a bit quite oily.<br><br>Ice Cold Brew ($5.90+)<br>It came in a bottle with syrup in a small container.<br><br>Iced Vanilla ($5.40+)<br>The milky drink was rich and milky.<br><br>Overall the the food was not bad. Servings were just nice.

text: Horrible experience at O&#39;Coffee Club @ Seletar Mall: Prepare to WAIT for your breakfast for 40mins or more!<br><br>The service I experienced here on July 29, 2018, Sunday morning was horrible beyond words. Waited 40mins for my breakfast to be served because the kitchen, waitresses served the order to another guest who came later (the second incident in my third visit). While waiting I asked the waitresses about the order, the waitress replied &#34;not sure&#34; &#34;being prepared&#34; and never bothered to check with the kitchen what went wrong. Finally I raised my voice then another waitress explained the orders got mixed up. The staff were not apologetic to apologise or make up to customer for the mistake made (that explained why I ever saw angry customers walked out without settling bills).<br><br>Avoid O&#39;Coffee Club at Seletar Mall if you do not want it to ruin your day. ZERO star for customer service at this O&#39;Coffee Club.

text: Nice and cozy cafe. Serve western and desserts like waffles and ice cream. Few selection of waffles which can be mix and match flavour of waffles. Great place for family and friends. Mini games like scrabble, boards games and more. Try out their butter beer, superb.

Unlike my counterparts, I&#39;m one of those who doesnt go crazy over chocolate. I&#39;d pick vanilla over chocolate any day.. but that doesnt mean I dont appreciate chocolate from time to time. <br><br>Similar to Terrence L. mentioned, Lana used to the epitome of a cool birthday cake. Not sure what&#39;s the Lana equivalent for kids these days, but if I had a choice, I&#39;d want my birthday cake to be a cheese cake, ice cream cake, or Lana&#39;s chocolate cake.<br><br>Yes, it made my list. Lana existed way before awfully chocolate ever did, and I may be biased, but I think Lana&#39;s chocolate cake is still better than the ones by Awfully chocolate.<br><br>Definitely call them up and order your cake, then pick it up from the shop on the day itself. You&#39;ve got to try it to believe it :)

text: The most overrated cake in Singapore. I have been on a journey trying out different chocolate cakes islandwide and LANA, although the &#39;OG&#39;, proved to be the biggest disappointment. It&#39;s rather dry instead of the moist, and dense quality you&#39;d expect of a chocolate fudge cake. It feels much like a chocolate chiffon cake similar to Swee Heng&#39;s Chocolate Fudge ($5) cake. Especially with the horrible texture of the fudge. The chocolate lacks in taste and feels more like a jelly than of a sinful fudge. I thought the hefty price tag of $55 for 800g would be worth since many has given it the title of the best chocolate cake, but it&#39;s nothing more than a rip off. I saw that only 4 years ago, they were charging $39 for the 800g, the price difference is monstrous. Would rather buy multiple Swee Heng cakes if I like that chocolate jelly in my cakes or buy from better stores like Choc-a-bloc or even that $20+ Qoo10 cake.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Wq7d7a9M56PtJKrPl_lKiA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/lana-cake-singapore-3?reviewid=QLyZxxqWvpFdvvtyOFYe3A&select=Wq7d7a9M56PtJKrPl_lKiA', 'altText': 'Photo of Lana Cake - Singapore, Singapore. $52 for 1 kg, $2 for the wording', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': '$52 for 1 kg, $2 for the wording'}]
text: The last time I had Lana cake was years and years ago. Having a sudden craving for it, fueled by the news that she was selling off her recipe, I decided to try to get a cake. I called and couldn&#39;t get through so I dropped by to see if I could get a cake and found out that you have to make an order 7 days in advance. They&#39;re closed on Sunday and Monday. <br><br>A bit later I decided I&#39;d order a cake for Mothers&#39; Day and called 10 times on a Tuesday (at 11am, 12pm and 3pm) before finally getting through around 5.30pm. $52 for 1kg, $2 extra for any wording on the cake.<br><br>Fortunately, pick up, two weeks later, took 2 minutes and the staff were friendly.<br><br>Unfortunately, the cake just wasn&#39;t worth the hassle. The bottom layer was dry and the cake just didn&#39;t live up to what I remembered, or the general hype. Since you can&#39;t walk in for a cake, it&#39;s not the place to satisfy a craving, and if I were ordering a cake I&#39;d go elsewhere. The chocolate heaven cake from Lynn&#39;s Cake is better in my opinion - it&#39;s more moist - and you can get one large slice for $5.50. Get it for the nostalgic value I suppose, but not much else.

text: I came in yesterday to buy a cake since I heard the original owner is retiring. <br><br>Cash Only.<br><br>You need to order this at least a week in advance, and I think they are getting more and more backlogged so now that wait is up to 10 days. <br><br>I ended up with some remnant cake that they had - some kind of walnut, chocolate, raisin, date cake. I absolutely did not want it, but since I just walked from Farrer Park station in the sweltering heat, I was leaving Lana&#39;s with a cake either eay - I would have paid someone else walking out of the door, even.<br><br>My date cake was absolutely awesome and delicious - it was so smooth and just the right amount of everything - 5 stars all the way. <br><br>What was not five stars was the lady&#39;s attitude who worked there. It was ATROCIOUS. So high and mighty she is, selling cakes, that she cannot even be bothered to answer questions. Let alone, listen to them. You can sell five star stuff but if you do not have a shred of decency you don&#39;t deserve five stars. <br><br>Others who have reviewed have talked about their terrible attitude going way back a few years. I can imagine that this was not a one-off thing or the recipient of someone&#39;s bad day. It is ingrained.

When I was a little boy, every birthday party I&#39;ve attended had a Lana Cake. It was the epitome of cool, a sign that your parents love you, and that they knew what they were doing. Now that I&#39;m a grown man and I&#39;ve been weaned off chocolate cake, I still reminisce the times when life was simpler and all I did was run around and had cake.<br><br>One thing you should note, the staff are not the most pleasant. So suck it up and sink your teeth into a little piece of nostalgic heaven.

I&#39;m actually attempting to hand carry this bloody chocolate cake all the way to China for my boyfriend&#39;s family.<br><br>That should tell you how amazing it is.<br><br>Lana&#39;s is the cake I missed when away in America studying. It&#39;s the cake I had for my birthday every year starting with your 1 month celebration (which of course I couldn&#39;t eat but still). <br><br>When I have kids, I just really hope Lana&#39;s cake is still around so I can pass this tradition on to the next generation. BWHAHAHA.<br><br>Awfully chocolate&#39;s cake is good too btw, but that&#39;s a whole other review :P

text: Favorite cake shop now run by the legendary Mrs. Kwan&#39;s son who has returned to Singapore. Operations have been modernized and (hard to believe but true) cake quality and consistency have gone up! Mrs. Kwan can be found now at the front of the shop greeting customers and chit-chatting rather than hidden away baking.

I used to study in the area and my mum would pick up cakes from here for special occasions or just because she felt like it. Usually, we would get their famous chocolate cake or carrot cake and it would be snatched up almost instantly at home. While Lana Cake has been branded as &#39;over-rated&#39;, I would beg to differ. Beyond sentimental value, there is something special about their chocolate cake that I still enjoy. <br><br>While it could definitely be more moist, I enjoy their use of a lighter sponge cake over the heavier cake base most cake shops go for. Chocolate in itself is already a very heavy flavour, particularly with the dense fudge that is about to be laden on top, so it would be sickening if the cake was just as rich too and &#39;moist&#39; in its higher density. Rather oddly, their fudge, made with a secret recipe, has a slightly gelatinous texture which makes it more enjoyable. I also like how their cakes tend to be less sweet than cakes from other places and taste distinctly home-made. Its direct competitor, Awfully Chocolate, has the closest tasting chocolate cake similar to that of Lana&#39;s and though the texture of the fudge is right, there is what can only be described as a &#39;plastic&#39; taste.<br><br>It is clear that I am still a fan of Lana Cakes, but be warned that the staff are not very pleasant at all and to check the opening hours before going. Also, calling in beforehand and booking the cake you want would be a good idea.

Wow .. it seems like we have many well off / spoilt brat Yelpers in Singapore who grew up eating Lana Cakes every year for their birthdays (since 1st month, no less). Well, unlike other reviewers, we never had that many Lana chocolate cakes growing up which was quite odd since we live 3 mins. away. Too much of a good thing makes u nauseous I suppose. All said &amp; done, yes the cakes are really good &amp; I&#39;d pick them over Awfully Chocolate anytime (hello Made in Johor but retail at the same price, seriously .. chocolate my ###). I remember Lana&#39;s blueberry cake was also very good, we ordered it one year for my Dad&#39;s birthday, &amp; I&#39;m sure they still make it - I might give it a try again soon.

Old school chocolate cakes! Lana cake shop is the best. <br><br>Delicious and moist and the right amount of sweet, their chocolate cakes are what entire generations have grown up on.<br><br>You need to book the cake on the phone and pick it up on an appointed date. That would be best.<br><br>You&#39;d also be in for a bit of a scolding: the people behind Lana cake shop know they&#39;re the best, and can be quite diva-ish :) The amount of abuse we go through in this country for good food of any kind.

I practically grew up eating the chocolate cake from here. It was and still is a special birthday treat for my family. You would be hard pressed to find anyone in Singapore who has not heard of Lana cake shop, it is that famous. Perhaps there are chocolate cakes that taste as good or even better out there, but for me there&#39;s just that extra special ingredient in there - a dash of nostalgia.

Everyone has to grow up having lana chocolate cake for their birthdays. I used to be jealous at my sister&#39;s huge dog shaped chocolate cake, but as I grew up, I realised the shape doesn&#39;t matter. When it comes to buttercream, the small details, no one beats Mrs Violet Kwan. You might not think it matters, but it does. I want to eat cake, and every bit of it, even the cream. The salty creamy texture of the buttercream at Lana means I can dig into it without picking out anything. So their cakes a old-fashioned with different flavours along with buttercream. Blueberry and walnut is really good. <br>Cake eating is great, but what I enjoy most is just going into the cake shop. I love seeing the rolls of purple ribbon and seeing the veterans tying up boxes swiftly and beautifully.<br>Not only just to see what they have left for me to take home other than their chocolate cake, I love taking that gold cake slice box with a piece of rich fruit cake. It is by far the best, and I&#39;d have gobbled it up during the car ride home, feeling very contented, like a 10 year old all over again.

As any other Costa, this one has great coffees, and good selection of sandwiches and cakes.<br>The layout and seating area is particularly bright and spacious, this is clearly a brand new Costa branch.

text: Sadly, I have to give a bad report. My friend and I were really excited to eat at the Las Vegas location. We had a waitperson who seemed to know what she was doing however it turns out she just made up answers about the food as she went along. I am vegetarian, which is why we picked the restaurant (because there were many vegetable options) and I told the waiter this to be sure I wasn&#39;t ordering vegetable dishes that were made with sauces or ingredients that were meat based. I ended up with a broccoli dish from the vegetable menu made with chicken powder in the sauce (I only know this because I found rouge chicken pieces in it from being cooked in a wok that was used to cook another dish beforehand and not cleaned in between). The waitperson was nowhere to be found to fix the issue so basically my friend was done eating and I still didn&#39;t have anything to eat. We ended up leaving due to my upset stomach since I had eaten some of the broccoli before realizing it was made with chicken (I was assured the sauce was vegetarian when ordering). Be VERY careful at this restaurant if you have any food allergies or diet preferences because the wait staff appears to not be educated about the food. Thank goodness I didn&#39;t have a shellfish allergy and ended up with a dish made with shellfish.

text: We stopped by for a late lunch after reading reviews to avoid the lunch crowd. Food was delicious and served quickly. Hainanese boiled chicken rice was well worth the recommendation to visit and all our other dishes (sizzling beef plates and seafood) we delicious as well. Reasonably priced and local charm this was a great place to eat!

text: A friend who is a local resident took me here and it was one of my favorite meals in Singapore. The Hainanese style chicken rice was the centerpiece of our amazing and affordable meal. Very informal place with friendly staff. If in doubt ask for suggestions and go with it. We did and loved it. Be adventurous if this all seems new to you. So glad a friend took me here and did all the hard work!

text: An excellent meal! A Singapore friend suggested that we eat here. There is no air conditioning (a few ceiling fans around the large seating area) and they do not accept credit cards. It appeared that we were the only Americans in the restaurant at the time. The chicken and rice was outstanding! We ordered a whole chicken, half boiled and half roasted. Both types of chicken were moist and tasty. The rice was also delicious. We also shared a pork chop which was outstanding. The restaurant is a short walk from many hotels in the area. The prices were very reasonable.

text: I&#39;ve been here several times over the past decade yet I&#39;ve never had the Hainanese pork chop. Big mistake! It was so tasty we ordered a second serving! <br><br>Besides the pork chop, we also had the chicken rice, eggplant with salted fish, kailan and hei zhor (minced meat roll). They were good but not outstanding to specially return. <br><br>The bill came to about $50 for 4 persons.

The chicken rice is very good, maybe comparable to Tian Tian. We had 1.5 chicken, a fishhead claypot, tofu claypot, pork chop, kangkong, sweet potato leaves. Very satisfied group of 13 people.<br><br>The portion is decent, the service is quick. The servers is the usual coffeeshop standards but they serve good food at great value.

text: This seems like a popular place and got good ratings so we brought our visitor here.  The chicken is pretty good, but I also can&#39;t say it&#39;s a lot better than any of the other equally well known chicken rice places.  Personally I prefer the chicken rice at Tian Tian or Boon Tong Kee but I have not tried the roast chicken though so perhaps that&#39;s better?<br><br>One of their signature dishes is the Hainanese pork chop but I found that to be just ok - the meat is a bit dry and I prefer it to be thicker and more succulent.  Other dishes like stir fried kangkung are ok but nothing special.  Prices are pretty cheap so definitely a good value for money.

text: Among all the stalls that I have tried, this is the best due to the soft fragrant rice, the chilli and the tenderness of chicken.  The portion is big. Generous spring onions on the chicken soup too. S$4 for a set.

Came all the way for the chicken rice and mutton soup but the mutton soup was already sold out. First time here and it was really one of the best chicken rice I&#39;ve had. Would definitely come back!!

text: Chin Chin Eating House has been my go-to place for fast and convenient zichar and chicken rice since young. This place is what a zichar place is like - hot, crowded, noisy and big tables with lazy susans in their middle. A typical local eatery with no airs about it and where people can just come and have a good meal at any time of the day.<br><br>Other than the chicken rice and chicken that are must-trys, I will recommend their pork chop and chap chye. <br><br>If you are a tourist and want to try local food, get out of Raffles Hotel and walk one street down to Chin Chin Eating House!

Came all the way for the chicken rice and mutton soup but the mutton soup was already sold out. First time here and it was really one of the best chicken rice I&#39;ve had. Would definitely come back!!

text: Tried this place several months ago and made a point of returning because it was so good. Not sure why chicken rice isn&#39;t on their (rather extensive) menu, but that&#39;s the dish to get. Perfect tenderness and flavor, a great broth to accompany it, and the chili/ginger are so good that I get an upset stomach every time (in the best way possible - watch your spice levels, people). Right up there with Tian Tian at Maxwell.

text: Sadly, I have to give a bad report. My friend and I were really excited to eat at the Las Vegas location. We had a waitperson who seemed to know what she was doing however it turns out she just made up answers about the food as she went along. I am vegetarian, which is why we picked the restaurant (because there were many vegetable options) and I told the waiter this to be sure I wasn&#39;t ordering vegetable dishes that were made with sauces or ingredients that were meat based. I ended up with a broccoli dish from the vegetable menu made with chicken powder in the sauce (I only know this because I found rouge chicken pieces in it from being cooked in a wok that was used to cook another dish beforehand and not cleaned in between). The waitperson was nowhere to be found to fix the issue so basically my friend was done eating and I still didn&#39;t have anything to eat. We ended up leaving due to my upset stomach since I had eaten some of the broccoli before realizing it was made with chicken (I was assured the sauce was vegetarian when ordering). Be VERY careful at this restaurant if you have any food allergies or diet preferences because the wait staff appears to not be educated about the food. Thank goodness I didn&#39;t have a shellfish allergy and ended up with a dish made with shellfish.

text: OK food. Terrible service. No one could speak Engilsh, the wait staff ignored people they thought couldn&#39;t speak Chinese. Never going again.

Purvis street used to house many European families which had Hainanese chefs working for them so I&#39;m not surprised that it is a known haunt for the best Hainanese food in town.<br><br>Get the Hainanese pork chops - sweet ketchup sauce drenching crispy pork cutlet is the ultimate comfort food that reminds one of childhood meals by the grandmother. I even like that crinkle-cut fries are stir-fried into the dish too. Super old school!<br><br>I&#39;ve yet to try more Hainanese dishes from here but it is a safe bet if you&#39;re looking to go good old traditional!

Along the stretch of shophouse restaurants at Purvis Street, this stall has old chicken rice seller Yet Con Restaurant to compete with, but Chin Chin Eating House has nothing to worry about. In a traditional local coffee shop setting, Chin Chin Eating House sure looks like it goes way back. <br><br>Studying in a nearby school, Chin Chin is an eating haunt for my friends and I. The dishes that we regularly order include chicken rice, Hainanese pork chops, Hainanese chap chye and claypot beancurd. The chicken rice has an authentic taste to it, and the chicken is blanched in cold water after cooking, making the skin smooth and the texture of the meat tender. Afterwhich, the chicken is served in a flavorful and aromatic sauce. The Hainanese pork chops here are passable but if you want a better version, try the one at Yet Con just across the street.<br><br>My favorite dish at Chin Chin has to be the Chap Chye. The vegetables are fresh and crunchy and the sauce is the deal breaker. The sauce has a special oomph to it, which is provided by the dried cuttlefish strips I guess.

text: The Gallery Cafe at Marina Barrage is a perfect end to an informative tour of the facility. Being at the second floor, it provides a good indoor view of the reservoir and everything that runs the barrage.<br><br>As spacious as the property, its high ceilings provided an impression of a much bigger place, when actually, its only a few-just check how many seats there are. Speaking of seats, my friend and I had a hard time moving them. Define workout? But nonetheless, those seats are quite a steal.<br><br>We each had a slice of tiramisu cake and sampled their Barrage Fresh Burt (i.e green apple, calamansi, and sour plum) which all three flavours complemented each others acidity very well, hence resulting into a refreshing drink and a relaxing after-tour.<br><br>The place is perfect for an afternoon hangout, and I heard that its way better at night, guess I should check that one out as well.

text: I can&#39;t believe it took me over 5 years to finally try this place. My colleagues have been recommending it but every time we were there it was either too crowded (and we didn&#39;t want to wait) or they were not ready. I believe they are ready to serve at 12pm or at least for the claypot dishes. <br><br>My colleagues like the claypot rice. <br><br>So I finally tried it after I read about the salted egg yolk pork ribs rice. There was a line and it was a 15 minutes wait for just two of us. <br><br>The queue system: Inform the staff how many are in your party, you will be given a menu to browse. Place your order and wait. When a table is available, they will signal you over. So it is based on # of people in your group (all must be present before being seated) and the # of seats are freed up. So don&#39;t be surprised if a party of two who is behind you (party of 4 or more) gets seated first because only a 2-seater is available. It is communal style with a few rows of combined tables. This is also a place to eat and go so that others can take your spot.<br><br>The salted egg yolk pork rib rice was good but I was not very wowed by it. Maybe the sauce was a bit weak that day. The claypot chicken rice was excellent. Nicely charred rice which was doused with dark soy sauce, none of those white rice with drizzles of sauce over. The aroma of the sizzling rice and meat was mouth watering. The pot of rice included tender pieces of chicken, some slices of lup cheong (chinese sausage) and bits of salted fish. I found my favorite place for claypot rice now.

text: i walk by this place all the time and never once did i pay attention to it because it&#39;s always packed with people. Today, however my friend was like &#34;we must eat here!&#34; Amazingly despite the crowd, we got seated within 3 minutes upon arrival. i didn&#39;t even get to see the menu. I was told what the signature dish was by my friend, then the auntie/server pointed at the girl next to me who has that dish and the ordering was finished with a nod of agreement between the 3 of us; it almost felt like i was finally let into a secret cult who&#39;s membership everyone coveted.<br><br>so what is the signature dish? It&#39;s deep fried pork rib slices covered in salted egg yolk sauce on a piece of lettuce with a portion of rice. it was AMMMMaaAZZzzing! if you like salted egg crabs, you&#39;ll like this one for sure. we devoured our meal in 15 mins and gave our table to the hungry ones in waiting.

text: head to the 5th floor at far east plaza at lunchtime and you&#39;ll probably notice a long line forming outside this place. most people are queuing for the zi char dishes, but there&#39;s a separate line for the salted egg yolk pork ribs. you probably can&#39;t go wrong with any of the other dishes (i hear the popcorn chicken is great) but definitely try out the pork ribs. for $6, you&#39;ll get a plate of rice and these delectable pieces of fried pork smothered in a slightly sweet yet savory salted egg yolk sauce. you can even add on stuff - i paid $1.50 more for some greens. it&#39;s not the cheapest (nor healthiest) hawker center dish but it&#39;s really good. lines can get really long, so be prepared to wait.

How cute is this?', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'How cute is this?'}]
text: LOL at Nik T. calling me out on the possibility that I&#39;ll never write a review for this place! Well, I&#39;ve now been called out to the Yelp Review Plate, so I will step up and give my 2 cents. <br><br>Nik introduced me to this place, and the first time I went I only had coffee. After skimming their menu, I liked their offerings: for main courses, they have fish and chips, sausage and chips, and pastas. They offer some salads, soups, fruity drinks, and a good amount of dessert as well. I knew I&#39;d have to come back again to give the food a try.<br><br>I&#39;m a fan of their pasta bolognese. If I&#39;m too lazy to cook my own version (which I do every now and then) this is a nice replacement. My husband ordered one of their seafood pastas in a light sauce, and while good, they shower it with peppers so it makes it very spicy! I&#39;m pretty sure they mention this on the menu, though.<br><br>I&#39;ve also had the pleasure of trying their fish and chips. I know Nik ordered this last time, but when I ordered it I forgot how big the portion size was! The fillet was probably 8 inches long, and although I was hungry, I couldn&#39;t finish it all.<br><br>I really like their set lunch/dinner deals, which are on the weekdays. It comes with a soup and a flavored drink, and the price is very reasonable.<br><br>Professor Brawn&#39;s prides themselves on being a restaurant that&#39;s a social enterprise. Their mission is to give employment opportunities to anyone regardless of socio-economic status and disabilities. Although I appreciate this gesture, I have mixed feelings about it. Being from the US, I was raised on the idea that ALL employers are not allowed to discriminate against potential hiring candidates regardless of gender, race, religion, etc. I guess this is something I&#39;ve taken for granted, and at times I feel a bit saddened that this isn&#39;t the case everywhere else. But of course, this discussion is neither here nor there.<br><br>Bottom line: nice space, great food at affordable prices, and for a good cause. If Novena is out of the way for you, visit their other outlet at Boat Quay!

text: I was really interested in this local cafe&#39;s concept of social entrepreneurship. It was a refreshing change from the usual chain food places. The setting in the Novena branch was cozy and inviting. Unfortunately, the food was really not up to standard and I&#39;m hoping that it&#39;s because we made the wrong orders as I would like to support such ventures. Please avoid the chicken with truffle sauce and squid ink pasta.

text: in the rat race of a place that is singapore, it is inevitable that many who fail to keep up has fallen behind.<br>job opportunities like those created by professor brawn cafe(a social enterprise) must thus be lauded.<br><br>if you have the chance to visit them, you will witness for yourself an equal opportunity employer that does not discriminate in age, ability nor socio-economic background.<br><br>when you do visit them, a bright and cheery place awaits you.<br>the staff do make great effort to enhance your dining experience with them.<br>i found myself a little more patient and specific in my requests when ordering.<br><br>they have various sets which are always a value for money.<br>you get a drink, soup of the day and a main for about $15.90.<br>today the choice was a creamy carrot soup which wasn&#39;t too carroty.<br>orange juice was a generous size.<br>as for the fish and chips, it was most likely a frozen dory fillet, breaded and well fried, served with fries, mesclun salad and a tartare sauce.<br><br>and if you order an ala carte item and use your UOB credit card to pay, you will score yourself a free ice cream!<br>that decadent chocolate scoop makes it worth your while just to get a UOB credit card!!!<br><br>an ala carte order of mushroom soup($6.90) is way big and comes with foccacia.<br>for dainty eaters, this will be a meal in itself. <br><br>as for the carb addicts, the spaghetti bolognese($13.90) is decently tasty and al dente.<br><br>and if you so decide to enjoy a cuppa, a cappuccino here will only set you back just $4.20.<br>as for how that compares with other cappuccinos, please refer to michelle m&#39;s review which she has yet to, or may never, write!:)<br><br>who can say no to supporting a good cause while still doing what you like to do?<br>i can&#39;t!

Bless the benevolent geniuses at Fairprice.  I love having a 24 hour grocery store in the neighborhood!<br><br>Probably my favorite aspect is never running into a ramen shortage after a night on the town.  Aside from that, it is certainly handy to have an entire &#34;kitchen stadium&#39;s&#34; worth of ingredients available anytime a food network marathon strikes my inner chef.<br><br>Beyond the accessibility, the store features lower prices when compared to Cold Storage and Giant, which is always a nice benefit!<br><br>PARTING THOUGHT: Lately, I&#39;ve been working my way through the exotic sauces in the condiments section!  I have amassed quite a collection for my culinary experiments!

Do Singaporeans use garbage bags?  Nope, because I must have looked around Fair Price for a good 18 minutes listening to country music trying to find them.  Then it dawned on me, probably not.  Duh. <br><br>I have a love hate relationship with this store.  It&#39;s cheap, but a lot of the stuff I want, they don&#39;t carry.  (ground beef, any beef in general unless it&#39;s hidden under all the fish stuff) and other name brand stuff I like.  Spoiled princess, I know.  <br><br>But, they do have a shit ton of Ramen, and some good spice action happening.  Their produce is pretty darn good, and CHEAAAAAAAPPPPP.  They also have lots of coffee selection, and some good cleaning product stuff.  but their frozen food section could use an over haul, and it still freaks me out to have eggs non refrigerated but what do I know?  <br><br>All in all, it&#39;s 24 hours, it&#39;s cheap, just don&#39;t come on the weekends, it&#39;s bananas.

text: I love that it&#39;s open 24 hours here. It has everything you need (minus cold beer) and conveniently located.<br><br>I like that they have a Fair Price radio station and more times than not, they are playing &#34;Kiss Me&#34; by Sixpence None the Richer. I&#39;m convinced Singapore is in love with this song as it has an inordinate amount of airtime at very random places I frequent.<br><br>It&#39;s a catchy tune. I digress. Squirrel!

Reasonably priced and not too large food and household items supermarket steps away from the Tanjong Pagar MRT station. Good quality and also a small range of organic food and European food - due to the many expats who shop here - next to the Chinese who are certainly by large the majority here, which you can also tell from e.g. the vegetables on offer.
If I am not wrong, the third branch that has opened in ten min walk of each other.<br><br>A much bigger space than the other two located along Scotts road.
